<HEADLINE> EU Forecasts Positive Economic Picture </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, October 14 (Xinhua) -- The European Commission, the
European Union (EU)'s executive body, said today that Europe's
economic recovery is well established, with its economic growth
gaining speed.
</P>
<P>
The autumn economic forecasts published by the EC said the
situation is in line with the trend implied in the Commission
services' spring forecasts.
</P>
<P>
The figures published today forecast average gross domestic
product (GDP) growth in the EU to strengthen progressively from
1.8 percent in 1996 to 2.6 percent in 1997, and to 3.0 percent in
1998.
</P>
<P>
Compared with the spring forecasts published in April, the
figures represent an upward revision of 0.2 percent of GDP in both
1997 and 1998.
</P>
<P>
The same trend is observed at the level of most individual
member states. The EU growth is expected to accelerate further to
3.1 percent in 1999, on the assumption of unchanged economic
policies.
</P>
<P>
The report says member states are making good progress with
economic convergence required for participation in the EMU
(Economic and Monetary Union).
</P>
<P>
Inflation is expected to remain at historically low levels --
the EU average is expected to be 2.1 percent in 1997 and 2.2
percent in 1998, apparently putting 14 member countries on track
to respect the Treaty criterion for inflation in 1997.
</P>
<P>
This has confirmed the Commission's view that a majority of
member states should be capable of meeting the necessary
conditions to participate in the euro from January 1, 1999.
</P>
<P>
The report also indicates positive improvements in the
employment situation in Europe, but says the member states need to
take further structural measures to ensure more significant
reductions in the levels of employment. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
