<BODY>
<HEADLINE> GCC to Finish Commodity Classification </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUWAIT CITY, October 14 (Xinhua) -- A Gulf Cooperation Council
(GCC) committee met today in Saudi capital Riyadh to finalize the
classification of commodities as part of an effort to unify
tariffs among its member nations.
</P>
<P>
A statement issued by the GCC said the customs committee is
working on the remaining 36 commodities prior to the GCC summit
scheduled for December in Kuwait, Kuwait News Agency reported.
</P>
<P>
Up to 1,240 commodities had been categorized in accordance with
an internationally accepted classification list in the previous
meeting of the committee.
</P>
<P>
The GCC summit is expected to give the final say on the
unification of tariffs, according to the statement.
</P>
<P>
The commodities fell into three categories - goods exempted
from tariffs, basic goods to be levied for a tariff of 4 to 12
percent, and other goods without a set tariff limit.
</P>
<P>
Abdallah Al-Khlaifi, GCC's assistant secretary general for
economic affairs, expressed optimism Monday that the organization
would soon finish the work of unifying tariffs, which at present
range from 4 to 25 percent in different countries.
</P>
<P>
If successful, the unification of tariffs among GCC member
nations would prove be a major step toward the proposed formation
of an Arab common market in the future.
</P>
<P>
The GCC, a political and economic organization founded in 1981,
consists of six Arab countries of Saudi Arabia, Kuwait, the United
Arab Emirates, Oman, Qatar and Bahrain. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
