<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Seoul Unveils Investment Plan in DPRK </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SEOUL, October 14 (Xinhua) -- The South Korean government today
permitted some of its companies to do business with the Democratic
People's Republic of Korea (DPRK).
</P>
<P>
The state-invested Korea Land Corporation (KOLAND) and four
other firms were endorsed to do business in the DPRK's
Rajin-Sonbong Free Economic Trade Zone.
</P>
<P>
The KOLAND, with Pyongyang's Committee for Promotion of
External Economic Cooperation as its partner, is planning to build
a 1,320,000 square meters industrial park in the zone through
direct investment, the first investment in the DPRK by Seoul.
</P>
<P>
It hopes to expand the construction of the industrial park, the
first of its kind in the zone, to 6.6 million square meters by the
year 2000, the KOLAND said.
</P>
<P>
"We hope to take inter-Korean economic cooperation into a
higher gear," said Cho Kun-shik, director-general of the
Intra-Korean Interchange and Cooperation Bureau at the Ministry of
National Unification.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the four other companies are not hesitating in
investing in the zone.
</P>
<P>
Daesang Super Express Incorporation is expected to pour 4.2
million U.S. dollars into a logistics center.
</P>
<P>
Samchuly Bicycle Industrial Company and LG Business will
jointly invest with the DPRK's Kwangmyonsong General Trading
Corporation in an 8-million-dollar bicycle factory.
</P>
<P>
Taeyong Fisheries and LG Business, together with
Kwangmyongsong, will invest two million dollars in a scallop farm
in either Wonsan or Rajin-Sonbong. 
</P>
</TEXT>
