<HEADLINE> German 1998 Economic Growth Set for 3 Percent </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, October 14 (Xinhua) -- Germany's gross domestic product
(GDP) will increase by 2.5 percent this year and the growth will
rise to 3 percent next year, a leading German economic institute
predicted today.
</P>
<P>
In its latest economic report released today, the Cologne-based
Institute for German Economy said about 130,000 jobs will be
created in western Germany in 1998 while some 30,000 jobs will be
lost in the eastern half of the country.
</P>
<P>
This will bring some relief to the country's record high
unemployment, which stood at nearly 4.5 million in September, the
report said.
</P>
<P>
The current economic upswing could almost solely be attributed
to booming exports, which were expected to expand by 9 percent
this year, the report noted.
</P>
<P>
A quick solution to the current standstill in structural
reforms would be a key remedy to revive the weak domestic demand,
the report added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
