<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Papon Trial Revives Memory of 1961 Massacre of Algerians </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, October 14 (Xinhua) -- The proceeding trial of former
Vichy official Maurice Papon for crimes against humanity has
revived memories of another distinctly different atrocity
connected with Papon -- the 1961 massacre of Algerians by Paris
police.
</P>
<P>
Papon is being tried for his role as a Vichy official in the
deportation of 1,690 Jews from southwest France to Nazi death
camps, from 1942 to 1944.
</P>
<P>
He was Paris police chief when the massacre took place on
October 17, 1961, a few months before the end of the 1954-1962
Algerian War.
</P>
<P>
The French civil group, Movement Against Racism, Anti-Semitism
and for Peace (MRAP), is organizing a series of actions to
memorize the victims of the 1961 massacre, including a press
conference on Friday in Bordeaux where Papon is standing trial.
</P>
<P>
A demonstration will be held in Paris on Friday at the Pont
Saint-Michel by the Seine River, which was the scene of the
massacre.
</P>
<P>
French police brutally suppressed a peaceful demonstration by
Algerians in Paris, who defied a curfew imposed on them on October
17, 1961. The government said three were killed and 64 injured in
the suppression, but the actual number of victims stood at around
200.
</P>
<P>
Most of the victims were drowned after being thrown into the
Seine, crushed by subway trains after being pushed onto the tracks
by police, beaten to death or shot.
</P>
<P>
"Anti-Semitism led to the crimes of the Vichy: anti-Algerian
racism allowed the massacre of October 17, 1961," said the MRAP in
a communique today. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
