<DOCNO> XIE19971015.0012 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Italian President Seeks Government Confidence Vote </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ROME, October 14 (Xinhua) -- Italian President Oscar Luigi
Scalfaro sent the government back to parliament today for a
confidence vote after the caretaker government and the Communist
Refoundation party reached a compromise on the 1998 draft budget.
</P>
<P>
The announcement from the president's office came following a
deal between the government and the hard-left party on a program
to ensure Italy's entry into the single currency union in 1999.
</P>
<P>
Considering it was necessary to resume the work of both
government and parliament immediately, Scalfaro rejected Prime
Minister Romano Prodi's resignation and told him to go before the
parliament "as soon as possible."
</P>
<P>
Prodi tendered his resignation to the president last Thursday
after finding it was not possible for his draft budget for 1998 to
be passed by parliament without the support of the communist
deputies.
</P>
<P>
The Communist Refoundation party, holding the balance of power
in the lower house of parliament, complained that the budget had
too many deep cuts in social and welfare spending and few measures
to stimulate employment, and vowed to back away from it.
</P>
<P>
The budget would help the country become one of the charter
members of the European economic and monetary union. 
</P>
</TEXT>
