<DOCNO> XIE19971015.0014 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Common-law Couples More Common in Canada </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OTTAWA, October 14 (Xinhua) -- Marriage has lost its appeal and
common-law is becoming increasingly popular in Canada, Statistics
Canada reported today.
</P>
<P>
"Of all family structures, growth was strongest among
common-law couple families," the federal statistics agency said in
its third release today about the 1996 census.
</P>
<P>
In 1996, common-law couple unions rose 28 percent from that of
1991. And one couple in seven in the country was living by
common-law, compared to about one in nine in 1991.
</P>
<P>
Common-law families were by far the most frequent in Quebec
province, where one couple in four lived common law.
</P>
<P>
While common-law unions had traditionally been more prevalent
among people in their early 20s, they have become more popular
among older individuals as well.
</P>
<P>
In the meantime, marriage appears to be a fragile bond for more
and more individuals.
</P>
<P>
In 1996, there were over 1.6 million people who said they were
divorced, a 28 percent increase from 1991. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
