<DOCNO> XIE19971015.0015 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Zimbabwe's Inflation Drops Sharply in September </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, October 14 (Xinhua) -- Zimbabwe's year-on-year
inflation was pegged at 14.4 percent in September, in a drop that
came as a surprise to many in the market who had expected the
rate to be higher, the Zimbabwe News Agency reported today.
</P>
<P>
The rate was 3.6 percent lower than August figure of 18
percent and came against the backdrop of warnings of severe
underlying inflationary pressures by the Reserve Bank of Zimbabwe
(RBZ) during the month.
</P>
<P>
While details about the cause for the decline were not
available, most market analysts were sceptical about the
authenticity of the figures produced by the central statistical
office.
</P>
<P>
President of Zimbabwe Economics Society Kenias Mafukidze
described the latest set of figures as "unbelievable", especially
following the recent statement by RBZ governor Leonard Tsumba who
warned that inflation could be as high as 21 percent by the year
end.
</P>
<P>
Financing of the 1997/98 budget deficit, recent wage and
salary settlements and a spate of administered price increases
during the past few months had been expected to exert pressure on
inflation.
</P>
<P>
The budget deficit, which was last year 7.1 percent of gross
domestic product, is this year expected to be over 12 percent as
the impact of the government's decision to pay former freedom
fighters over five billion Zimbabwe dollars (400 million U.S.
dollars) in gratuities and pensions starts to trickle into the
economy. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
