<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Zimbabwe's New Economic Reforms About to Take </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, October 14 (Xinhua) -- The Zimbabwean government plans
to present the second phase of the economic reform program to
cabinet before the end of October, Finance Minister Herbert
Murerwa told parliament today.
</P>
<P>
He said the Zimbabwean Program for Economic and Social
Transformation (ZIMPREST), a home grown product aimed at
indigenising the economy through economic empowerment, was on the
verge of taking off.
</P>
<P>
Replying to points raised during debate on the presidential
speech, Murerwa said finance ministry officials were putting
finishing touches to the document on the ZIMPREST which would
target alleviation of poverty and reduction of rampant
unemployment.
</P>
<P>
"It is my intention to bring the ZIMPREST document to
parliament as soon as it is brought before cabinet. It is my
intention to place it before cabinet in the next week or two," he
added.
</P>
<P>
Murerwa also commented on lessons learnt from the first phase
of the economic structural adjustment program (ESAP one)
(1991-95), saying reform program must embody the aspirations of
the people and must resolve the imperatives of giving the
majority of the people a meaningful stake in the economy of
Zimbabwe.
</P>
<P>
The reform program must be pursued as a coordinated program
for the whole of government and the community.
</P>
<P>
The reform program, he added, should be an integrated package,
and any seepage in one direction would have profound
repercussions in the other areas. 
</P>
</TEXT>
