<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> S. Africa's Production Price Index Falls in </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, October 14 (Xinhua) -- South Africa's annual
production price index (PPI) for August fell to 5.9 percent --
the lowest since May 1996 when it was 5.8 percent, Central
Statistics Services (CSS) figures show.
</P>
<P>
The monthly increase in this index also slowed down to 0.1
percent compared with 0.2 percent in July, South African Press
Association quoted CSS as saying.
</P>
<P>
The annual rate of increase in the PPI for locally produced
commodities in August was 6.5 percent, 1.0 percentage point lower
than July. From July to August, this index increased by 0.4
percent, while the seasonally adjusted index went up by 0.2
percent.
</P>
<P>
The PPI for imported commodities reflected an annual increase
of 2.8 percent in August, 1.1 percentage point lower than the
corresponding annual rate of 3.9 percent in July and the lowest
since March 1994, when it was also 2.8 percent.
</P>
<P>
From July to August, this index declined mainly due to a
decrease of 9.1 percent in the price of imported crude petroleum,
the report said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
