<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Roundup: Sanctions Should be Used Sparingly </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, October 14 (Xinhua) -- As the Sixth Committee
(The Legal) continued its discussion on the implementation of
Security Council sanctions, many representatives expressed the
views that sanctions should only be used as a last resort when all
other means of settling disputes had been exhausted.
</P>
<P>
Addressing the sixth Committee, Sudanese representative Omer
Dahab Fadol said sanctions must be resorted to as a last measure
and in exceptional instance, after all means of peaceful
settlement of disputes had been exhausted. It must "be limited in
time and must not be deformed by dualism and selectivity".
</P>
<P>
The representative said that his country supported the view
that the adoption of sanctions should not be approached from
politically or ideologically partial or emotional positions.
</P>
<P>
He said a clear criteria should be employed for determining
the use of such measures. Concerned states should be able to
participate in the informal discussion of the Security Council
on the question of sanctions.
</P>
<P>
Also speaking at the Sixth Committee, Chinese representative
Gao Feng said China never supported the use of sanctions as the
primary means to settle international disputes. China was
concerned that it was mainly developing countries which suffered
from the effects of sanctions.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese representative said that the international
community should show understanding of the legitimate demands of
the states affected by the implementation of sanctions and give
them practical support.
</P>
<P>
He said the problem could be resolved by reducing sanctions
to a minimum and limiting their duration, if they had to be
imposed. He called for the establishment of a mechanism for
consultations between the affected third states and the Security
Council.
</P>
<P>
He said China supported the the proposal by Sierra Leone on the
establishment of a dispute prevention and a early settlement
service. Such a body would be conducive to elimitating and
reducing the further expansion of disputes and would also
eliminate or reduce the possibility of large-scale United Nations
action, including imposition of sanctions.
</P>
<P>
Cuban representative Caridad Yamira Cueto Milian said that
there was widespread demand from developing countries that the
United Nations address the problem of the effects of sanctions
on third states. The issue should continue to be the priority
for the special Committee on the Charter.
</P>
<P>
she said that the responsibility of the Security Council, as
the body that imposed sanctions, could not be diluted, and it
should assume the responsibility of examining and repairing the
consequences of sanctions.
</P>
<P>
Egyptian representative Nabail A. Elaraby said his country
welcomed the the report by the UN secretary-General on the
effects of sanctions on third states. Broader freedom should be
given to the sanctions Committee to deal directly with
applications for relief from the affected third states.
Countries which would be affected by the imposition of the
sanctions should be allowed to participate, without a vote, in
informal discussions of the Security council on the subject.
</P>
<P>
He said the issue should be dealt with comprehensively. The
Security Council should have a time-frame for imposing sanctions
to avoid unnecessary suffering by vulnerable groups in the
affected third countries. The objective of the sanctions should
be clearly defined.
</P>
<P>
He said his country welcomed Russia'proposals on the effects of
sanctions on third countries which should be considered. It also
supported the principles proposed by Russia on peacekeeping
operation, as well as the proposals of Sierra Leone on the
establishment of a dispute prevention and the early settlement
service. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
