<HEADLINE> Ethiopia Dispatches 13 Teams to Assess Crop </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ADDIS ABABA, October 14 (Xinhua) -- The disaster prevention
and preparedness commission of Ethiopia announced today that 13
teams have been dispatched to assess the damage made on standing
crops across the country because of shortage of rainfall during
the last rainy season.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at a press conference here, officials from the
commission said the teams will also review the situation of food
shortage and the number of drought victims in different regions.
</P>
<P>
The teams drawn from federal and regional governments as well
as donors are expected to disclose the information at the end of
October, the officials said.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, officials of the commission said of the 400,000
metric tonnes of food the country needs for 1997, 185,000 metric
tonnes of food has already been pledged by donors.
</P>
<P>
They said of the stated amount of food pledged, the commission
has already received 103,000 metric tonnes.
</P>
<P>
The official said there are 3.4 million drought affected
people across the country, adding that the number of drought
victims in the country may rise following the disclosure of the
information by the teams. 
</P>
