<HEADLINE> Canadian FM Assails U.S. Congress </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OTTAWA, October 14 (Xinhua) -- Canadian Foreign Affairs
Minister Lloyd Axworthy has assailed the U.S. Congress for its
increasingly isolationism.
</P>
<P>
He also warned that the congress' go-it-alone mentality
threatens international relations, reports said today.
</P>
<P>
Axworthy told a meeting on Canada-U.S. relations here Monday
that new demands in the new world order require co-operation among
countries worldwide.
</P>
<P>
And Canada and the U.S. should be working closely on issues
ranging from human rights to the environment, he said.
</P>
<P>
"But one thing gets in the way of that kind of relationship,
and that is what I see is an increasingly isolationist trend
taking place in the U.S. Congress," the minister said.
</P>
<P>
The congress "does not recognize this increasing need to work
in partnership according to a broad-based international set of
rules," he noted.
</P>
<P>
It seems to be working in the opposite direction where "it
tends more and more to want to go it alone."
</P>
<P>
He took the instances of Cuba and its refusal to pay
long-accumulated dues to the United Nations.
</P>
<P>
Any powerful country resorting to unilaterally changing
international law introduces a "virus" that erodes the established
structure, he said.
</P>
<P>
Long-time convergence in Canadian and U.S. policy should not
mean that the two countries will continue to agree on everything
in a world where new issues are emerging.
</P>
<P>
"Now we have to look at what happens when there is far more
diversity in the system and far more opportunities for niche
diplomacy.
</P>
<P>
"We understand there has to be a degree of accommodation,
understanding, and at times areas where we can agree to disagree,"
he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
