<HEADLINE> 22 PKK Rebels Killed in Southeastern Turkey </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA, October 14 (Xinhua) -- Twenty-two militants of the
outlawed Kurdish Workers' Party (PKK) were killed today by Turkish
government troops in southeastern Turkey, the semi-official
Anatolia News Agency said.
</P>
<P>
A statement issued by the Emergency Regional Governor's Office
said these rebels were wiped out in operations launched in
retaliation for their attack on a military vehicle of the
government troops on Monday.
</P>
<P>
Ten soldiers of the government troops were killed in that
ambush, it said.
</P>
<P>
Last Saturday, a group of PKK militants reportedly attacked a
military post in northern Black Sea town of Giresun, killing nine
soldiers.
</P>
<P>
The PKK rebels, who have been fighting a separatist war in
southeastern Turkey since 1984, are trying to build new bases in
the Black Sea region after Ankara sent troops into northern Iraq
to sweep their camps there, according to local reports.
</P>
<P>
Late last month, around 15,000 Turkish troops, backed by jets
and artillery fire, crossed into northern Iraq, an area beyond
control of Baghdad since the 1991 Gulf War, in a bid to eradicate
PKK militants.
</P>
<P>
A total of 837 PKK rebels were killed in the operations, which
triggered strong protests from Iran and some Arab countries.
Turkey announced on Monday that it had started to withdraw some of
its troops from northern Iraq.
</P>
<P>
More than 27,000 soldiers, civilians and anti-government
militants have been killed in armed conflicts between the
government troops and the PKK over the past 13 years. 
</P>
</TEXT>
