<BODY>
<HEADLINE> UNCTAD to Play Greater Role in Globalization, Says </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GENEVA, October 14 (Xinhua) -- UNCTAD Secretary-General Rubens
Ricupero has stated that the phenomena of globalization and
liberalization have reinforced the utility of UNCTAD, the United
Nations Conference on Trade and Development.
</P>
<P>
Ricupero was speaking at the opening session of the annual
meeting of the Trade and Development Board (TDB), UNCTAD's highest
executive body between the quadrennial ministerial conferences.
</P>
<P>
During the session on October 13-24, delegates from many of
UNCTAD's 188 members will focus their discussions on the broad
issues of economic interdependence and globalization, and their
impact on developing countries, notably, their socio-economic
development and competitiveness, according to a UNCTAD press
release. The main specific agenda items relate to Africa and the
Least Developed Countries (LDCs).
</P>
<P>
"Greater international flows of goods, finance and investment
associated with globalization are not the only basis on which the
development process should be judged," Ricupero said. "The
ultimate objective of development policy is raising living
standards for everybody. measuring economic performance should
thus pay greater heed to growth and distribution than has so far
been the case."
</P>
<P>
"The business of UNCTAD is development. Not only for a few, but
for all men, and for man as a whole," Ricupero pointed out. "It
takes a multilateral body with a universal membership and a
mandate like ours, to examine the interdependent nature of complex
economic phenomena, to make sense of the confusion and propose
appropriate measures to policy-makers."
</P>
<P>
Ricupero expressed the hope that the TDB would make headway in
identifying policy considerations which would help policy-makers
everywhere to meet the challenge of making globalization
compatible with domestic social and political stability. UNCTAD's
message, he said, is that globalization carries the potential for
raising living standards worldwide, provided action is taken at
the global and national levels,, aimed at a more equal
distribution of its benefits. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
