<HEADLINE> Iraq Urges UN to Lift Sanctions </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BAGHDAD, October 14 (Xinhua) -- Iraq again called on the United
Nations Security Council to lift the seven-year-old sanctions
against it, Iraqi News Agency reported today.
</P>
<P>
The appeal came in a message sent by Iraqi Deputy Prime
Minister Tariq Aziz to the U.N. Security Council, according to the
agency.
</P>
<P>
Aziz said in his message that the U.N. Special Commission on
Iraq has adopted a prejudiced stance in its report about Iraq's
weapon programs submitted every six months to the U.N. Security
Council.
</P>
<P>
This has misled the Security Council in questioning Iraq's
capability to produce weapons of mass destruction, he said.
</P>
<P>
The U.N. commission, set up after the 1991 Gulf War in which
occupying Iraqi troops were driven out of Kuwait by allied forces,
is responsible for inspecting and destroying weapons of mass
destruction in Iraq.
</P>
<P>
Aziz said that more than six years have passed since the
commission started its work, but there is nothing to indicate when
it would announce that its duties are over.
</P>
<P>
He accused the commission of dragging on its work on purpose to
keep in place the economic sanctions, including the oil embargo,
the U.N. Security Council imposed on Iraq in 1990 after its troops
invaded Kuwait.
</P>
<P>
However, Aziz expressed Iraq's readiness to cooperate with the
U.N. Special Commission on outstanding problems between them and
to seek appropriate solutions. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
