<HEADLINE> Blair Names Top Policeman as Drugs Czar </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, October 14 (Xinhua) -- British Prime Minister Tony
Blair Tuesday appointed Northern England's West Yorkshire Chief
Constable Keith Hellawell as the country's first "Drugs Czar".
</P>
<P>
The 55-year-old top policeman will lead the fight against drug
abuse and co-ordinate efforts to tackle traffickers and addiction
problems.
</P>
<P>
Michael Trace, Director of the Rehabilitation for Addicted
Prisoners' Trust, was named as his deputy.
</P>
<P>
Announcing the move, the Prime Minister said that real progress
was needed to reduce drug misuse especially among the young.
</P>
<P>
Hellawell pledged to tackle "one of the biggest challenges
facing the country" and said that he hoped to be able "to make a
difference".
</P>
<P>
"I know about the pervasive and damaging effects drugs have on
our communities," Hellawell said.
</P>
<P>
He added that his first priority in the job would be to
"consult widely" so the best solutions could be found.
</P>
<P>
According to figures released by Britain's Home Office, the
number of people being treated for opiate or cocaine addiction
have risen 17 percent to more than 43,000 in the past year, and in
1996, 113,000 people were apprehended by police for drug-related
offences, up from 87,000 in 1994. 
</P>
