<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Greek Prime Minister Meets Visiting Cypriot President </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ATHENS, October 14 (Xinhua) -- Greek Prime Minister Costas
Simitis today met with visiting Cypriot President Glafcos Clerides
to discuss the long-protracted Cyprus problem.
</P>
<P>
Speaking to reporters after their talks, Simitis attributed the
failure of the meetings between the two communities in Cyprus to
the continued intransigence of the Turkish Cypriot side.
</P>
<P>
He stressed the need of realizing the two main goals of Greece
and the island republic, which were the resolution of the Cyprus
problem in accordance with U.N. resolutions and Cyprus' entry into
the European Union (EU).
</P>
<P>
The prime minister expressed the hope that "significant
developments" could be expected over the next few months,
especially with regard to Cyprus' accession negotiations with the
EU.
</P>
<P>
He warned that there would be difficulties if no progress was
made towards solving the Cyprus problem and the proposal by
Clerides for the demilitarization of the divide island was not
accepted.
</P>
<P>
Greece did not want tension or conflict with Turkey, he said,
adding that relations between the two countries could not be
normalized if there was no just and viable solution to the Cyprus
problem.
</P>
<P>
He said that it was impossible for Turkey to want to develop a
special relationship with the EU and not to recognize fundamental
rules of international law.
</P>
<P>
Simitis called on all countries that wanted peace and stability
in the region to back efforts being made within the framework of
the United Nations.
</P>
<P>
For his part, Clerides, who arrived here Monday evening,
thanked Athens for its support with regard to the Cyprus problem,
accession to the EU, demilitarization proposal and the effort to
strengthen Cyprus's defense capability.
</P>
<P>
He emphasized that Nicosia was obliged not only to continue
with the military exercises but also with arming itself.
</P>
<P>
Clerides hoped that substantial developments in the Cyprus
problem could be made after the Cypriot presidential elections
which will take place in February next year.
</P>
<P>
Cyprus has been divided since 1974 when Turkish troops invaded
and occupied the northern third of the island in the wake of a
pre- Athens coup.
</P>
<P>
Direct talks have been held over the past months between
Cypriot President Glafcos and Turkish Cypriot leader Rauf
Denktash, but no progress has been made so far. 
</P>
</TEXT>
