<BODY>
<HEADLINE> United States Dominates International Arms Trade </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, October 14 (Xinhua) -- The United States, the only
superpower in the world, remains the biggest international arms
trader in 1996, with its arms sales increasing from 1995's 14
billion to 17 billion US dollars, according to an authoritative
annual report.
</P>
<P>
The report named "The Military Balance", published today by
London's International Institute for Strategic Studies (IISS),
said: "The international arms trade grew by eight percent in 1996
in real terms from 36.9 billion to 39.9 billion dollars, following
a 13 percent increase in 1995."
</P>
<P>
The United States, the world's biggest arms exporter, exported
various arms worth 17 billion dollars last year for a 42.6 percent
global arms sales market share.
</P>
<P>
Britain and France, which were ranked the second and third
places respectively, recorded arms sales of 8.8 billion and 5.6
billion dollars in the same year.
</P>
<P>
On the main factors behind the big arms sales increases, the
report said:" the unpredictable tensions in North-east Asia and
the Middle East, favorable oil prices for the Gulf states and
sustained modernization demand in East Asia" have combined to help
achieve the arms trade record.
</P>
<P>
Speaking on future international arms trade tendency, IISS
Director John Chipman told reporters: "the extent of spending in
numerous Gulf countries is likely to decline as the cycle of big
purchases made after the Gulf War draws to a close."
</P>
<P>
"Over the coming years, it will be important to look closely at
how this years currency crisis in South east Asia and the
depressed economic climate in other parts of Asia affects arms
orders," he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
