<HEADLINE> China Attaches Importance to Work of Youth, Aging, </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, October 14 (xinhua) -- Chinese government had
always attached great importance to the work of the youth, aging
and disableed persons, and series of laws and policies in this
regards had been formulated and implemented, Chinese representative
Lin Sha said here today.
</P>
<P>
Addressing the Third Committee(Social, humanitarian and
Cultural) of the fifty-second session of the General Assembly, Lin
Sha said that the question relating to the youth, aging and
disabled persons constituted an important and integral part of the
work in the field of social development.
</P>
<P>
Lin Sha said that a total of 80 percent of youth, aging and
disabled persons lived in developing countries. Plagued by
poverty, backwardness and other factors, they were confronted with
a particularly difficult situation.
</P>
<P>
The representative said the United Nations should focus on
their needs, take practical and effective measures to promote
international cooperation and provide assistance and technical
services in particular, so that favorable conditions would be
created for the resolution of the difficulties and full
integration into society.
</P>
<P>
Lin Sha said the Chinese government and youth organizations, in
light of China's realities, had conducted a great variety of local
and national activities with an eye to the 21st century.
Impressive achievements had been registered in the development of
all types of education including that for youth in employment, in
the improvement of youth 's overall level of science and culture,
in the education of young peasant illiteracy and dissemination of
agricultural scientific and technical knowledge, as well as in the
enhancement of youth's professionalism and moral standards.
</P>
<P>
She said aging was a problem facing all mankind. China would
join the ranks of states with aging population by the year 2000
when the number of older people aged 60 and beyond that would
reach 130 million. The Chines government had taken notes of this
social problem affecting the overall situation.
</P>
<P>
She said that last year, measures were taken to strengthen
institutions for the aged, and the Law of the People's Republic of
China on the Protection of the Rights and interests of the Aged
was promulgated, thereby bringing work of older people into line
with the local and national plans for economic and social
development.
</P>
<P>
The representative said China had 60 million people with
disabilities. In order to safeguard their rights, improve their
plight and give play to their potential, China was implementing a
policy characterized by governmental leadership, social support
and participation by the disabled. A set of measures had been
carries out and noticeable results achieved.
</P>
<P>
She said the Chinese government, in response to the call for
the establishment of national coordinating bodies, set up in 1993
the State Council Coordinating Committee on Disability, followed
by the setting up of corresponding organs at local levels, thus
incorporating work of the disabled into the national development
plan.
</P>
<P>
She said the Chinese government and organizations for youth,
the aged and disabled persons had taken a active part in UN
exchanges in these areas in support of exchanges and cooperation
with various countries. China was earnestly implementing the world
Program of Action for Youth to the year 2000 and beyond through
cooperation with international organizations in participating in
or organizing world regional conferences.
</P>
<P>
She said in carrying out the World Program of Acton
concerning disabled persons, China took an active part in
activities for the United Nations Decade of Disable persons, had
initiated, participated and financed the Asia-Pacific Decade of
Disabled Persons.
</P>
<P>
She added China would continue to attach importance to the
work of youth, aging and disabled persons, and do a good job of
it. 
</P>
</TEXT>
