<HEADLINE> Germany, France Reaches Agreement on Euro </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, October 14 (Xinhua) -- The finance ministers of Germany
and France today reached an agreement on how future members of the
single European currency (Euro) should informally coordinate their
economic policies after the currency's introduction in January
1999.
</P>
<P>
Under the agreement reached by German Finance Minister Theo
Waigel and his French counterpart Dominique Strauss-Kahn, finance
ministers of those EU states that form the single currency should
meet first in an "informal forum" to coordinate their economic
policies prior to finance ministers meetings of all EU member
states.
</P>
<P>
A proposal to form such a forum would be submitted by Germany
and France at the next EU finance minister meeting due in
November, said the two ministers after their meeting in the
western German city of Muenster.
</P>
<P>
Describing the forum as "a bit like the Group of Seven
industrialized countries", Strauss-Kahn said it would discuss
exchange rates, fiscal reforms and structural policies.
</P>
<P>
Waigel meanwhile stressed that economic coordination should not
compromise independence of the future European central bank.
Moreover, meetings of the EU finance ministers should still play a
pivotal role in economic coordination.
</P>
<P>
Today's agreement between Bonn and Paris apparently represented
a compromise over their dispute concerning the management of the
Euro.
</P>
<P>
The French Socialist government had been demanding the
establishment of an economic council for policy coordination among
the members of the Euro club, which would serve as a political
counterweight to the European central bank.
</P>
<P>
Germany, however, wants the new central bank to be as
independent as Germany's Bundesbank. It also prefers to leave
economic coordination in the hands of the finance ministers of all
15 EU member states, fearing that a body limited to the Euro
member countries would create a divisive, two-speed Europe.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
