<HEADLINE> Developing Nations Urged to Encourage Investment </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, October 14 (Xinhua) -- The Food and Agriculture
Organization (FAO) has urged developing countries to encourage
investment from world food producers to ensure that the poor and
hungry get their share of food.
</P>
<P>
FAO made the appeal on the eve of World Food Day, which falls
on October 16.
</P>
<P>
In a statement released here today, FAO said with external
assistance to agriculture declining, " the way forward will be
for governments to work with farmers and the private sector, and
with non-governmental organizations and the international
community, to encourage investment al all levels from the food
producers upwards especially to ensure that the poor and hungry
get their share of the food that is produced."
</P>
<P>
In order to increase food production in developing countries
to match demand until the year 2010, FAO estimates that gross
annual investment of about 86 billion U.S. dollars in primary
production will be needed, 43 billion dollars for processing,
storage, distribution and marketing facilities and 37 billion
dollars for support services and infrastructure.
</P>
<P>
In a World Food Day message released earlier, FAO
Director-General Jacqes Diouf said, " By choosing investing in
food security we will highlight the need to create conditions and
incentives that will promote investment both by private and
public sectors to enchance food supply as well as ensure adequate
access to food by all.
</P>
<P>
"All sectors of civil society must work together if we are to
succeed in our objective to achieve food for all. Investng in
food security means that grassroots and local efforts together
with government, the private sector, multilateral and bilateral
efforts at national level should all be focused on a common
vision and agenda for food security," Diouf said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
