<HEADLINE> Zambia May Use Mozambique's Nacala Corridor </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MAPUTO, October 14 (Xinhua) -- Gerry Chabwera, President of
the Association of Commerce and Industry of Zambia, said today
that his country might use Mozambique's Nacala Corridor for the
transportation of goods starting from next year.
</P>
<P>
Gerry made the remark after meeting officials from the
Mozambican Railways Company at Nacala, northern Mozambique,
according to a report by Mozambique News Agency.
</P>
<P>
He said that Mozambique and Zambia may reach an agreement in
this respect by the end of the year.
</P>
<P>
Gerry said that he is optimistic about the possibility for the
Mozambican side to open the way for negotiation on the issue.
</P>
<P>
He said that the basic infrastructures at the corridor left
deep impression on him, adding that Nacala Corridor may open
another attractive channel for import and export.
</P>
<P>
The Zambian official said that Zambia would export about
500,000 ton of goods and import 150,000 tons through Nacala Port.
</P>
<P>
Zambia may become the second foreign customer after Malawi to
use the corridor. Zambia finds Nacala Corridor to be a more
competitive transport channel than the Dar es Salaam Port, Durban
Port in South Africa, and the Beira Port in Mozambique, he said.
</P>
<P>
About 77 km of the 920 km-long Nacala Railways was destroyed
in the civil war, but Miguel Matavele, official with the
Mozambican Railways Company, said that Zambia should not be
bothered by the matter which is being solved by his company.
</P>
</TEXT>
