<HEADLINE> Two American Scientists Awarded World Food Prize </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, October 14 (Xinhua) -- The 1997 World Food Prize
has been awarded jointly to two American scientists for their
contributions to new approaches to agricultural pest control,
reducing insecticide use while increasing yields.
</P>
<P>
The prize, the leading international award in recognition of
individuals whose work has advanced human development by improving
quantity, quality and availability of the world's food supply, was
awarded to Dr. Ray F. Smith, 78, from the University of California
in Berkeley, and Dr. Perry L. Adkisson, 68, from the Texas A&AMP;M
University.
</P>
<P>
"Working individually and together over 30 years, Smith and
Adkisson helped bring about a fundamental shift in agricultural
production marked by a dramatic reduction in the use of chemical
pesticides," said a statement on the award.
</P>
<P>
It said their work on new approaches, known as "integrated pest
management" (IPM), to agricultural pest control had sparked a
global ecological revolution. The IPM employs a variety of
biological, cultural, ecological and chemical techniques to
protect a wide variety of food and fiber crops from insect damage
in an environmentally sustainable manner.
</P>
<P>
The new techniques have made the United States a focal point
for the development of IPM programs for fruit, citrus, vegetables,
soybeans, grain sorghum, cotton, peanuts and rice. As a result,
pesticide use on U.S. food crops has dropped by half, and more
than 77 percent on cotton.
</P>
<P>
Assisted by a number of internationals organizations, including
the Food and Agriculture Organization, the United Nations
Environment Program and the U.S. Agency for International
Development, the two scientists have also worked to promote IPM
programs for crops, fruits and vegetables grown in Africa, Asia,
Latin America and Middle East. The IPM is practiced on millions of
farms throughout the world.
</P>
<P>
"In helping to provide food security for billions of people
around the world while reducing the risk to our soil, our water,
our air and to the people who grow and consume food, Drs. Smith
and Adkisson have served their fellow human beings in truly
exemplary fashion," said World Food Prize Foundation Chairman John
Ruan, who presented the award to the winners today.
</P>
<P>
The prize was created by Norman Borlaug, who won the Nobel
Peace Prize in 1970 for developing high-yield wheat strains as
part of the so-called Green Revolution. Since 1990, the award has
been sponsored by the foundation established by Ruan.
</P>
<P>
The prize was awarded to distinguished persons annually and He
Kang, former Minister of Agriculture in China, received the prize
in 1993 for his leadership lead to large increase in agricultural
output in the early 1980s in China. 
</P>
</TEXT>
