<HEADLINE> Mandela to Visit Libya, Egypt, Morocco </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, October 14 (Xinhua) -- South African President
Nelson Mandela will visit three north African countries -- Libya,
Egypt and Morocco -- later this month.
</P>
<P>
"North Africa is increasingly becoming an important trading
partner for South Africa as well as an important partner within
the context of the Organization of African Unity (OAU), " a
statement of the president's office said today.
</P>
<P>
The visits emphasize the importance of the north African
region to South Africa, that is, South Africa's ability to
provide technology for the exploitation of the resources in the
region, said the statement.
</P>
<P>
This will be Mandela's first north African trip since his
election as president in 1994 except his attendance of the OAU
meeting in Tunis in the same year.
</P>
<P>
Mandela's decision to visit Libya comes in response to a
long-standing invitation from Libyan head of state, Colonel Omar
Qadhafi, the statement said.
</P>
<P>
"Libya is a country which was very supportive of the South
African liberation movements during the struggle against
apartheid and is one of the countries that the president has not
visited since his inauguration," it said.
</P>
<P>
Relations between South Africa and Libya have been on a sound
footing since the democratic election of 1994. Both countries
have expressed the wish to expand trade relations.
</P>
<P>
"Currently bilateral trade is limited. However, Libya remains
a potentially significant trading partner for South Africa," the
statement added.
</P>
<P>
South Africa insisted on developing relations with Libya, Iran
and Cuba, defying pressure and warning from the United States, of
which the three countries are bitter rivals.
</P>
<P>
According to the statement, Mandela's visit to Egypt will
focus on economic matters.
</P>
<P>
Two-way trade between the two countries has grown from 61
million Rand (13 million U.S. dollars) in 1994 to 410 million
Rand (87 million dollars) in 1996.
</P>
<P>
Mandela will visit Libya and Egypt on his way to the
Commonwealth heads of government meeting scheduled for October
24-27 in Britain.
</P>
<P>
He will go to Morocco immediately after the meeting.
</P>
</TEXT>
