<HEADLINE> World Needs to Develop All Its Oil And Gas, Shell </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, October 14 (Xinhua) - The world will need to develop
all its oil and natural gas reserves before sufficient renewable
energy sources become available next century, according to Cor
Herkstroter, chairman of Royal Dutch/Shell.
</P>
<P>
In an interview with the Financial Times published here today,
he said, the world's largest international oil company was
committed to developing renewable energy sources into a new core
business.
</P>
<P>
But Herkstroter warned countries "not to expect miracles from
renewables". The growth in use of renewables would be relatively
slow, he added.
</P>
<P>
The chairman predicted that the market share of renewable
energy sources such as solar and biomass would grow rapidly
between 2025 and 2050, when they could account for half the
world's energy needs.
</P>
<P>
To develop renewables "is not just a matter of money.
Technology also needs to be developed and projects put together,"
he said.
</P>
<P>
Herkstroter also warned a dramatic reduction in energy use
would not encourage the use of renewables, and could even slow
the pace of their development.
</P>
<P>
Such shifts could only be brought about by break-throughs in
information and communication technology and the introduction of
new industrial materials, he said.
</P>
<P>
The company has calculated that development of all the known
and expected conventional oil and gas resources will add about 60
parts per million to the present atmospheric concentration of
carbon dioxide of . That, Herkstroter said, would be below
most proposed limists.
</P>
<P>
The EU argues that it would be economically and technically
possible for the industrialized nations to bring their emissions
down to 15% below the 1990 level by 2010.
</P>
<P>
Herkstroter said his company supported action to reduce the
emission of greenhouse gases. But he described the EU's proposals
as "unrealistic".
</P>
<P>
"A reasonable cut would be what can actually be done," he said,
adding that a 5% reduction over 10 years would be a better
solution. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
