<HEADLINE> Turkey Urges Greece Not to Increase Tensions </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA, October 14 (Xinhua) -- The Greek government should
stop its policy of increasing tensions in Cyprus, a senior
Turkish official said here today.
</P>
<P>
Following a meeting with visiting British Minister of State Doug
Henderson, Minister of State Sukru Sina Gurel warned that if
Greece continue to intensify situation in Cyprus, the possibility
of clashes might come true.
</P>
<P>
"A very dangerous game is being played by Greece at the
moment. They are playing with fire," he said.
</P>
<P>
At present, Greek and Greek Cypriot troops are holding
one-week joint exercises, code-named "Nikiforos '97" in Cyprus
under their joint defense pact.
</P>
<P>
In reaction, a large number of Turkish military jets flew
over the airspace of Cyprus over the past two days.
</P>
<P>
The Greek Foreign Ministry accused Turkey of violating Greek
Cypriot's airspace. However, Ankara rebuffed the accusation,
saying this was only a move to show Turkey's determination to
defend Turkish Cypriots' freedom and rights.
</P>
<P>
The situation in Cyprus have been worsening in recent months
because Cyprus signed in January an arms deal to buy Russian-made
S-300 missiles.
</P>
<P>
Turkey had threatened that it will destroy these missiles if
they are finally deployed in the Greek Cypriot-controlled area of
the island country.
</P>
<P>
Cyprus has been divided into rival Greek Cypriot community in
the south and Turkish Cypriot community in the north since 1974
when Turkish troops took over the northern third of the island
following a pro-Athens coup.
</P>
<P>
On a shuttle mission for solution to the protracted Cyprus issue,
U.S. special envoy for Cyprus Richard Holbrooke, accompanied by
U.S. State Department's new coordinator for Cyprus Thomas Miller,
arrived here last Sunday.
</P>
<P>
Following a meeting with Turkish Foreign Minister Ismail Cem
on Monday, Holbrooke urged all parties concerned in Cyprus to
exercise restraint and avoided actions which might increase
tensions.
</P>
<P>
Both Holbrooke and Cem refrained from disclosing the contents
of their two-hour-long meeting.
</P>
<P>
The Turkish Cypriots, who gain political, economic and
military support from Turkey, declared in 1983 a break-away
"Turkish Republic of Northern Cyprus" which has been recognized
only by Ankara.
</P>
<P>
The United Nations and international community have been
making efforts for a political solution to the Cyprus problem,
but no tangible results have been achieved so far. 
</P>
</TEXT>
