<HEADLINE> General Assembly Elects Five Security Council Seats </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, October 14 (Xinhua) -- Gabon, Gambia, Bahrain,
Slovenia and Brazil were today elected by the General Assembly to
two-year terms on the Security Council effective on January 1,
1998.
</P>
<P>
Chile, South Korea, Egypt, Guinea-Bissau and Poland will
depart from the 15-member council at the end of this year.
</P>
<P>
Five other non-permanent members of the council whose two-year
terms expire at the end of 1998 are Japan, Costa Rica, Kenya,
Portugal and Sweden.
</P>
<P>
The council's five permanent members, each with veto power, are
China, Britain, Russia, France and the United states. 
</P>
</TEXT>
