<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Forces of Sassou Nguesso Announces Capture of Brazzaville </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, October 14 (Xinhua) -- The forces of the former
president of Congo Republic Denis Sassou Nguesso announced today
that they have captured "totally" the country's capital
Brazzaville.
</P>
<P>
Agence France-Presse (AFP) quoted Isidore Mvouba, the spokesman
of the Democratic and Popular Forces (FDP) party of Sassou
Nguesso, as saying that FDP forces have "taken the total control
of Brazzaville and are massing upon the bridge of Djoue" at the
southern end of the city.
</P>
<P>
He said that the "last pocket of residual resistance" of
troops loyal to President Pascal Lissouba and Prime Minister
Bernard Kolelas were "eliminated by mid-day."
</P>
<P>
The FDP forces took the district of Bacongo and Makele-Kele
from the militiamen loyal to Kolelas, while the presidential
palace fell on Monday, AFP quoted the spokesman as saying in
Libreville, Gabon.
</P>
<P>
Mvouba said that a dozen government soldiers were killed in the
fighting, while the loss on the FDP side was "actually nil,"
because the FDP soldiers were proceeded by several tanks.
</P>
<P>
He also said that FDP used a Mig-21 combat aircraft to bomb a
camp of government forces on Monday, killing about 20 government
soldiers.
</P>
<P>
He called on the forces loyal to Lissouba and Kolelas to lay
down their arms to prevent more sufferings be inflicted upon
Congolese people, who he said had "already suffered more than
they counted."
</P>
<P>
The FDP estimated that 10,000 people have been killed since
fighting broke out in Brazzaville on June 5.
</P>
<P>
The FDP spokesman also said that the FDP would not tolerate any
attempt to divide the country and intends to maintain the unity of
Congo. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
