<DOCNO> XIE19971015.0049 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-14 19:45 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Cyprus, Greece to Continue Defense Cooperation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NICOSIA, October 14 (Xinhua) -- Cyprus and Greece today agreed
to continue executing their joint defense pact unless a just
solution to the Cyprus problem is reached.
</P>
<P>
The agreement was reached between Cyprus' Acting President
Spyros Kyprianou and Greek Defense Minister Akis Tsohatzopoulos,
who is on a visit here.
</P>
<P>
The two were reviewing the five-day military exercises launched
by Cyprus' National Guard and participated by Greek naval and air
forces.
</P>
<P>
Kyprianou, also Speaker of the House of Representatives of
Cyprus, expressed satisfaction with the success of the exercises
code-named "Nikiforos (Victorious) '97" which started on October
10.
</P>
<P>
The Greek defense minister said that the high efficiency of the
maneuvers has sent a message to all "whose behavior is nothing but
a threat." He stopped short of naming Turkey.
</P>
<P>
Cyprus and Greece signed in 1993 the Common Pact on defense,
under which Greece will provide Cyprus with military assistance in
case the island is attacked.
</P>
<P>
The Greek-Cypriot joint military exercises have drawn strong
protest from Turkey, which warned it will negatively affect the
Cyprus peace talks. Turkey sent troops onto the island in 1974 and
maintains 35,000 troops in its northern third to protect Turkish
Cypriots.
</P>
<P>
Turkey's State Minister Sukru Gurel said today that the
exercises will not only poison the relations between Turkey and
Greece, but can also lead to an increased possibility of
incidents, including armed conflict.
</P>
<P>
Greece and Turkey have long been at odds over territorial
waters and seabed mineral rights in the Aegean Sea, the
sovereignty of a couple of uninhabited islets and the protracted
issue of Cyprus.
</P>
<P>
Cyprus has been divided since Turkey troops seized its northern
part following a failed coup by the Greek Cypriots seeking union
with Greece.
</P>
<P>
Turkish Cypriots declared in 1983 a breakaway "Turkish Republic
of Northern Cyprus", recognized only by Turkey, against the
internationally recognized Republic of Cyprus controlled by the
Greek Cypriots. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
