<HEADLINE> US Special Coordinator for Cyprus Visits Greece </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ATHENS, October 14 (Xinhua) -- A radical lifting of the
deadlock in relations between Greece and Turkey would be very
important, but if this was not attainable, weight might be placed
on small steps in various issues, said U.S. State Department
special coordinator for Cyprus Thomas Miller today.
</P>
<P>
Miller made the statement after meeting with Greek Foreign
Minister Theodoros Pangalos here today.
</P>
<P>
Miller arrived here this morning from Turkey to discuss with
Greek officials ways of resolving the Cyprus issue and improving
Greek-Turkish relations.
</P>
<P>
Miller said that the spirit of the Madrid communique guiding
principles for bettering ties, signed by Greek Prime Minister
Costas Simitis and Turkish President Suleyman Demirel in July, was
still alive and that it was a "dynamic text on the basis of which
we are trying to build new efforts."
</P>
<P>
His statements came only days after Turkish Prime Minister
Mesut Yilmaz declared in Strasbourg that "the spirit of Madrid is
dead," blaming the Greek government and Pangalos in particular for
their "radical statements" regarding Ankara.
</P>
<P>
As for the situation in the Aegean, Miller said that efforts to
achieve progress in the recent meetings between Pangalos and his
Turkish counterpart, Ismail Cem, in New York had not been
materialized, but Miller expressed the hope that this could happen
in future.
</P>
<P>
When asked about the Cyprus problem, he reaffirmed that the
U.S. supported the creation of a bi-zone, bi-communal federation
in the island republic. Washington had made it clear to the Turks
that it also fully backed Cyprus' accession to the European Union
(EU), he added.
</P>
<P>
But he stressed that EU accession negotiations with Cyprus must
be conducted with the Republic of Cyprus after the participation
of the Turkish Cypriots in a single negotiating delegation was
secured.
</P>
<P>
He hailed Cyprus President Glafcos Clerides's proposal for a
demilitarization of the island as "positive," saying that the
condition was that it took into account necessary security
measures for the Turkish Cypriots.
</P>
<P>
Commenting on the proposed deployment of Russian-made S-300
ground-to-air missiles on Cyprus, Turkish threats over the
missiles and infringements of Greek and Cypriot national air
space, he said that these did not help in the necessary reduction
of tension in the area. 
</P>
</TEXT>
