<HEADLINE> Chretien to Visit Russia, Attend Commonwealth Meeting </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OTTAWA, October 14 (Xinhua) -- Canadian Prime Minister Jean
Chretien announced today he will attend the Commonwealth Heads of
Government Meeting in Edinburgh, Scotland, after a visit to Russia
from October 18-22.
</P>
<P>
During his visit to Russia, Chretien plans to meet with Russian
President Boris Yeltsin and other political leaders.
</P>
<P>
They will "discuss a variety of issues such as the treaty to
ban anti-personnel mines, Canada's economic relations with Russia
and cooperation in the Arctic," according to a news release from
Chretien's office.
</P>
<P>
At the Edinburgh meeting from October 24 to 27, the
Commonwealth leaders will consider the report by the Commonwealth
Ministerial Action Group regarding the membership status of
Nigeria, Sierra Leone and the Gambia.
</P>
<P>
This year, the biennial meeting has the theme of "Trade,
Investment and Sustainable Development: The Road to Commonwealth
Prosperity."
</P>
<P>
This will be the first time that an economic theme has been
chosen for the meeting.
</P>
<P>
Chretien "will take the opportunity to promote trade
liberalization and the greater integration of developing countries
into the international trading system."
</P>
<P>
"He will also use the occasion to discuss the campaign to ban
anti-personnel landmines," according to the release. 
</P>
