<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-14 20:23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Cairo Bus Attackers Deny Joining Islamic Group </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, October 14 (Xinhua) -- The two Egyptians on charge of
killing nine German tourists in an attack in downtown Cairo on
September 18 today denied they had joined any Islamic
fundamentalist group.
</P>
<P>
Saber Farahat Abu el-Ela and his brother Mahmoud were standing
trial today at the Higher Military Court for the deadly attack
which killed an Egyptian driver as well.
</P>
<P>
Before the hearing began, Saber, the main defendant, told
reporters from behind a steel cage that he and his brother did not
join any Islamic group but admitted leaning towards the ideology
of the banned Al-Jihad (Holy War) organization.
</P>
<P>
He said that his association with Al-Jihad is purely spiritual
and that he was not a member of the organization.
</P>
<P>
He confessed to reporters that he had meant to deal a blow to
the country's resurging tourist industry and he had been ready to
use knives to kill the tourists in case his pistol malfunctioned.
</P>
<P>
In the appalling attack, the Farahat brothers shot randomly at
German tourists in a bus parked in front of the renowned Egyptian
Museum and then threw a petrol bomb inside it, killing nine German
tourists and the Egyptian driver.
</P>
<P>
Saber had been admitted to the Abbasiya mental asylum where he
escaped about three days before carrying out the attack. The head
of the hospital has been arrested for taking bribes from Farahat's
family.
</P>
<P>
The mental status of Saber, who had been declared insane by a
court in a previous trial for murdering three foreigners at a
Cairo in 1993, is yet to be determined by the military court.
</P>
<P>
Reflecting on his that attack, Saber said it came after the
breakout of conflicts in Bosnia-Herzegovina that involved the
Muslims, Croats and Serbs. "I wanted to go there on a Jihad
mission, but I could not make it," he added.
</P>
<P>
Saber, who refused to be treated as a nutcase, said he had a
whole month to plan for the attack, which took place in Cairo's
busiest square at rush hours.
</P>
<P>
Earlier, Saber claimed his attack was to avenge blasphemous
posters put up by an Israeli woman in Hebron depicting Islam's
Prophet Mohammed as a pig. The drawing came under fire across the
Muslim world.
</P>
<P>
Mahmoud told reporters that he and his brother agreed to launch
the attack together using a pistol, ammunition and steel
weapons. Other seven men, who sold them the weapons and
ammunition, have been named co-defendants in the trial.
</P>
<P>
Amid tight security, the first hearing was held at 11
a.m. (local time) today in a courtroom thronged with Arab and
foreign reporters. The second hearing is scheduled for Saturday.
</P>
<P>
The Farahat brothers, on charges of manslaughter, arson,
sabotage, illegal possession of weapons and attack on police
officers, could face the death penalty if convicted.
</P>
<P>
The case was transferred to the military tribunal from the
state security on September 22 on an order of Egyptian President
Hosni Mubarak for a speedy trial.
</P>
<P>
In a bid to contain damages to its multi-billion-dollar tourist
industry, the Egyptian government has laboriously denied the
attack was staged by Islamic extremists as in the previous cases
and was quick to ban media coverage on the court's investigations.
</P>
<P>
A total of 1,255 people have been killed since 1992 by
fundamentalist militants in a violent campaign against Egypt's
secular government. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
