<HEADLINE> London Silver Business Rises Sharply in September </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, October 14 (Xinhua) -- Silver business rose sharply on
the London bullion market last month, with average daily turnover
jumping by more than 19 percent to 314.3 million ounces, the
Financial Times reported today.
</P>
<P>
Citing figures released by the London Bullion Market
Association (LBMA), the newspaper said that the average silver
price in London also rose from 4.50 US dollars a troy ounce in
August to 4.73 US dollars.
</P>
<P>
As a result, the daily value of silver turnover also increased
by 25 percent to 1.5 billion US dollars.
</P>
<P>
The chief executive of the LBMA said that the main cause of the
increase in silver business was a high level of physical demand
and increased activity in the forward market.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, average daily gold business also rose last month
although more modestly, with daily clearing turnover up by 3.3
percent to 34.3 million ounces.
</P>
<P>
The average daily turnover in value terms rose from 10.7
billion US dollars in August to 11.1 billion US dollars in
September although the average price fell from 324.01 US dollars
an ounce to 322.82 US dollars. 
</P>
</TEXT>
