<HEADLINE> Turkey Defends Its Military Co-op with Israel </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA, October 14 (Xinhua) -- Turkey's military cooperation
with Israel is aimed at promoting tranquility in the region, a
senior Turkish official said here today.
</P>
<P>
Before meeting with visiting Israeli Chief of Staff Amnon
Shahak, Turkish Deputy Prime Minister Ismet Sezgin told the press
that Turkey and Israel always do their utmost to ensure peace and
stability in the region and will continue to do so, the Anatolia
News Agency reported.
</P>
<P>
Sezgin, also defense minister, made the remarks in a bid to
soothe Arab countries, which have expressed grave concern over the
growing Turkish-Israeli military alliance.
</P>
<P>
Shahak arrived here Sunday on a three-day visit aimed at
enhancing bilateral military cooperation. During his visit, he
exchanged views with Turkish government and military leaders.
</P>
<P>
Shahak and his Turkish counterpart Ismail Hakki Karaday
reportedly discussed a joint project to produce Delilah long-range
missiles during their Monday meeting.
</P>
<P>
Earlier, local reports said the Israeli chief of staff would
persuade the Turkish military to replace its tank units with
Israeli-made Merkava 3, one of the world's most sophisticate types
so far.
</P>
<P>
The Turkish-Israeli cooperation in military and defense fields
has expanded rapidly since early last year, when they signed two
agreements to allow, among other things, their warplanes to be
trained in each other's airspace.
</P>
<P>
The scheduled joint naval exercises involving Israel, Turkey
and the United States on November 16 might be further postponed at
U.S. request. The exercises were originally set for May.
</P>
<P>
Turkey, a predominantly Muslim nation, has been condemned by
Iran and some Arab countries for betraying the interests of the
Muslim world by developing closer ties with the Jewish state.
</P>
</TEXT>
