<HEADLINE> EU Gets Support for Proposal to Reduce Gas Emissions </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, October 14 (Xinhua) -- The World Wide Fund for Nature
(WWF) today welcomed industry support for the European Union's
proposal to reduce greenhouse gas emissions by 7.5 percent by the
year 2005 and by 15 percent by 2010.
</P>
<P>
A report released today offers a set of 12 recommendations on
climate change policy which were jointly elaborated by Shell
Netherlands, the WWF Netherlands and the Center for European
Policy Studies (CEPS).
</P>
<P>
The report, published by the CEPS, is a result of a series of
workshops between the WWF and representatives of European oil,
electricity and energy-intensive industries which took place
earlier this year.
</P>
<P>
The workshops were sponsored by the WWF Netherlands and chaired
by Leen Koster, the director for environmental affairs of Shell
Netherlands, according to the WWF European Policy Office in
Brussels.
</P>
<P>
"This report shows that the industry's negative attitude
towards climate change is starting to change in the light of
overwhelming evidence that climate change is a real threat and
needs to be dealt with," said Sible Schone, climate change expert
of the WWF Netherlands.
</P>
<P>
He added that the oil business had recognized that the climate
summit in Kyoto would only be the beginning of the climate
discussion.
</P>
<P>
Industry representatives also recognize the precautionary
principle and support the EU proposal to reduce greenhouse gas
emissions by 7.5 percent by the year 2005 and 15 percent by the
year 2010.
</P>
<P>
The WWF and industry both agree that much stronger energy
efficiency policies are necessary, according to the WWF European
Policy Office. It also says that the WWF welcomes the support from
industry for policies like progressive energy efficiency standards
for cars and appliances, and a life-cycle assessment obligation
for new appliances. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
