<HEADLINE> Turkey Denies Secret Military Pact with Denmark </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA, October 14 (Xinhua) -- The Turkish military today
denied a Danish press report that Turkey and Denmark had signed a
secret pact to jointly intervene any possible exigencies in
southern Turkey.
</P>
<P>
According to the semi-official Anatolia News Agency, the
military called the report, published in a daily called Jylland
Posten, as "baseless."
</P>
<P>
The newspaper report said that under the military agreement,
Denmark will send warplanes and missile experts in case of
emergency in southern Turkey, but Copenhagen had tried to keep it
secret due to Turkey's poor human rights record.
</P>
<P>
Dismissing the report as unfounded, a high-ranking official
from the Turkish General Staff who preferred anonymity said such
an arrangement is not a bilateral agreement between Turkey and
Denmark.
</P>
<P>
This should be realized within the framework of the North
Atlantic Treaty Organization (NATO) if there is any trouble in the
bloc's southern flank, he added.
</P>
<P>
"Turkey is sending troops to different places within the
understanding of NATO solidarity, and in turn, other countries
can send troops here," he said.
</P>
<P>
During the 1991 Gulf War, Germany, Italy and Belgium all sent
their warplanes to southern Turkey's NATO air bases to join the
battle against Iraq.
</P>
<P>
The Danish Embassy here was not immediately available for
comment.
</P>
<P>
Turkey has shared bitter relations with its southeastern
neighboring countries including Iran, Iraq and Syria, which were
accused by Ankara of harboring its outlawed Kurdish Workers'
Party (PKK) militants.
</P>
<P>
The PKK has been fighting a separatist war against the
Turkish government since 1984 in southeastern Turkey. 
</P>
</TEXT>
