<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> ASEAN to Provide Technical Assistance to Laos, Myanmar </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SUBANG JAYA, Malaysia, October 15 (Xinhua) -- ASEAN will
provide technical assistance to its two new members, Laos and
Myanmar, to help them fulfill their obligations for the ASEAN Free
Trade Area (AFTA), it was announced here today.
</P>
<P>
Malaysian International Trade and Industry Minister Rafidah
Aziz told a news conference at the end of the 11th AFTA Council
meeting that the two countries would be given help to set up a
trade database of up-to-date export and import data.
</P>
<P>
Assistance will also be given in compiling information on
technical barriers to trade, building up the technical capacity
for standards development, laboratory testing and conformity
assessment, implementation of ASEAN harmonized tariff
nomenclature, human resource development and implementation of the
GATT Valuation Agreement.
</P>
<P>
Laos and Myanmar, both admitted into the Association of
Southeast Asian Nations (ASEAN) in July, attended the council
meeting for the first time. They have acceded to the Common
Effective Preferential Tariff (CEPT) agreement, AFTA's main
operating mechanism, following their admission.
</P>
<P>
The two countries are to implement their tariff reduction
programs on January 1, 1998, and complete it within 10 years. By
then, the AFTA tariff band must be between zero and 5 percent.
</P>
<P>
Both countries have submitted their final CEPT packages --
inclusion list, temporary exclusion list, sensetive and general
exception list.
</P>
<P>
Laos has so far a total of 533 tariff lines (15 percent of its
total) in its inclusion list in which all products have tariff
rates of 5 percent, and 2,820 tariff lines (79.4 percent of its
total) in the temporary exclusion list.
</P>
<P>
Myanmar submitted 2,355 tariff lines (43 percent of its total)
in the inclusion list, and 2,987 tariff lines (54.6 percent of its
total) in the temporary exclusion list. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971015.0062 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Instrument Company Eyes on Wider China Market </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW YORK, October 15 (Xinhua) -- Curtis Instruments Inc., a
small company by the American standard but a world leader in
instrumentation and controls for electric vehicles for decades, is
now finding its way into the Chinese market.
</P>
<P>
Its newly established production line in Suzhou, east China,
will soon begin to turn out the electronic speed controllers for
electric bicycles, motorized wheelchairs and other vehicles. It is
a solely American invested venture, which cost more than 6 million
U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
"China will become our important technical base after an
electric transportation," Edward Marwell, President of the Curtis
Instruments Inc., told the reporter during an interview recently.
</P>
<P>
Curtis has joined a growing number of technical companies
devoting resources to the challenge of supporting the quest of
many Asian nations to find a clean, viable alternative to the
noisy, air polluting 2-cycle engines widely in use in Asia. Using
electric devices to replace the pollutant emitting engines has
become a trend of the market.
</P>
<P>
Marwell said that Curtis will work closely with primary Chinese
bicycle manufacturers to facilitate electrification of standard
bicycles, which continue to be an important transportation method
in Asia. It will also cooperate with other foreign investors in
China such as Linde, the major forklift manufacturer of Germany,
and Nacco, a U.S. forklift maker in Shanghai.
</P>
<P>
This important product development program will be spearheaded
by the Curtis China Co. at the new, highly modern Suzhou
manufacturing plant, which was approved by the Chinese government
in September, 1995. The Suzhou plant is now producing modules, the
chip-on-board gadgets for various kinds of LCD and LED indicators
used in vehicles, mobile working tools such as forklifts and
bulldozers.
</P>
<P>
Marwell also said that gradually Suzhou will produce most of
its modules and electronic control boards for the Asian market.
</P>
<P>
He said he has been excited by the success in his new plant in
China. Now the Chinese are fully responsible for the management of
production, personnel and financial matters. Its Beijing office
assists the sales on the Chinese market. "They have been doing
very well," he said.
</P>
<P>
Commenting on the forthcoming U.S. visit by the Chinese
president Jiang Zemin, Marwell said that it, by all nature, will
become an important visit to enhance bilateral relations in all
fields. The two countries traditionally have close relations,
which should be further promoted, he noted.
</P>
<P>
He added that the local authorities of the Suzhou High-Tech
Zone have been very cooperative during the whole process of
establishment.
</P>
<P>
He said that the success of his China business also lies in the
high technology and the use of smart people who not only know the
actual conditions of the country but also have real expertise in
the technology.
</P>
<P>
The Suzhou plant is expected to turn out 1 million modules next
year, which is really a big size compared to the world's market
needs of 2.5 million to 3 million pieces annually, according to
Marwell.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
