<HEADLINE> Tokyo Asked to Refrain from Challenge on Islets </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SEOUL, October 15 (Xinhua) -- South Korea today demanded that
Japan refrain from taking issue with Seoul on the sovereignty over
the Tokto islets (Takeshima islets in Japanese).
</P>
<P>
The request came in reaction to a Japanese Foreign Ministry
spokesman's expression of regret over a South Korea's defense
white paper which described Tokto (Takeshima), two tiny islets
located in the middle of the sea between the two countries, as
South Korean territory.
</P>
<P>
Director Park Joon-woo of the South Korean Foreign Ministry, in
charge of issues with Japan, called in Hideaki Mizukoshi, the
First Secretary of the Japanese Embassy. He said that Tokto was
South Korean territory from "an historical as well as legal
viewpoint" and this was based on international law.
</P>
<P>
Japanese Foreign Ministry spokesman Hiroshi Hashimoto said the
previous day that Japan had officially filed a complaint with the
South Korean Embassy in Tokyo, complaining that Takeshima (Tokto)
was included in the South Korean defense white paper. 
</P>
</TEXT>
