<HEADLINE> No-confidence Vote Damages Russia's Economy: Chubais </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, October 15 (Xinhua) -- Russian First Deputy Prime
Minister Anatoly Chubais said today that the State Duma's
no-confidence vote in the government would considerably damage the
country's economy.
</P>
<P>
Addressing a meeting at the Ministry of State Property, Chubais
said the vote may cause a governmental crisis which could lose the
country 300-400 million U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
The motion will also complicate the situation with the Russian
national debt servicing, he added.
</P>
<P>
Last week, the lower house of parliament criticized the
country's economic performance in the first nine months this year
and rejected the government's 1998 draft budget.
</P>
<P>
The Communists, who have 140 members in the 450-seat State
Duma, initiated the no-confidence vote against the government.
</P>
<P>
The State Duma convened today to decide the fate of the
reformist government.
</P>
<P>
If the no-confidence vote passes through, State Duma has to
vote again within three months to force President Boris Yeltsin to
dissolve either the cabinet or the legislative body. 
</P>
</TEXT>
