<HEADLINE> Somalis Accuse Foreigners of Looting Their </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOGADISHU, October 15 (Xinhua) -- The accusations against
foreigners in relation with the looting of Somalia's national
assets are not confined only to the sea and land, but they are
also stretched up to the air space.
</P>
<P>
About a dozen Somalis from the former civil aviation
department have accused foreigners in the Kenyan capital,
Nairobi, for misusing funds collected from the planes using
Somalia's air space.
</P>
<P>
Osman Isse Abdi, spokesman for the Somali civil aviation, an
office that handles all air traffic business over Somalia's air
space, remains open in Nairobi since the departure of the
multi-national forces from Somalia in early March 1995.
</P>
<P>
Abdi furthermore said this office is run by a Canadian
national, J.W. Drunswig.
</P>
<P>
The spokesman from Mogadishu's former main tower said every
plane that passes through Somalia's air space is charged with 427
US dollars per hour. Abdi believes this money is used by Brunswig
all by himself, "Unfortunately this money goes straight to the
pockets of Brunswig, and there's no one to control him," said
Abdi.
</P>
<P>
Abdi said they have already forwarded their accusations to
Brunswig himself who, according to them, claimed to have been
giving salary to many Somalis from the Somali civil aviation
department. Abdi has called the United Nations agencies and the
Somali leaders to take appropriate measures against the so-called
"looting of Somalia's air space."
</P>
<P>
Few former civil aviation employees are currently working for
the factions in their local airstrips where the narcotic leaves
of khat and few aid agencies's planes land every day around the
capital and several regions in the country.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, heavy rains from the Deyr season have started
falling in several regions in the country. In Mogadishu and its
surrounding areas, it has been raining for the last 24 hours, but
no damage or casualties are reported thus far despite the havoc
it is posing for the traffic in Mogadishu by creating puddles of
water everywhere in the ruined streets of the capital.
</P>
<P>
Reports from VHF radios also indicate that heavy rains have
also fallen in the central and northern regions. In the
northwestern region of Sanag, the rains have badly affected many
farm lands, water wells and houses.
</P>
<P>
According to the report, nearly 50 houses were destroyed while
about 1,000 animals mainly cattle and goats were also killed by
the rain waters. 
</P>
</TEXT>
