<BODY>
<HEADLINE> American, French Scientists Win Nobel Prize </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
STOCKHOLM, October 15 (Xinhua) -- American Professor Steven
Chu, French Professor Claude Cohen-Tannoudji and American
scientist William D. Philips have won the 1997 Nobel Physics Prize
"for development of methods to cool and trap atoms with laser
light," the Royal Swedish Academy of Sciences announced today.
</P>
<P>
The new methods of investigation developed by the Nobel
Laureates "have contributed greatly to increasing our knowledge of
the interplay between radiation and matter," the Academy said.
</P>
<P>
In particular, they had opened the way to a deeper
understanding of the quantum-physical behavior of gases at low
temperatures, said the Academy. And the methods might lead to the
design of more precise atomic clocks for use in practices such as
space navigation and accurate determination of position.
</P>
<P>
Steven Chu, born in 1948, is now Professor of physics at
Stanford University in the United States.
</P>
<P>
Claude Cohen-Tannoudji, born in 1933 in Algeria, is a French
Professor at College de France and Ecole Normale Superieure in
Paris.
</P>
<P>
William D. Philips, born in 1948, is a scientist at the
National Institute of Standards and Technology in Gaithersburg in
the U.S. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
