<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 1.3 Billion in Developed World Live in Poverty </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, October 15 (Xinhua) -- About one-third of the
population in the developing world, or 1.3 billion people,
currently live on less than one U.S. dollar per day, according to
a press release issued here today by the Bangkok-based United
Nations Economic and Social Commission for Asia and the Pacific
(ESCAP).
</P>
<P>
The largest number of poor people, about 950 million, live in
the Asia-Pacific region, and almost 40 percent of the total number
of poor, or about 500 million, live in South Asia, said the
release issued before the International Day for the Eradication of
Poverty on October 17.
</P>
<P>
Poverty in the Asia-Pacific region is still, to a large extent,
rural, the press release said.
</P>
<P>
However, as more and more poor people move to cities to seek
employment in hope for a better life, there is a trend towards the
urbanization of poverty.
</P>
<P>
On the other hand, poor people tend to be women, with the
number of poor women growing faster than that of poor men.
</P>
<P>
Community development and empowerment of the poor are
increasingly recognized as prerequisites to poverty alleviation.
This has been the experience of countries which have tackled
poverty in the Asia-Pacific region, said the press release.
</P>
<P>
To mark the International Day for the Eradication of Poverty,
ESCAP will organize a "hunger lunch" at its Bangkok headquarters
serving simple meal of vegetarian fried rice and fish sauce to
raise money for the construction of a day-care center for poor
children in the Chao Phraya community in Yannawa district,
Bangkok. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
