<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Roundup: Congo's Strategic Oil City Falls to Angolans </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, October 15 (Xinhua) -- The four-month war in the Congo
Republic took a dramatic turn today as troops from the Angolan
enclave, Cabinda, captured the country's strategic oil city
Pointe-Noire.
</P>
<P>
Coordinated reports from Congo said Angolan troops, backed by a
dozen tanks, took Pointe-Noire at 6:30 a.m. (5:30 GMT) this
morning after crossing from Cabinda, an enclave thrusting into
Congo and less than 100 kilometers from Pointe-Noire.
</P>
<P>
The presence of Angolan troops in Pointe-Noire was confirmed by
both the French consul there and the Belgian Defense Ministry, but
the Angolan government denied the report.
</P>
<P>
The commander in the Pointe-Noire military zone of the
government forces of Congo, Colonel Louembe, told Radio France
International today that he had ordered his soldiers to lay down
their arms and stop shooting.
</P>
<P>
"We don't want a bloodbath. We want to keep this city," he
said. " Whoever the conqueror is, they all need this city to
re-make the rest of the republic. It is peace which interests
us. One should save the city."
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the Democratic and Popular Forces (FDP) of former
Congolese President Denis Sassou Nguesso, who is fighting with
President Pascal Lissouba, announced this morning the capture of
Pointe-Noire by FDP forces.
</P>
<P>
"Our forces are circulating now on the principal artery of the
city, Avenue Charles de Gaulle. Residual resistance remains in
certain peripheral districts, but from now to mid-day, we will
have finished sweeping the last militiamen, the Zulus, Cocoyes and
other Mambas (supporting President Lissouba)," said FDP spokesman
Isidore Mvouba.
</P>
<P>
Following the latest development, France put its troops
deployed in Gabon and Chad on alert for a possible intervention to
evacuate about 1,600 French nationals now in Pointe-Noire.
</P>
<P>
But the French oil group Elf said the situation in Pointe-Noire
is calm and normalizing.
</P>
<P>
Pointe-Noire is Congo's second largest city, and is the base
for several oil companies engaged in offshore oil exploration in
Congo.
</P>
<P>
The oil trade volume of the city in 1997 is estimated at 800
billion CFA francs (1.4 billion U.S. dollars), with an expected
net income of some 380 billion CFA francs (600 million
U.S. dollars) for Congo.
</P>
<P>
The city accounts for 85 percent of the total oil product
exports of Congo, whose gross domestic product (GDP) heavily
depends on the oil industry. The Djeno oil terminal in the city
handled in 1995 traffic of 9.4 million tons of oil and liquefied
gas.
</P>
<P>
Elf-Congo, a branch of the French oil group Elf-Aquitaine, is
the biggest oil operator in Pointe-Noire, producing 720 million
barrels of crude oil out of the 870 million barrels produced there
each year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
