<HEADLINE> Hong Kong Wins First Golds In National Games </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANGHAI, October 15 (Xinhua) -- Hong Kong won its first gold
medal through cyclist Wong Kam-Po while Chen Yan became the triple
champion in the third-day competitions of the Eighth National
Games here on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
In the road race shortened from 180 kms to 157.88 kms due to
rains, the 24-year-old Wong beat vetaran Tang Xuezhong of Beijing,
clocking first in four hours 10 minutes and 7.50 seconds.
</P>
<P>
"I'm very proud to win the first gold for Hong Kong," Wong said
after beating a field of 56 riders.
</P>
<P>
Timothy Fok, head of the Hong Kong delegation, said Wong's gold
will enhance the morale for other Hong Kong athletes.
</P>
<P>
"By witnessing the fierce competition, I was as nervous as I
was awaiting my first child in the hospital," said Fok.
</P>
<P>
As one of the ace cyclists in Asia, Wong won the Tour of the
Philippines and Tour of Chinese Taipei and finished second in the
Asian Championships last year.
</P>
<P>
Chen Yan, a 16-year-old teenager from Liaoning province, reapt
her third gold medal by taking the women's 400-meter freestyle in
an Asian mark.
</P>
<P>
Chen who broke the world record in the 400-meter individual
medley on Monday and won the 200m freestyle on Tuesday, clocking
the year-best of four minutes five seconds in the 400-meter
freestyle this evening.
</P>
<P>
Her winning timing beat the previous Asian mark of 4:09.22 set
by Zhou Guanbin in 1994.
</P>
<P>
Wang Luna of Shanghai who lost to Chen in the 200m freestyle,
finished second again in 4:07.86. Chen Hua of Zhejiang bagged
home the bronze in 4:09.56.
</P>
<P>
"I feel very satisfied with the results," Chen said. "I have
trained in Beijing for a period of time before coming over here. I
guessed I have been in a superb form."
</P>
<P>
World record holder He Cihong of the Chinese Army was beaten to
second place by Zhen Yingjuan of Guangdong province in the women's
100m backstroke.
</P>
<P>
Zhen, 19, was timed at one minute and 0.22 second, only six
hundredths of a second shy of the world mark, which was set by He
in the Rome Swimming Worlds in 1994.
</P>
<P>
However, Le Jingyi also had something to cherish after
anchoring her teammates to win the women's 4X100m freestyle relay
in three minutes and 42.30 seconds.
</P>
<P>
In the men's 100m freestyle, local favorite Jiang Chengji
displayed his prowess by taking the gold in 50.62 seconds.
</P>
<P>
Jiang made the breakthrough for the Chinese men swimmers by
finishing the record fourth places both in 50m and 100m freestyles
in Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
"I had hoped to set a new Asian record," said the disappointed
Jiang. "And now I can only hope to challenge the foreign ace
swimmers in the World Championships."
</P>
<P>
The men's 200m butterfly was taken by Xie Xufeng of Guangdong
in one minute and 59.07 second.
</P>
<P>
Six more world records were broken in the women's 64-kg and
70-kg categories as a batch of Chinese strongwomen crushed all the
listed marks in their attempts.
</P>
<P>
Sun Tianni of Shandong province claimed her 70-kg weightligting
title while Lei Li of the Chinese Army took the 64-kg title.
</P>
</TEXT>
