<DOCNO> XIE19971015.0075 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Scientists Have High Hopes for Tibet Oil Reserve </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LHASA, October 15 (Xinhua) -- Chinese scientists think that the
Tibet Autonomous Region could follow in the footsteps of the
oil-rich Tarim Basin in the Xinjiang Uygur Autonomous Region.
</P>
<P>
After years of oil exploration, potential oilfields have been
mapped by the Ministry of Geology and Mineral Resources and the
China National Petroleum Corporation in the Qiangtang Basin in
northern Tibet.
</P>
<P>
Thick oil layers have been discovered in the Gangba Basin in
southern Tibet on more than 10,000 sq.m. of ground, according to
Qiu Dongzhou, of the China Academy of Geological Sciences.
</P>
<P>
Geologists found the region's first deep oil deposit, with 200
million tons, in the Lhupola Basin, and 1.5 million tons of proven
reserves have been found.
</P>
<P>
Geologists have found 6-sq. km. No. 1 field, and a major oil
formation has been found along the Changliu Spring-Tsony-Baitan
Lake Block in the Qiangtang Basin.
</P>
<P>
Many geologists believe that Tibet has favorable geology for
oil formations. The strata are of the Mesozoic and Cenozoic
periods and similar to oilfields in the Persian Gulf and the
Karakorum in Central Asia. Tibet is called "the last and largest
oil belt on the continents".
</P>
<P>
Professor Liu Tianyou, of China Geology University, points out
that, in keeping with the country's oil industry strategy of
"stabilizing the output in eastern oilfields while developing the
west", there will be greater exploration in Tibet.
</P>
<P>
"We are confident that Tibet will become an oil reserve base in
the 21st century," he noted.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971015.0076 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> President Kim's Son Appeals His Case </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SEOUL, October 15 (Xinhua) -- The second son of South Korean
President Kim Young-sam today appealed his case to the Seoul
District Court, two days after being sentenced to three years in
prison for bribery and tax evasion.
</P>
<P>
Through his lawyer, Kim Hyun-chul contended that it was
unreasonable for the court to find him guilty of evading taxes
which he was never asked to pay.
</P>
<P>
In Monday's ruling, the court ordered the junior Kim to pay
524.2 million won (about 580,000 U.S. dollars) in penalty for
receiving the same amounts of bribes from businessmen. He was also
fined 1.44 billion won (about 1.51 million dollars) for tax
evasion with the "political funds" he received from them.
</P>
<P>
It was the first case in South Korea, in which someone was
punished for failing to pay tax on political funds received.
</P>
<P>
But some taxation experts are skeptical about the court
judgement, and it is not clear whether the same principle will be
applied to other politicians against the background of the
sharpening political dispute on political funds.
</P>
<P>
It has been a common practice in South Korea for decades for
politicians to get funds from businessmen. 
</P>
</TEXT>
