<DOCNO> XIE19971015.0079 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> EU to Improve Aid Services </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, October 15 (Xinhua) -- The European Commission, the
European Union (EU)'s executive body, today decided to improve the
implementation of its aid to third world countries.
</P>
<P>
The Commission said it made the decision because its aid
programs currently had neither the visibility or the political and
geo-strategic impact they should have.
</P>
<P>
At the same time, programs and the number of countries in which
the Commission operates have increased while the Commission staff
has not grown in proportion to the workload.
</P>
<P>
The decision aims to simplify and rationalize the
implementation of the various programs, increase coherence and
transparency and make effective use of economies of scale.
</P>
<P>
By delegating technical tasks to a Joint Service, staff in the
external services would be able to better concentrate on the
primary tasks of aid.
</P>
<P>
The new structure was needed to enable the Commission to
effectively use an ever increasing aid budget amounting to almost
seven billion ECUs, or nine billion U.S. dollars, in 1997.
</P>
<P>
The proposal reconciles the need to improve co-ordination and
coherence between the wide range of programs, while maintaining
their flexibility to respond to individual countries' needs or
specific situations, such as urgent humanitarian aid. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
