<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Spain Trounces Dutch in Show of Skill </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, October 15 (Xinhua) -- Spain scored a 5-2 win over
the Netherlands, who squandered its many opportunities at goal, in
the men's hockey Champions' Trophy tournament Wednesday night in
Adelaide, Australia,
</P>
<P>
It was the first time in seven meetings that Spain defeated the
Netherlands.
</P>
<P>
Spain, whose captain Joaquin Malgosa played his 203rd match to
set a new Spanish hockey record, demonstrated brilliant defensive
skills and stick control under intense pressure from the current
Champions Trophy holder.
</P>
<P>
Despite two early Dutch attempts on goal, one from the field by
captain Stephan Veen and one penalty corner, Spain took the lead
with two goals in the first 11 minutes.
</P>
<P>
Javier Arnau scored twice for Spain who has six points from
three games.
</P>
<P>
Teun de Nooijer netted twice in three minutes before halftime
to briefly bring the Dutch back into the match.
</P>
<P>
The Netherlands failed to capitalise on any of its six penalty
corners during the second half.
</P>
<P>
European champion Germany moved into second place in the
standings on seven points, two behind unbeaten host Australia,
with a 3-1 win over Asian champion South Korea later Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Christoph Bechmann, Patrick Bellenbaum and Oliver Domke hit for
Germany, who has played one more game than their close rivals,
after Seong Tae Song gave South Korea an early lead. 
</P>
</TEXT>
