<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Exodus Triggered by Continuing ECOMOG-S.Leone </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
FREETOWN, October 15 (Xinhua) -- Nigerian forces in the west
African peace-keeping forces (ECOMOG) traded heavy artillery
overnight with the Sierra Leone army at Jui, 13 miles east of
Freetown, which resulted in an exodus of civilians today fleeing
into the capital.
</P>
<P>
Reports said Sierra Leone ferried a large number of troops to
the warfront in what is seen as a preparation for a pitched
battle with the Nigerians.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Abdul Bangura, a medical statistician at the main
hospital in Freetown told Xinhua that a total of about 30 cases
have so far been recorded as a result of clashes since last
Friday between government troops and ECOMOG forces.
</P>
<P>
According to Bangura, two unidentified corpses and 11 injured
victims were brought to the hospital on Friday, which included
six males, five females and four children under 10 years.
</P>
<P>
The victims sustained injuries when they were hit by fragments
and explosions in the nearby village of Wellington, he said.
</P>
<P>
Up to 19 cases were recorded from Saturday to Monday including
four deaths, two of whom, were children, Bangura said, adding
that no cases were reported on Tuesday and victims with minor
wounds have been treated and discharged.
</P>
<P>
Daniel Anderson, spokesman for the chief of staff at the
military headquarters, also gave what he called preliminary
figures of military casualties over the five-day period.
</P>
<P>
Two government soldiers and five members of the people's army
(former rebel combatants) died, he said.
</P>
<P>
A defense source disclosed that Captain Solomon Musa, chief
secretary of state (Prime Minister), survived a one-mile long
ambush in Grafton (near Jui) by Nigerian soldiers on Monday.
</P>
<P>
Sources said seven Nigerian soldiers were killed by
rocket-propelled grenades while the Sierra Leone side suffered no
casualties.
</P>
<P>
The sources said Musa and his team were visiting the war zone
when they ran into the ambush.
</P>
<P>
A military spokesman told Xinhua that government troops were
occupying all strategic points in Jui while the Nigerians were
either at a former medical college building or a slope
overlooking Jui.
</P>
<P>
"It is from these directions that they are shelling our
positions," the spokesman said.
</P>
<P>
"We have pushed back the Nigerians from the strategic Orogu
bridge and established a strong military presence on the main
road but we are not allowing traffic to go through yet as the
area is still unsafe," he said.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, reports from Kenema in the east said a Nigerian
airforce jet flew over the town at very low altitude on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
"The plane flew very low sending everyone into panic that it
was about to drop some bomb on the Brigade Headquarters but it
did not," said one resident. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
