<HEADLINE> Chinese Communist Party Waging War Against Extravagance </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, October 15 (Xinhua) -- All Communist Party of China
(CPC) and government departments will no longer be allowed to
purchase what are considered luxury consumer goods like cellular
phones or to take part in expensive recreational activities.
</P>
<P>
Wei Jianxing, a member of the Standing Committee of the
Political Bureau of the CPC Central Committee and secretary of the
CPC Central Commission for Disciplinary Inspection, made this
announcement at a national telephone conference today.
</P>
<P>
A new anti-corruption drive running through next Spring is
focusing on the rampant use of luxury items and extravagant
activities and reflects the essence of the recent 15th Party
Congress, Wei explained.
</P>
<P>
Although there has been some success in this since the last
tele-conference in May, it should not be overestated, Wei said,
calling the move a significant one by CPC Central Leadership and
one that will build a clean government.
</P>
<P>
Statistics from 11 provinces, municipalities, and autonomous
regions show that, by the end of September, local Party and
government offices had halted the following: construction work on
over 2,500 office buildings; 13,000 meetings of various kinds;
2,400 ceremonial services; and over 2,600 inspection activities.
</P>
<P>
Some 1,900 CPC members and government officials were
disciplined for being involved in extravagant activities paid for
with public funds, and a number of government-paid mobile phones
and house phones were removed with. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
