<HEADLINE> Chen Yan Wins Third Gold at National Games </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANGHAI, October 15 (Xinhua) -- Chen Yan, who broke the world
record in the women's 400-meter individual medley and won the 200m
freestyle early, captured her third gold medal from the women's
400m freestyle at the Eighth National Games on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Chen, 16, clocked the year-best of four minutes five seconds
for the gold, beating the previous Asian mark of 4:09.22 set by
Zhou Guanbin in 1994.
</P>
<P>
Chen was chased by Shanghai's Wang Luna in 4:07.86. Chen Hua
of Zhejiang finished third in 4:09.56.
</P>
<P>
"I feel very satisfied with the results," Chen said. "I have
trained in Beijing for a period of time before coming over here. I
guessed I have been in a superb form."
</P>
<P>
Yet, coach Han Bingyan warned her of serious challenges in the
World Swimming Championships to be staged in Perth, Australia,
next January.
</P>
<P>
"A few swimmers have proved their strong strength in the
European Championships and the Pan-Pacific Championships this
year," Han said. "And I believe Chen can win over them thourgh
hard training in the two months."
</P>
<P>
In the men's 100m freestyle, local favorite Jiang Chengji
showed his prowess by taking the gold in 50.62 seconds.
</P>
<P>
"It's not my favorite and it's rather hard for me to win the
gold. I stopped trainning for four months after returning from the
Atlanta Olympic Games," Jiang said.
</P>
<P>
Jiang, who swore at the opening ceremony on behalf of the
athletes, made the breakthrough for the Chinese men swimmers by
finishing the record fourth places both in 50m and 100m freestyles
in Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
"I had hoped to set a new Asian record," said the disappointed
Jiang. "And now I can only hope to challenge the foreign ace
swimmers in the World Championships."
</P>
<P>
He also denied the rumor on his retirment. "I will not quit
soon, but I will give up some events which are not suitable to my
conditions in the later international meets."
</P>
<P>
World record holder He Cihong of the Chinese Army was beaten to
second place by Zhen Yingjuan of Guangdong province in the women's
100m backstroke.
</P>
<P>
Zhen, 19, was timed at one minute and 0.22 second, only six
hundredths of a second shy of the world mark, which was set by He
in the Rome Swimming Worlds in 1994.
</P>
<P>
"I failed to keep my good form after the Rome Worlds," He
explained.
</P>
<P>
The men's 200m butterfly was taken by Xie Xufeng of Guangdong
in one minute and 59.07 second.
</P>
<P>
World record holder Le Jingyi anchored her win in the women's
4X100m freestyle relay with a time of three minutes and 42.30
seconds for the host Shanghai team, which also included Cai
Huijue, Zhu Yingwen and Wang Luna. 
</P>
</TEXT>
