<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Ukraine Accused of Defying Sanction on S. Leone </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, October 15 (Xinhua) -- Nigeria, whose troops are
leading the enforcement of sanctions against Sierra Leone, has
accused Ukraine of defying the United Nations order on the
severance of relations with the military junta by shipping goods
to Freetown.
</P>
<P>
One week after the U.N. Security Council announced oil, arms
and other sanctions against the junta, "Ukraine is shipping goods
and services to Freetown," Nigeria's defense spokesman, Col.
Godwin Ugbo, said here on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
These developments "are gradually showing that sanctions may
not work because of varied interests in the country," he said.
</P>
<P>
Both the sub-regional economic community known as ECOWAS and
the Security Council are imposing sanctions for an early
restoration of the legitimate government of President Ahmed Tejan
Kabbah ousted in a coup on May 25 this year.
</P>
<P>
According to reports, the junta in Sierra Leone hired
Ukrainian shipping companies to import fuel and food in the wake
of the ECOWAS economic embargo on the troubled country two months
ago.
</P>
<P>
The Expo Times, a Sierra Leone newspaper seen as the
mouthpiece of the junta, once quoted a Ukrainian captain as
saying "in the event that we are attacked while delivering food
and other essential supplies to Sierra Leone, we will prove to
Nigeria what military might we also have."
</P>
<P>
The west African peacekeeping forces led by Nigeria and
mandated by ECOWAS to enforce the embargo has warned it will
attack any violators of the embargo.
</P>
<P>
ECOWAS has also said if sanctions fail to press the junta out
of power, it will consider the use of force to oust the coupists.
</P>
<P>
Fighting between ECOWAS peacekeepers and the junta's army has
been reported over the past few days even after ECOWAS decided
last weekend to resume dialogue with the illegal regime in Sierra
Leone. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
