<BODY>
<HEADLINE> France Puts Troops in Africa on Alert </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, October 15 (Xinhua) -- France has put its troops
deployed in Gabon and Chad on alert for possible intervention in
the Congo Republic, French military sources said today.
</P>
<P>
This order was issued after the Congo Republic's oil city,
Pointe-Noire, fell to Angolan troops this morning.
</P>
<P>
Angolan troops entered the city earlier today from the Angolan
enclave of Cabinda and took control of the city, meeting little
resistance from Congolese government forces, reports reaching here
said.
</P>
<P>
"The situation is confusing in Pointe-Noire... France has put
into place all the means for ensuring a possible evacuation of all
the French nationals if the situation calls for it," said Foreign
Ministry spokesman Jacques Rummelhardt.
</P>
<P>
French military sources said that if necessary, French troops
will evacuate about 1,600 French nationals, now in Pointe-Noire,
to Libreville, the capital of Gabon.
</P>
<P>
"The situation is now very very critical. The Angolan troops
entered (Pointe-Noire) very early... around 6:30 (5:30 GMT). The
city is entirely occupied and submitted to looting," the French
consular in Pointe-Noire, Andre Querton, told French television
reporters.
</P>
<P>
The French Foreign Ministry set up a crisis team and opened a
telephone service for relatives of the French nationals trapped in
Pointe-Noire.
</P>
<P>
However, the French oil group Elf-Aquitaine, which has a branch
in Pointe-Noire, said earlier today that the situation was calm.
</P>
</TEXT>
