<DOCNO> XIE19971015.0091 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Backgrounder: ASEAN Free Trade Area in Progress </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SUBANG JAYA, Malaysia, October 15 (Xinhua) -- The 11th Council
Meeting of the ASEAN Free Trade Area (AFTA) was held here today
with ASEAN member countries agreeing to speed up the schedule and
tariff cuts for the AFTA.
</P>
<P>
All the nine ASEAN members -- Brunei, Indonesia, Laos,
Malaysia, Myanmar, the Philippines, Singapore, Thailand and
Vietnam -- reaffirmed at the one-day meeting their commitment to
realizing the AFTA by the year 2003 or earlier.
</P>
<P>
The AFTA was mooted in 1992 with an objective to create an
ambitious single market within 15 years beginning from January
1993, to enhance ASEAN's position as a competitive production base
geared towards servicing the global market.
</P>
<P>
To implement the AFTA concept, the Common Effective
Preferential Tariff (CEPT) scheme was launched on January 1, 1993.
Since then, much progress has been made towards that direction.
</P>
<P>
The deadline for realizing the AFTA has been moved up from the
year 2008 fixed originally to the year 2003 when import taxes must
be no more than 5.0 percent.
</P>
<P>
Some 93 percent or 40,755 tariff lines of the original six
ASEAN members -- Brunei, Indonesia, Malaysia, the Philippines,
Singapore and Thailand -- are included in the inclusion list for
CEPT concessions.
</P>
<P>
As for new members, a grace period has been given for each of
them to join the AFTA. Vietnam, which joined ASEAN in 1995, has
been given a grace period until 2006 to join AFTA while Laos and
Myanmar, which joined ASEAN in July 1997, are allowed until 2008
to complete cutting import taxes to an average five percent or
less.
</P>
<P>
An encouraging sign in the creation of AFTA is that over 85
percent of intra-ASEAN trade is already at between zero and five
percent under the CEPT scheme.
</P>
<P>
Regulations contained in the CEPT scheme clearly spell out
commitments to tariff reduction and "what countries can or cannot
do".
</P>
<P>
Under the rules, member countries can exclude products from the
CEPT scheme, for the protection of their national security, human,
animal, or plant life.
</P>
<P>
There are goods that need to have preferences, or protection,
but there is an avenue for them under the temporary exclusion list
(TEL), or even the "sensitive" or "highly sensitive lists" such as
rice and sugar. Eventually, they have to be brought under the TEL
and thereafter under the CEPT scheme.
</P>
<P>
The result is that some countries, such as Indonesia and the
Philippines, have more items on the "exclusion list", a list which
makes the goods ineligible for tariff reduction. Others, such as
newcomers Myanmar and Laos, need not satisfy the tariff targets
until nine years later.
</P>
<P>
The inclusion of unprocessed farm products in the tariff
reduction scheme has been a thorny issue for ASEAN.
</P>
<P>
To complement the region's AFTA scheme, ASEAN members decided
last year to implement the ASEAN Investment Area (AIA), details of
which are expected to be finalized by the end of 1998.
</P>
<P>
The AIA seeks to promote ASEAN as a single investment region.
Through it, ASEAN would strive to make the region a more
attractive location for foreign direct investment by reducing
barriers to the free flow of capital and the adoption of more
transparent rules.
</P>
<P>
The fact that ASEAN, one of the world's fastest growing
regions, sits right in the middle of the Asia-Pacific region, the
hottest investment destination in the world today, has made it the
focus of attention. Its market potential of some 500 million
people is indeed attractive.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
