<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Family Planning Is Crucial to China's Development </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, October 15 (Xinhua) -- China's one-child policy is
expected to have a far-reaching influence on the country's
sustainable development, experts said at the on-going 23rd
International Union for the Scientific Study of Population's
General Population Conference in Beijing.
</P>
<P>
They held that China must persist in its population controls to
ease the pressure of its already immense population on the
environment and limited resources.
</P>
<P>
Sustainable development means development achieved without
making conditions worse for later generations, according to Wang
Qiming, an official with the national center of the 21st Century
Agenda.
</P>
<P>
Although the rate of population growth in China is falling, the
number of new births remains large, Wang noted. By the end of
1996, China had 1.22 billion people, 22 percent of the world's
total. Each year, about 21 million babies are born, and the net
population increase is about 13 million.
</P>
<P>
If China does not control its population growth, deterioration
of the environment is inevitable, said Lu Yu of the Shandong
Academy of Social Science.
</P>
<P>
"This would threaten sustainable development and the basic
living condition of the Chinese people," he noted.
</P>
<P>
China's one child policy is estimated to have reduced the
population by 300 million.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
