<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Seoul's Share Prices Dip to Five Year Low </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SEOUL, October 15 (Xinhua) -- Share prices on the South Korean
stock market plummeted to nearly 600 points today, to the lowest
level in five years, as the cash-strapped Ssangbangwool Group
applied for court mediation.
</P>
<P>
The Korea Stock Price Index (KOSPI) dropped a hefty 15.94
points to close the day at 604.74 points, two days after the
government announced a set of bourse buoyancy measures.
</P>
<P>
The index marked the lowest level since October 28, 1992 when
it stood at 585.34.
</P>
<P>
Ssangbangwool's application for court mediation chilled
investors' sentiments, prompting a widespread selling-spree on the
stock market.
</P>
<P>
Panic fed rumors of imminent bankruptcies of numerous other
large business groups, which were reportedly suffering an acute
shortage of funds over the past few months.
</P>
<P>
Nearly all sectors fell victims to today's drop, with firms
rumored to be suffering from cash-flow problems experiencing
considerable drops in their share prices, said bourse analysts.
</P>
</TEXT>
