<DOCNO> XIE19971015.0096 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Intra-ASEAN Trade Grows Fast </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SUBANG JAYA, Malaysia, October 15 (Xinhua) -- Intra-ASEAN trade
grew at more than twice the rate of about 3.7 percent the world
merchandise export enjoyed from 1995 to 1996, it was officially
announced here today.
</P>
<P>
According to a statement issued at the end of the one-day ASEAN
(Association of Southeast Asian Nations) Free Trade Area (AFTA)
council meeting here, total ASEAN exports expanded from 296.7
billion U.S. dollars in 1995 to 323.4 billion dollars in 1996,
increasing by 8.99 percent.
</P>
<P>
As a result of the successful implementation of the AFTA's
Common Effective Preferential Tariff (CEPT) scheme, Intra-ASEAN
trade continued to expand much faster than the member countries'
total trade.
</P>
<P>
Statistics show that Intra-ASEAN exports grew by 13.4 percent
from 68.7 billion U.S. dollars in 1995 to 77.8 billion U.S.
dollars in 1996.
</P>
<P>
Intra-ASEAN exports of CEPT products grew by 11.3 percent from
56.3 billion U.S. dollars in 1995 to 62.6 billion U.S. dollars in
1996.
</P>
<P>
ASEAN's total exports grew from 228 billion U.S. dollars to
245.6 billion dollars, rising 7.7 percent.
</P>
<P>
This was double the growth of world trade and showed ASEAN's
strong fundamentals, it said.
</P>
<P>
The statement said the AFTA Council endorsed the CEPT packages
submitted by the new ASEAN members, Laos and Myanmar, which joined
ASEAN in July.
</P>
<P>
The council also examined the growth of intra-ASEAN trade and
strengthened the CEPT agreement by making emergency provisions
consistent with the World Trade Organization and examined the
progress in eliminating non-tariff barriers and harmonizing
customs.
</P>
<P>
Ministers at the council meeting agreed that the CEPT package
would be implemented by member countries in the coming year, and
the 1998 package would be finalized by November 15, 1997.
</P>
<P>
On CEPT tariff rate, the statement said that the average CEPT
tariff rate of products in the inclusion list had fallen to 6.38
percent in 1997 from about 12.76 percent in 1993 at the start of
the tariff reduction program and is scheduled to fall to 2.55
percent by the year 2003.
</P>
<P>
The council agreed that trade barriers, including bureaucratic
and administrative barriers and delays in decision etc., should be
eliminated to support the AFTA process.
</P>
<P>
ASEAN groups Laos, Myanmar, Vietnam, Brunei, Indonesia,
Malaysia, the Philippines, Singapore and Thailand. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
