<HEADLINE> Indian Industry Shows Signs of Recovery </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, October 15 (Xinhua) -- India's industry has started
to show signs of recovery with improved performance of the
manufacturing and electricity sectors during the first four months
of the current fiscal year, the Press Trust of India said today.
</P>
<P>
According to the latest quick estimates of the Index of
Industrial Production (IIP) released here today by the Central
Statistical Organization, industrial production grew by 6.4
percent in April-July compared with 5.2 percent in the first
quarter of the current fiscal year (from April 1997 to March
1998).
</P>
<P>
The manufacturing sector staged the most remarkable recovery
particularly in the month of July with a growth rate of 9.1
percent as against a mere 3.0 percent in the previous month.
</P>
<P>
However, the overall performance of a 6.4 percent growth
registered in April-July remained relatively poor compared with
10.5 percent in the same period of the previous fiscal year.
</P>
<P>
The official figures were released barely a day after Prime
Minister Inder Kumar Gujral's Tuesday meeting with manufacturing
industries to find ways out of the sustained industrial slowdown.
</P>
<P>
During the one-day meeting, the government promised to announce
a series of measures to spur the economy within a week. 
</P>
</TEXT>
