<HEADLINE> China's National Library Celebrates 10th Anniversary </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, October 15 (Xinhua) -- Beijing Library, the fifth
largest in the world, celebrated its 10th anniversary today.
</P>
<P>
Although the current building it occupies in northwest Beijing
was built in 1987, scholars say that the library's history
actually goes back to 1912.
</P>
<P>
The library holds 20 million books, including two million rare
books, and 30,000 tortoise shells and animal bones with the
earliest known examples of Chinese characters.
</P>
<P>
The library's curator Ren Jiyu, a famous philosopher and
historian, said that the library has contributed a lot to China's
economic and cultural progress, and "We will bring a modernized
National Library into the 21st century."
</P>
<P>
Jiang Zemin, Li Peng, Qiao Shi, Li Ruihuan and Li Lanqing have
written congratulatory notes for the event. President Jiang
wrote: "Protect the heritage of civilization, develop information
resources to serve the reforms and opening up, and let Beijing
Library play its role in promoting material progress and ethical
and cultural progress ."
</P>
<P>
Premier Li Peng wrote: "Explore the treasure house of
knowledge, collect information of the times, and speed up the
moderization of Beijing Library."
</P>
<P>
The library now has 1,500 staff members and has started
providing services on the Internet.  
</P>
</TEXT>
