<DOCNO> XIE19971015.0104 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Has To Confront Aging Challenge in Next Century </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, October 15 (Xinhua) -- Demographers at an
international conference on population in Beijing say that China
needs to improve its social security system while developing its
economy in the next two decades to meet the aging challenge of the
next century.
</P>
<P>
Experts predict that the proportion of children in China will
continue to drop while the proportion of elderly begins to
increase in the 1982-2025 period.
</P>
<P>
Zhang Wenfan, director of the China National Aging Committee,
explains that up to the 2030s, the proportion of working people in
the total population will remain above 60 percent and the annual
increase of six million provides good labor sources for economic
growth.
</P>
<P>
China has had a sharp drop in fertility since it started the
one-child policy in 1980, and experts predict that China will
become an aging society at the end of this century. The number of
people above 60 will increase to 130 million by then, 10 percent
of the population, then to 280 million in 2025, and to about 400
million in 2050, amounting to more than a quarter of the
population.
</P>
<P>
Xiong Bijun, of the Chinese Social Science Academy, says that
China is aging faster than its economy is growing as a result of
family planning. He explains that developed countries normally
encounter this challenge during periods of economic prosperity.
</P>
<P>
Xiong predicts that this imbalance will remain for quite a long
period of time.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971015.0105 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> EU to Promote Combined Heat, Power Generation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, October 15 (Xinhua) -- The European Commission, the
European Union (EU)'s executive body, today accepted a proposal on
the promotion of combined heat and power generation (CHP).
</P>
<P>
The proposal, adopted at the initiative of Christos Papoutsis,
EU commissioner responsible for energy, suggests a strategy to
facilitate CHP development and remove barriers to its penetration
in the European market.
</P>
<P>
It was cited as an energy-saving and environmentally friendly
system of heat and power production.
</P>
<P>
The strategy aims to establish the actions and policies
required at EU level to ensure that CHP benefits are exploited by
a significant penetration in gross electricity generation in the
EU by 2010.
</P>
<P>
"The strategy we propose is another example of our
determination to promote rational use of our energy resources and
thus significantly reduce greenhouse gas emissions," Papoutsis
said.
</P>
<P>
The CHP system is an efficient way of exploiting all the
useful energy within a fuel -- oil, gas and coal. A CHP plant can
convert 85 to 90 percent of the energy content of the fuel. Only
30 to 40 percent of energy is converted to useful energy in a
conventional way. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971015.0106 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-15 13:35 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Egypt Produces 55 Percent of Wheat Needs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, October 12 (Xinhua) -- Egypt's gross wheat production
reached 6 million tonnes in 1996 to cover 55 percent of the need of
the nation, a net wheat importer, Minister of Agriculture Youssef
Wali said today.
</P>
<P>
This year's output is expected 3.3 percent higher to reach 6.2
million tonnes and more than double the production in the
mid-1980s, he said in an address to a symposium on "French wheat
and its uses," which opened here today.
</P>
<P>
But this amount would still leave a large supply shortfall in a
country of 62 million people with an annual per capita wheat
consumption of 200 kilograms.
</P>
<P>
As the top importer of vegetarian products from Europe, Egypt
is working to narrow the gap between its needs and actual yield of
wheat through application of high-tech methods and increasing the
cultivated plot, Wali said.
</P>
<P>
Egypt, the biggest importer of wheat in the world, imports
one billion U.S. dollars of American wheat annually to fill the
domestic shortfall.
</P>
<P>
Besides, it has been allocating 3 billion pounds (883.4 million
dollars) every year to provide subsidized cheap wheat bread,
which is the most important staple food of common Egyptians.
</P>
<P>
The government said it is expected to realize 75 percent
self-sufficiency in wheat production three years from now, while
the Food and Agriculture Organization predicted that Egypt will be
totally self-sufficient in wheat in five years.
</P>
<P>
Today's symposium surveyed the optimal utilization of the grain
and possible cooperation between wheat farmers in Egypt and
France, which turned from the ranks of wheat-importers to the
world fifth largest exporter. 
</P>
</TEXT>
