<HEADLINE> Japan to Discuss Establishment of Liaison Office in DPRK </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO, October 15 (Xinhua) -- The Japanese government will
begin talks with the three ruling parties on establishing liaison
offices with the Democratic People's Republic of Korea (DPRK),
Kyodo news service reported today.
</P>
<P>
Earlier, the ruling Liberal Democratic Party (LDP) and its two
non-cabinet allies -- the Social Democratic Party (SDP) and New
Party Sakigake, asked the government to set up a formal channel
between Japan and the DPRK to discuss bilateral issues.
</P>
<P>
The request was made by executives of the three parties during
a meeting with Prime Minister Ryutaro Hashimoto and other top
government officials.
</P>
<P>
Chief Cabinet Secretary Kanezo Muraoka told an afternoon Press
conference that the government will further discuss the call with
the ruling party.
</P>
<P>
The proposed liaison offices are intended as a channel for
dialogues between Japan and the DPRK prior to normalization of
diplomatic relations, a government source told Kyodo.
</P>
<P>
The two countries, which have no diplomatic ties, agreed in
August to resume negotiations on normalizing relations. 
</P>
