<HEADLINE> Mideast Gas Development Has Rosy Future </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, October 15 (Xinhua) -- The Mideast plans to invest
tens of billions of US dollars in its proven natural gas
resources.
</P>
<P>
Scientists at the 15th World Petroleum Congress in Beijing say
that gas deposits there account for about a third of the world's
total, but there is still exploration to be done and output is
only a fifteenth of the world's total.
</P>
<P>
Iran is the largest producer of natural gas in the region, with
2.3 billion cubic meters in deposits, or 46.5 percent of the
area's total and 15 percent of the world's, making it 2nd after
Russia.
</P>
<P>
On September 28, France's Total signed a two-billion-US-dollar
natural gas agreement with Iran, ignoring the U.S.'s sanctions
against Iran, to help Iran develop natural gas in the Persian Gulf.
</P>
<P>
Qatar reached a 25-year agreement with a Japanese power company
earlier this year to provide six million tons of liquefied natural
gas every year to the company. Last year, it started to supply the
United States with 57,000 tons of liquefied natural gas. Another
source says that Qatar will export liquefied natural gas to Spain
from November of this year to the end of 1998. This is regarded as
the first time the country has been successful in marketing gas in
Europe.
</P>
<P>
Yemen and four foreign oil companies started a natural gas
development corporation in March, while Egypt has been giving
priority to oil and gas resources. A total of seven US companies,
nine European companies, and 21 enterprises from other countries
are involved in oil and gas exploration in the country. Since
early last year, 32 oil and gas fields have been discovered.
</P>
<P>
In addition, Iraq, which is suffering from UN imposed
sanctions, is also choosing appropriate partners for exporting
natural gas.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971015.0113 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Tianjin Expands Economic Cooperation with Overseas Firms </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TIANJIN, October 15 (Xinhua) -- Tianjin, a major port city in
north China, has witnessed rapid growth in economic and
trade cooperation with overseas firms over the past five years.
</P>
<P>
Since 1993, the city has approved 8,464 foreign-funded
enterprises involving investments of some 6.5 billion US dollars,
respectively 3.2-fold and 9.5-fold increases on the 1979-1992 period.
</P>
<P>
The city's 1996 import and export volume hit 8.3 billion US
dollars, a 2.5-fold rise on 1992. The export volume grew by
24.7 percent to slightly over four billion US dollars and
accounted for more than 30 percent of the city's gross domestic
product (GDP).
</P>
<P>
Last year, Tianjin signed 1,320 contracts for labor services
and engineering projects with overseas firms, with total
contracted capital totaling 158 million US dollars.
</P>
<P>
The city hosted 233,300 foreign tourists in 1996, with total
profits of 152 million US dollars, representing a three-fold rise
on 1992. 
</P>
</TEXT>
