<HEADLINE> Singapore to Hold Next East Asia Economic Summit </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, October 15 (Xinhua) -- Singapore will play host to
the 7th East Asia Economic Summit, which will be held on October
19 next year, announced World Economic Forum Managing Director
Claude Smadja here today at the closing session of the '97 East
Asia Economic Summit.
</P>
<P>
He also announced that the World Economic Forum is also
planning an East Asia-Pacific Economic Summit to be held in
Melbourne of Australia in the year 2000 in conjunction with the
Olympic Games, and all participants of the Summit will have the
opportunity to attend the opening ceremony of the Games.
</P>
<P>
The '97 East Asia Economic Summit concluded its three-day
sessions here this evening after discussing a broad spectrum of
regional economic, political and social issues.
</P>
<P>
The currency turbulence that hit some Southeast Asia countries
was again addressed at the discussions as one of the premier
topics, and most of the participants, as well as all the keynote
speakers, held the view that these countries will recover from
this shock.
</P>
<P>
Participants also discussed the scenarios for ensuring growth
and stability in East Asia.
</P>
<P>
A whole day of the Summit was devoted to discussions on key
prospects for the Chinese economy, with newly established Chinese
municipality Chongqing and Hainan Province on top of the topics.
</P>
<P>
The Summit also touched upon such issues as the
China-U.S.-Japan relationships, structural reforms, environment
challenge and trade agenda between Europe, East Asia and North
America.
</P>
<P>
Many participants described the Summit as very successful and
very useful.  
</P>
