<HEADLINE> China To Look For Oil In Venezuela </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, October 15 (Xinhua) -- China has won a bid for oil
exploration in two blocks in Venezuela in the third round of
bidding there, according to Zeng Xingqiu, deputy director of the
China National Petroleum Corporation's Department of International
Co-operation.
</P>
<P>
Zeng told Xinhua today that the bid was 358 million US dollars
for a 20-year contract on a 39 sq km area. The bid was CNPC's
largest ever overseas and could be a sign of recognition of CNPC's
technology and strength by the international petroleum industry.
</P>
<P>
There were more than 90 companies bidding, including most major
ones. Venezuela is one of the world's major oil-producing
countries and has an estimated recoverable reserves of 10.15
billion tons, and produced 170 million tons of crude oil last year.
</P>
<P>
Zeng says that China is both a big oil producer and a big
consumer. "The rich oil reserves and its opening process in
Venezuela create favorable conditions for China to enter the
marketplace," he said, and there is great potential for
co-operation.
</P>
<P>
The two countries signed a petroleum co-operation agreement
during Chinese Premier Li Peng's Venezuela visit last
November. The petroleum industries in the two country have done
"fruitful work" since then in implementing the agreement, he noted.
</P>
<P>
Zeng said that the Chinese government has an oil development
strategy on developing both domestic and overseas resources and,
with this active attitude, China and Venezuela will have bright
prospects for petroleum cooperation. 
</P>
</TEXT>
