<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Currency Crisis Prompts ASEAN to Realize Free Trade </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SUBANG JAYA, Malaysia, October 15 (Xinhua) -- Economic
ministers of the Association of Southeast Asian Nations (ASEAN)
today agreed that the recent currency crisis in the region has
made the implementation of the ASEAN Free Trade Area (AFTA) more
important for the grouping.
</P>
<P>
The agreement was reached at the 11th AFTA Council Meeting held
here today which reviewed progress in the implementation of the
Common Effective Preferential Tariff, the main operating mechanism
for AFTA, announced Malaysian International Trade and Industry
Minister Rafidah Aziz at a joint press conference at the end of
the council meeting.
</P>
<P>
Ministers from all the nine ASEAN member countries -- Brunei,
Indonesia, Laos, Malaysia, Myanmar, the Philippines, Singapore,
Thailand and Vietnam -- reaffirmed their commitment to realizing
AFTA by the year 2003 or earlier.
</P>
<P>
They also agreed that the recent depreciation of the region's
currencies had created favorable conditions for further expanding
ASEAN exports, both within and outside the region.
</P>
<P>
It has created a window of opportunities for the region's
industries to enter a period of consolidation and to make
necessary adjustments to increase their competitiveness in the
long run, they said.
</P>
<P>
The ministers also agreed that transient economic and exchange
rate fluctuations experienced by some member countries recently
would not affect the sound underlying economic fundamentals of the
region's economies.
</P>
<P>
They shared the view that the implementation of AFTA would
facilitate long-term adjustments of their economies to enhance
ASEAN's resilience towards external volatility.
</P>
<P>
They expressed optimism on the long-term economic prospects of
the region as well as its attractiveness to foreign direct
investment. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
