<HEADLINE> Three Gorges Resettlement Program Well under Way </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, October 15 (Xinhua) -- A total of 82,300 residents
had moved out of the Three Gorges Reservoir area by the end of
September.
</P>
<P>
The figure accounts for 10 percent of the total number of the
people scheduled for resettlement for construction of Three Gorges
Project in the middle reaches of the Yangtze River. The
resettlement effort will serve as a basic guarantee for damming of
the main course of the river on November 8, according to
information released today by the Bureau of Resettlement and
Development under the State Council's Three Gorges Project
Construction Committee.
</P>
<P>
Houses and apartments, with a combined floor space of 3.35
million square meters, already built account for some 10 percent
of the total floor space of housing scheduled for construction.
</P>
<P>
Resettlement for the Three Gorges project commenced in 1993,
with 8.575 billion yuan spent for related efforts over the past
five years.
</P>
<P>
Regions outside the Three Gorges Area have played an active
role in helping with the resettlement effort. And organizations
from outside the Three Gorges area had provided 1.847 billion yuan
to fund some 829 aid projects by the end of 1996.
</P>
<P>
Bureau Spokesman Lu Chun said damming the main course of the
Yangtze will symbolize the end of first-phase resettlement. He
noted that the second phase will be even more difficult.
</P>
<P>
Lu said between 300,000-400,000 people will be relocated over
the next five years, with 70,000-80,000 residents resettled
annually equalling the total for the past five years.
</P>
<P>
In addition, a number of large towns will be moved to new areas.
</P>
<P>
Lu pledged that the bureau will extend still greater efforts to
ensure the fulfilment of goals for second stage resettlement.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
