<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-15 12:16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 3 Condemned to Death for Reviving Egypt's Jihad </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, October 15 (Xinhua) -- Three men were sentenced to death
today for trying to revive the ultra-radical group Al-Jihad
Organization during a massive trial of suspected Muslim militants
by an Egyptian military court.
</P>
<P>
Two of the condemned are still at large. Leaders of the
outlawed Jihad (holy war) Organization, live abroad and take a
non-conciliatory stance despite the unilateral promises by some
other armed groups in Egypt to abandon violence against the
government.
</P>
<P>
Also standing trial at the Egyptian Higher Military Court this
morning were 84 suspected Muslim militants involved in the
organization, 31 of them were acquited afterwards.
</P>
<P>
The court issued life sentences against two of the defendants
and passed imprisonment terms ranging from three to 15 years on 48
defendants. All the prison sentences are with hard labor.
</P>
<P>
Two other defendants were sentenced to serve two years in
prison and a third was fined 50 Egyptian pounds (about 14.7
U.S. dollars).
</P>
<P>
The trial came exactly a month after Egypt's single largest
trial of Muslim extremists when 98 Muslims, including lawyers,
students and engineers and four women went on trial on charges of
attempting to topple Egypt's secular government by unleashing a
wave of terror.
</P>
<P>
Four were sentenced to death by hanging on conviction of
staging major terrorist attacks. They were allegedly members of
the outlawed Al-Gama'a Al-Islamiya, or the Islamic Group that
launched a violent campaign since 1992 to install a strict Islamic
rule. More than 1,200 people have been killed in the violence.
</P>
<P>
Sixty-eight got sentences ranging from one year to life
imprisonment and 26 others were acquited.
</P>
<P>
According to an anti-terrorism law, membership of outlawed
militants groups is punishable by death, but the punishment has
never been imposed. So far, 66 extremists have been executed but
for crimes such as murder or armed attacks on banks.
</P>
<P>
Suspected Islamic militants began to be tried in military
courts in 1993. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
