<DOCNO> XIE19971015.0123 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Bangladesh to Buy Electricity from American Company </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, October 15 (Xinhua) -- Bangladesh has signed an
agreement with an American company to procure electricity for a
period of 15 years, national news agency BSS reported today.
</P>
<P>
The agreement was signed here Tuesday night between
Bangladesh's Power Development Board (PDB) and M/S Congeneration
(Bangladesh) PVT Ltd., a full subsidiary of the Smith
Congeneration International of the U.S.A.
</P>
<P>
Under the agreement, M/S Congeneration (Bangladesh) PVT Ltd.
will sell power to the PDB on mutually variable prices, BSS said,
adding that the American company will install and commission a
100-megawatt power plant at Haripur near the capital Dhaka.
</P>
<P>
This will be the first private sector venture between
Bangladesh and a foreign company to generate electricity under the
private sector policy of the government announced last year.
</P>
<P>
The agreement, based on the BOO (build-own-operate) cooperation
mode, will be implemented within 10 months of its signing. Efforts
are under way to advance the commissioning of the plant by April,
1998, the agency said.
</P>
<P>
The Smith Congeneration International will sell electricity
generated with liquid fuel to the PDB at the rate of 2.23 taka
(5.10 U.S. cents) per kilowatt hour (KWH) in the initial stage,
BSS quoted PDB sources as saying.
</P>
<P>
However, the rate will be reduced to 1.77 taka (4.16 U.S.
cents) per KWH in December 1998 when natural gas is available for
use as fuel for electricity generation, the sources said.
</P>
<P>
Four barge-mounted power plants each with a 100-megawatt
capacity are to be set up by the private sector in Bangladesh, the
PDB sources added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971015.0124 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Seeds Advance into Second Round in Squash Worlds </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, October (Xinhua) -- More seeds advanced when world
No.4 Sue Wright and No.6 Liz Irving edged their opponents in
Wednesday's first-round matches of the world women's squash
championships in Sydney, Australia.
</P>
<P>
Wright, 27, won in straight sets over Australian Tone Weeks
10-9, 9-3, 9-7 to join her compatriots Cassie Jackman, Jane Martin
and Linda Charman in the second round.
</P>
<P>
Ircing, who handled three-time world champion Michelle Martin
in last year's quarter-finals, ousted Naha Zein of Egypt 9-3, 9-6,
9-0.
</P>
<P>
In Wednesday's other matches, qualifier Narelle Tippett was
defeated 3-9, 9-6, 0-9, 7-9 by Philippa Beams of New Zealand, who
will face Wright in next round.
</P>
<P>
Irving's next rival will be South African Natalie Grainger, who
beat Austrian qualifier Pamela Pancis, 9-3, 9-3, 9-4. 
</P>
</TEXT>
