<HEADLINE> Sri Lankan President Condemns Colombo Blast </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
COLOMBO, October 15 (Xinhua) -- Sri Lankan President Chandrika
Kumaratunga today condemned the explosion of downtown Colombo and
stated her government will continue the peace process in the
nation.
</P>
<P>
"I strongly condemn the brutal bomb blast carried out in
Colombo this morning by some terrorist group," the president said
in a news release.
</P>
<P>
She said: "At a time when we have reached the point at which we
can resolve the present conflict and end the war, we should
realize that there are forces who are opposed to peace and the
development of the country."
</P>
<P>
The president expressed deep sympathy to the families and
friends of the victims of the incident.
</P>
<P>
"I wish to state categorically that we will not be disturbed
from our determination and commitment to bring peace to our
country," she added.
</P>
<P>
A powerful truck-bomb exploded in downtown Colombo at 7:10 a.m.
local time, killing at least five people and injuring 105. Among
the wounded are 29 foreigners.
</P>
<P>
Security forces have so far killed five LTTE rebels who were
believed to have conspired the incident. Search and clear
operation is still going on in a building hundreds of meters away
from the explosion scene.
</P>
<P>
An officer told Xinhua that seven to eight rebels were involved
in the blast.
</P>
<P>
Two military men were killed and one injured in the crossfire.
</P>
<P>
The Galadari Hotel, the Hilton Hotel, the Bank of Ceylon and
the twin-tower of the World Trade Center, which was opened by
President Chandrika Kumaratunga three days ago, were seriously
damaged. Several government buildings were also damaged.
</P>
<P>
The LTTE has been fighting a 14-year ethnic war with the
government for a separate state of their own in the north and east
of the country.  
</P>
</TEXT>
