<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-15 12:40 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Cyprus Issue Parties Urged to Refrain From </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NICOSIA, October 15 (Xinhua) -- Sweden today called upon all
parties involved in the Cyprus issue to refrain from actions
hampering efforts for a solution to the protracted Cyprus problem.
</P>
<P>
The call was made by Swedish Foreign Minister Lena
Hjelm-Wallen after her meetings here today with President Glafcos
Clerides and House of Representatives Speaker Spyros Kyprianou.
</P>
<P>
Hjelm-Wallen arrived here Tuesday for a three-day visit to
discuss with Cypriot officials the Cyprus problem and island's
accession to the European Union (EU).
</P>
<P>
Stressing the need for a solution to the Cyprus problem, which
she described as important to both the people of Cyprus and to
Europe, Hjelm-Wallen told reporters that "we have heard about
overflights and military actions. That is something we are
worried about. It can hamper the whole peace process."
</P>
<P>
The Greek navy and air forces took part in the five-day Greek
Cypriot National Guard's annual military exercises which ended
Tuesday. The Turkish jet fighters were reported to frequently
violate the Greece and Cyprus' airspace over the past two days.
</P>
<P>
Hjelm-Wallen urged all sides, both the Greek and Turkish
Cypriot communities on the island, as well as Greece and Turkey
to "refrain from military actions and work in a constructive way
toward a solution" to the protracted Cyprus problem.
</P>
<P>
Cyprus has been divided into Turkish Cypriot-controlled north
and Greek Cypriot-dominated south since 1974 when the island was
divided after Turkish troops invaded and took over the northern
third in the wake of a failed pro-Athens coup.
</P>
<P>
The Swedish minister suggested that Greece and Turkey consider
once again a moratorium of flights of their warplanes over Cyprus.
</P>
<P>
Referring to Cyprus' prospects to become an EU member before a
political solution was reached, Hjelm-Wallen said "we want to see
Cyprus in the EU but there must be a solution. The two should be
parallel."
</P>
<P>
She said she is unhappy with Ankara's threats of annexing the
northern part of the island if the EU proceeded with the
accession of Cyprus to the EU.
</P>
<P>
She also described as "not constructive" Turkey's role in the
U.N.-led direct talks between Clerides and Turkish Cypriot leader
Rauf Denktash in New York and Montreux, Switzerland, in July and
August.
</P>
<P>
The two rounds of direct talks ended in failure due to
Denktash's refusal of further negotiations unless the EU freezes
the plan to start accession talks with Cyprus in early 1998. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
