<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Fish Yield Increased Dramatically by Gender Change </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, October 15 (Xinhua) -- Chinese technicians have
increased the yield of the "mouth breeder" fish by transforming
its gender.
</P>
<P>
After a period of ingesting a kind of Chinese herb together
with fish fodder, female mouth breeders will undergo a sex change, which
increases an individual fish's weight by more than 200 grams, said
Qin Deshan, head of the Beijing Changping Aquatic Farm.
</P>
<P>
Beijing is an important base in northern China for breeding the
fish, which originated in the Nile River of Africa. The fish has
become widely accepted for consumption in China.
</P>
<P>
Qin said the gender-change technique was developed by
technicians at the aquatic farm. By adopting this method, their
fish yield has increased by 90,000 tons in nine months, which is
equal to the establishment of one and a half aquatic farms.
</P>
<P>
The female mouth breeder is a fertile fish, but its weight
averages only 100 grams in one year. The natural ratio of male
and female mouth breeders is 50-50. Using the gender-altering
technique, the ratio now is 80 males to 20 females.
</P>
<P>
In another development, scientists at the Beijing Aquatic Research
Institute have found another way to increase the yield by
developing a distant hybridization method to cause infertility in
female mouth breeder.
</P>
<P>
After four years of experimentation, they have narrowed the
type of mouth breeders to two species. Using this technique, about
90 percent of newlyborn mouth breeders at the institute are males.
</P>
<P>
Hu Yinong, a senior engineer at the institute, said the net
income of a one-hectare fish pond can be increased by 50
percent using this technique.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971015.0129 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Getting Oil Industry To Care About Environmental Protection </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, October 15 (Xinhua) -- A major topic at the World
Petroleum Congress, which is going on in Beijing, is how to get
environmentally-minded people to be confident in the future of the
petroleum industry.
</P>
<P>
Petroleum products for industrial use have become the major
source of energy in the world and oil and gas consumption in
developing countries is expected to surpass the amount of member
countries of the Organization for Economic Cooperation and
Development by early next century.
</P>
<P>
John Lemlin, general secretary of the International Petroleum
Industry and Environmental Conservation Association (IPIECA), says
that any attempt to restrict the production of petroleum and
natural gas before a suitable energy replacement for petroleum can
be found will have a disastrous effect on society.
</P>
<P>
However, oil and gas spilled while being transported and the
pollution caused by oil refineries and exhaust gas emissions from
cars and buses pose a serious threat to the environment.
</P>
<P>
Some international environmental protection organizations say
that their mission is to terminate petrochemical production
quickly and permanently.
</P>
<P>
So, oil companies' representatives and research institutes
agree that the key to dealing with the contradiction between oil
production and environmental protection lies in with the oil
industry itself, which should improve technology and increase
contacts with the public.
</P>
<P>
And, efforts have been made to get oil and natural gas at
deeper layers by the least destructive means, said one
expert. Engineers have developed an oil catamaran to prevent oil
leakage caused by marine accidents, and lead-free gasoline is now
widely used around the globe.
</P>
<P>
In spite of these developments, however, some research findings
have not been applied. And, people in the oil industry and the
public disagree about environmental protection needs. The former
claim that their disaster and pollution estimates are based on
scientific evidence, while the latter say they base everything on
their own concept of value.
</P>
<P>
The oil industry is reported to be co-operating with the
International Maritime Organization to work out an international
guideline on controlling oil pollution, and some in the industry
are working on guidelines for dumping waste.
</P>
<P>
Lemlin said the petroleum industry faces a challenge on how to
produce oil and gas in a moral way that is acceptable to mankind
and the environment, and he has appealed to the industry to take a
more active approach to change its image. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
