<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Indonesia Says IMF Team Won't Touch Amount Of Loans </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, October 15 (Xinhua) -- Indonesia said it will not
discuss the amount of loans it needs to tide over its currency
crisis at the meeting between the government and the International
Monetary Fund (IMF).
</P>
<P>
Minister/State Secretary Moerdiono said Tuesday night that at
the meeting the IMF officials were told about the country's plan
to overcome its financial crisis.
</P>
<P>
A team of the IMF and the World Bank arrived here Friday at the
invitation of the Indonesian government to discuss the country's
financial crisis. IMF officials and Indonesian officials started
discussion here Monday.
</P>
<P>
Earlier, Indonesia said it considered to seek long-term loans
from international financial institutions including the IMF to
help prevent its rupiah from further depreciation against the U.S.
dollar.
</P>
<P>
Officials said the rupiah has dropped 46 percent since the
beginning of this year.
</P>
<P>
The Indonesian government has instituted programs to resolve
the monetary crisis that hit the country since July, a step the
IMF would most likely want to know in detail, Moerdiono said.
</P>
<P>
"If they (IMF) have the capacity to help us, why don't we take
it?" he said.
</P>
<P>
Moerdiono said the government programs concern how to boost
non-oil/gas exports, how to stabilize the rupiah and how to
prevent businessmen from buying up the U.S. currency.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Indonesia's central bank intervened in the money
market Tuesday to bolster the rupiah, dealers said today.
</P>
<P>
The central bank bought the rupiah at 3,495 against the U.S.
dollar, apparently guarding the 3,500 barrier as offshore dollar
buying emerged in early trading, dealers said.
</P>
<P>
The intervention helped send the dollar down to the 3,450 level
before domestic purchase pushed the U.S. currency back up to the
3,470/80 level.
</P>
<P>
Dealers said some big buying from local operators pushed the
dollar up, breaking the 3,500 barrier up to a high of 3,510.
</P>
<P>
But it was unclear how much the central bank sold at the money
market.
</P>
<P>
Early this month the rupiah once dropped to 3,865 per dollar as
many local operators rushed for dollars to pay their debts.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
