<HEADLINE> Prices of Basic Commodities Up in Philippines </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, October 15 (Xinhua) -- Prices of basic commodities in
the Philippines has gone up 3 percent due to the depreciation of
the peso, the Department of Trade and Industry said today.
</P>
<P>
Pedro Moreno, chief of the prices monitoring team of the
department, said that sardines, powdered milk and coffee are among
the goods whose prices have the highest surge.
</P>
<P>
Moreno attributed the price hikes to the plunge of the peso,
which has devaluated 30 percent to today's 34.3 pesos per dollar
since the financial turmoil swept Southeast Asia in early July.
</P>
<P>
However, some economists said the fall of the peso and the hike
of prices were not fully reflected in inflation.
</P>
<P>
In the first nine months this year, the country's inflation
rate stood at an average of 4.7 percent, much lower than last
year's 8.4 percent. 
</P>
</TEXT>
