<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Nigeria Expects Higher Economic Growth in 1997 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, October 15 (Xinhua) -- Nigeria may record an economic
growth rate higher than last year's 3.21 percent in 1997 but may
not attain the target of 5.5 percent growth, a senior government
official said on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Minister of State for Finance, Alhaji Abu Gidado, made the
statement at a meeting of the National Council on Finance and
Economic Development in Katsina.
</P>
<P>
The minister of state said the rise of Nigeria's external
reserve to over seven billion U.S. Dollars by September is an
indication of growth.
</P>
<P>
On the other hand, the country's external debt fell from 32
billion Dollars in 1995 to 28 billion Dollars in 1996, thanks to
improved debt management, Gidado said.
</P>
<P>
For the 1996 and 1997 fiscal year, two billion Dollars had
been budgeted each year for debt repayment, he added.
</P>
<P>
The minister of state stated that the country's revenue
performance has also witnessed substantial improvement. He
predicted that the revenue from the Value Added Tax will increase
from last year's 29.2 billion Naira (about 356 million Dollars)
to about 35 billion Naira (about 427 million Dollars). 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
