<DOCNO> XIE19971015.0152 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Europs Less Interested in S. A.'s Black </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, October 15 (Xinhua) -- European investors, who
account for 52 percent of direct foreign investment in South
Africa, have low level of interest in black economic empowerment
opportunities, an Euro-Chamber survey disclosed.
</P>
<P>
The survey, quoted by "Business Report" today, said about 37
percent of respondents were not considering black empowerment, 35
percent were still considering it, 13 percent had already
implemented it and 15 percent were still in the process.
</P>
<P>
The survey was circulated to 600 companies of European
majority share-holding or origin operating in South Africa.
</P>
<P>
"European firms are moderately committed to affirmative
action. But to our surprise, there is very little interest in
black empowerment," said Johannesburg-based Euro-Chamber
consultant Anahid Harrison, adding that it was difficult to
explain the reason for the disinterest.
</P>
<P>
The affirmative action was proposed by the South African
government in a bid to promote black people's social position
following the abolition of apartheid in 1994.
</P>
<P>
Under the regulations concerned, a considerable percentage of
black people must be involved in all trades and professions in
the country.
</P>
<P>
Although general confidence had declined, more than 80 percent
of European investors were reportedly positive about South
Africa's economic situation and its prospects.
</P>
<P>
The survey showed that respondents were generally positive
about the political framework and the context for economic
policies in South Africa.
</P>
<P>
They believed that the South African government led by African
National Congress was showing consistency and commitment in its
economic policies, the survey said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
