<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Australian Stock Lost 4 Percent In Five Trading Days </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, October 15 (Xinhua) -- Despite a positive bond
market,
the Australian sharemarket fell again today after losing more than
4 percent of its value in the past five trading days.
</P>
<P>
Brokers and fund managers could not point to a definitive
reason for today's 8.3-point drop in the all ordinaries index
which fell to 2,653.7.
</P>
<P>
"I guess the major non-influence in the market today is that
the bond market is better yet equities are still down," said
broker Andrew Sekely of Intersuisse.
</P>
<P>
Don Hamson, an investment director at Westpac Investment
Management, said he could not explain the downward close, citing
rises in European and North American markets.
</P>
<P>
He said other factors could be the heavy falls in Hong Kong and
other Asian markets today, adding: "Asia has generally had a bad
day. But I would have thought it's not a big deal."
</P>
<P>
The all resources index was down 5.3 points at 1,313.5 and the
all industrials index was down 12.4 points at 4,357.8.
</P>
<P>
National turnover was 327.24 million shares traded with a value
of 909.18 million Australian dollars (668.24 million U.S.
dollars), and falls of 680 easily outnumbered rises of 427.
</P>
<P>
Among the resources majors, Rio Tinto was down 35.7 cents, WMC
was down 1.9 cents, and bellwether BHP was down two cents.
</P>
<P>
Over the past five trading days, brokers have cited a range of
reasons for the falls in the all ordinaries index, from
less-than-convincing fears of the 10th anniversary of the Black
Tuesday to more concrete explanations such as falls on Wall Street
and comments by U.S. Federal Reserve chief Alan Greenspan.
</P>
<P>
In the banking sector, National Australia Bank was down five
cents, ANZ Banking Group was down one cent, Commonwealth Bank was
down five and Westpac Banking Corp. was up two cents.
</P>
<P>
The gold index was down 2.6 points at 1,323.0, gold bullion
closed at 327.00 U.S. dollars an ounce, down 0.95 dollars on the
opening of 327.95.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
