<DOCNO> XIE19971015.0156 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Troops Invade Congolese Oil City From Angola </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, October 15 (Xinhua) -- Troops coming from the Angolan
enclave Cabinda invaded Pointe-Noire, the "oil capital" of the
Congo Republic, this morning and met little resistance from the
government troops loyal to President Pascal Lissouba.
</P>
<P>
A spokesman of the Democratic and Popular Forces (DPF) loyal to
former President Denis Sassou Nguesso said hours later in
Libreville, capital of Gabon, that the DPF forces had taken
Pointe-Noire.
</P>
<P>
Quoting reports from Belgian expatriates in Pointe-Noire, the
Belgian Defense Ministry confirmed that Pointe Noire had fallen
into the hand of Angolan troops.
</P>
<P>
However, Angola immediately denied that its troops had
penetrated into Congolese territory or had entered Pointe-Noire.
</P>
<P>
"Angola has not sent soldiers to Congo," said a spokesman of
the Angolan Foreign Ministry in Luanda on Wednesday morning.
</P>
<P>
Cabinda, which is an Angolan enclave which thrusts into Congo,
is less than 100 kilometers from Pointe Noire.
</P>
<P>
Agence France-Presse (AFP) quoted witnesses as saying that a
"column of armored vehicles arrived at Pointe-Noire at 6:00 a.m."
after crossing the border from the Angolan enclave of Cabinda.
</P>
<P>
Government forces did not make any serious resistance although
some cannon shots were fired in several parts of the city, the AFP
reported.
</P>
<P>
The origin of the forces invading Pointe Noire and their number
were not clear.
</P>
<P>
Fighting was still going on this morning in the Total market in
Bacongo between the DPF and the forces loyal to Prime Minister
Bernard Kolelas, who is allied with President Lissouba, said the
report.
</P>
<P>
Gabonese President Omar Bongo, the president of the
international committee of mediation for Congo Republic, today has
"invited" the warring sides of Congo to start a ceasefire from
mid-night of October 17. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
