<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Australian Dollar Dips on Pressure by Profit Taking </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, October 15 (Xinhua) -- The Australian dollar ended
lower today, pressured down by profit-taking by investors, with
traders suggesting it might have been overbought recently.
</P>
<P>
But traders said local exporter interest to buy the unit at the
lower end of the day's trading range had seen it supported to the
close of the local session.
</P>
<P>
The Australian dollar finished at 73.51 U.S. cents, down from
73.78 previously.
</P>
<P>
"There was a bit of a pass-the-parcel down to the 73.50 area
and under that there were some stops (sell orders) that went off,"
said St George Bank foreign exchange dealer Tim Gillis.
</P>
<P>
Citibank Australia senior dealer Geoff Last said the Australian
dollar had been over-bought during the past few days following
last week's stronger-than-expected jobs data. Yesterday it touched
74.15 U.S. cents.
</P>
<P>
Expectations are now growing in the market that the Reserve
Bank of Australia won't ease policy again in the short term.
</P>
<P>
But next week's third quarter inflation data are seen key to
supporting, or reversing, that outlook.
</P>
<P>
The figures from the Australian Bureau of Statistics are
expected to show inflation remained subdued in the period.
</P>
<P>
The Australian dollar closed at 89.23 from 89.53 against yen,
and at 1.2853 from 1.2926 against mark.  
</P>
</TEXT>
