<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Reduction of Negative Impact on Sino-US Cooperation Urged (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, October 15 (Xinhua) -- The United States should
introduce further steps to reduce the negative impact of
governmental conduct on Sino-US economic and technological
cooperation, according to Zhu Yuli, General Manager of Aviation
Industries of China (AIC).
</P>
<P>
Zhu expressed the hope that the United States will take the
advantage of the forthcoming US visit by Chinese President Jiang
Zemin to create a favorable political atmosphere for strengthening
mutually beneficial long-term cooperation in the realm of high
technology, including the aviation industry.
</P>
<P>
Speaking in an interview with Xinhua, Zhu said that President
Jiang's visit to US will mark a new stage in Sino-US relations. He
said China and the United States should further intensify and
extend overall economic and technological cooperation to suit the
new situation of the improving Sino-US political ties.
</P>
<P>
Zhu noted that the aviation industry is a high-tech and
strategic industry. Aviation industries in China and the US, he
added, have recorded major progress in the realm of
multi-patterned cooperation, with joint efforts covering
wide-ranging areas.
</P>
<P>
However, he also cited the latent capacity of cooperation in
the field. He said the main reason centers on US government
conduct which has limited possibilities for more extensive
cooperation between businesses.
</P>
<P>
Zhu expressed the hope that US political circles and businesses
will fully consider long-term interests when viewing the Chinese
market, and will "not let certain periods or events create
meaningless conflicts."
</P>
<P>
Wide-ranging Sino-US aviation cooperation currently involves
aircraft, engineers, mechanical installations, raw materials and
personnel training. Modes of cooperation include aircraft
assembling, and cooperative, subcontracted and joint manufacturing.
</P>
<P>
The largest Sino-US cooperative aviation project involves the
assembly and co-production of aircraft. Shanghai Airline
Industrial Company (SAIC), an AIC affiliate, has assembled MD-82
aircraft of the former McDonnel Douglas Co. since 1985. The
company delivered 35 MD-82 in 1994, including five aircraft for
companies in the United States. SAIC is currently co-producing 20
MD-90 aircraft, with the first shipment scheduled for delivery in
1998. The two contracts are valued at 1.7 billion US dollars.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971015.0161 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Reduction of Negative Impact on Sino-US Cooperation Urged (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Subcontracted production represents yet another important form
of cooperation. Several AIC affiliates, including aircraft
manufacturing companies in Chengdu, Xi'an and Shenyang, and the
Xi'an Aircraft Engine Co. have subcontracted with Boeing and
McDonnel Douglas. The Chinese companies have produced tail
sections for Boeing 737 and 757 aircraft, with related contracts
valued at closed to one billion US dollars.
</P>
<P>
Zhu said his company imports 100 million US dollars worth of
avionics equipment, machinery processing equipment, raw materials
and computers annually. They account for some 60 percent of the
nation's total imports of related products, according to Zhu.
</P>
<P>
He said China continues to seek new forms of cooperation with
the US aviation industry, and noted that aircraft engine companies
in Chengdu and Xi'an are currently cooperating with United
Technologies Corporation of the US.
</P>
<P>
Zhu pointed to the Boeing-McDonnel merger as "purely a domestic
affair involving the restructuring of US enterprises".
</P>
<P>
He said the merger will strengthen the competency of the two
largest aviation companies in the US, and stressed that it should
have no bearing on the normal development of Sino-US contracts.
</P>
<P>
China has had one of the world's fastest growing aviation
industries in recent years. Although the industry ranks at the
forefront in the world in terms of scale and equipment, its
technology remains relatively backward.
</P>
<P>
Zhu noted that strengthened ties between aviation industries in
China and the US will benefit the latter's economy and provide
better access to the former's vast market.
</P>
<P>
He said the fact that AIC, as one of the nation's largest
industrial enterprises, has been named as an experimental
enterprise to introduce shareholding system. This will provide an
excellent opportunity for the two countries to expand and
introduce new modes of cooperation, he added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
