<BODY>
<HEADLINE> ASEAN Faces Two Challenges, Expert Says </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, October 15 (Xinhua) -- The Association of Southeast
Asian Nations (ASEAN), which plays an influential role in
Southeast Asia, is faced with future political and strategic
challenges, an Indonesian expert said here today.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at a plenary session of the World Economic Forum's
Sixth East Asia Economic Summit held in the Hong Kong Convention
and Exhibition Center, Jusuf Wanandi, chairman of the Supervisory
Board of the Indonesian Center for Strategic and International
Studies, said regional peace has given its members for the first
time the chance to develop economically and to build nation and
state.
</P>
<P>
However, there are "many challenges to ASEAN's cooperation,
stature and influence in the future," he said, noting, "The most
important and basic challenge is whether ASEAN can adjust and
change in the face of these new challenges."
</P>
<P>
"The first challenge relates to the enlargement of ASEAN," he
said, adding that "the postponement of Cambodia's membership due
to domestic conflict, specifically due to the use of force by one
of the coalition parties to change the government, is the most
vivid example."
</P>
<P>
ASEAN, which was formed 30 years ago, now groups Brunei,
Indonesia, Malaysia, the Philippines, Singapore, Thailand,
Vietnam, Laos and Myanmar. The entry of Cambodia, which ASEAN had
agreed to admit together with Laos and Myanmar earlier this year,
was later deferred owing to the situation in the country.
</P>
<P>
"Another important challenge is the increased participation of
ASEAN non-official organizations and peoples in shaping ASEAN's
future cooperation," Wanandi said.
</P>
<P>
He pointed out that since no more wars are expected to break
out among its members, ASEAN may cease to be taken seriously by
its members.
</P>
<P>
"Only with greater support, participation and attention by its
people as well as its non-governmental organizations and leaders,
can ASEAN remain relevant in the future and become stronger and
more cohesive to face its future challenges in Southeast Asia," he
added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
