<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Enhancing Economic Competitiveness Is HK's Top Priority </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, October 15 (Xinhua) -- Enhancing economic
competitiveness is a top priority for post-handover Hong Kong,
figures from media, commercial and political sectors said here
today on a panel discussion.
</P>
<P>
The panel discussion was held on the last day of the East Asia
Economic Summit, organized by the World Economic Forum, to review
the first 100 days of the Special Administrative Region (SAR) and
look beyond them.
</P>
<P>
Three speakers were Urban Lehner, executive editor of Dow Jones
Asia, Hong Kong, C.Y. Leung, member of both the SAR Executive
Council and Provisional Legislative Council (PLC), and James Tien,
chairman of Hong Kong General Chamber of Commerce and also a PLC
member.
</P>
<P>
Education was universally mentioned by them as critical to
improving competitiveness.
</P>
<P>
As Lehner put it, a higher percentage of GDP should be
allocated to education, while Tien stressed that the quality of
teachers should be paid much more attention to.
</P>
<P>
Hong Kong ranked the third this year for the third consecutive
year in global economic competitiveness, after the United States
and Singapore, according to an annual report compiled by a
world-renowned research institute based in Switzerland.
</P>
<P>
Commenting the first 100 days of SAR, the three speakers agreed
that it has enjoyed an extraordinary successful start, with the
life which Hong Kong people accustomed to exactly unchanged.
</P>
<P>
On press freedom, they shared the view that there has been no
problem so far.
</P>
<P>
"Press freedom is guaranteed by the Basic Law," Leung said,
adding that as far as he knows, reporters have not been told to
write this or that story.
</P>
<P>
"There has been no instance of any pressure put on the media
for them to change," Lehner said.
</P>
<P>
Lehner also pointed out that demonstrations, which constitute
part of Hong Kong culture, continue after July 1, while no
People's Liberation Army soldiers are seen on the streets.
</P>
<P>
The editor told the discussion that the confidence level of
local community has been "very high" with their Chief Executive
Tung Chee Hwa enjoying popularity.
</P>
<P>
Only tourism has been frustrated after the handover, Lehner
said, attributing the depressing situation to the sharp decline in
Japan tourist arrivals since too many came to Hong Kong during a
couple of months leading to the handover. The currency devaluation
in Southeast Asia, another short-haul market of Hong Kong, as well
as the rainy weather this summer, should also be blamed, he added.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
