<HEADLINE> Vietnam Allows Dong to Fluctuate More Around Official Rate </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HANOI, October 15 (Xinhua) -- State Bank of Vietnam has decided
to allow the country's legal tender, known as dong, to fluctuate
more around official exchange rates against foreign currencies.
</P>
<P>
The decision to widen the range, from previous plus or minus 5
percent to 10 percent, was made by the central bank on Monday and
carried by Vietnamese news media here today.
</P>
<P>
The measure, the bank said in a statement, was designed to give
traders an increased scope to arrive at more realistic prices to
better suit supply and demand.
</P>
<P>
It would also help curb speculation and discourage the hoarding
of foreign currencies, it said.
</P>
<P>
The bank vowed to continue managing and controlling exchange
rates flexibly in accordance with supply and demand, thereby
preventing the national economy from changing greatly.
</P>
<P>
As a result, it said, the move will contribute a lot to
encouraging exports, controlling imports and increasing state
reserves of foreign currencies.
</P>
<P>
After the announcement of this new measure, official exchange
rate between U.S. dollar and dong set by the Bank for Foreign
Trade of Vietnam went up obviously.
</P>
<P>
The bank today quoted the buying price of one U.S. dollar at
11,782 dong and the selling price at 11,796 dong, against 11,703
and 11,726 unit on Tuesday. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
