<HEADLINE> New Definitions of Oil Reserves Released in China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, October 15 (Xinhua) -- A set of new definitions of
petroleum reserves has been released as a 3-year joint effort by the
World Petroleum Congress and the Society of Petroleum Engineers.
</P>
<P>
The new definitions have been designed to permit more flexibility
in the methodologies used and to provide a template for future
improvements made possible by technological advances or made
necessary by changing economic or political conditions, according
to the ongoing 15th World Petroleum Congress here.
</P>
<P>
The fresh move has been made carefully so that it will not
revolutionize the definitions or generate major disruption in the
way oil fields are evaluated at present, according to the congress.
</P>
<P>
Prior to the new release, the two international bodies relied on
their own sets of definitions to classify petroleum reserves,
leading to confusion and misunderstanding in many cases.
</P>
<P>
Officials of the two organizations said that the new definitions
will be used until future adjustments in the light of changing
technical and economic realities. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971015.0168 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Import-Export Tax Revenue Below Targets in Vietnam </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HANOI, October 15 (Xinhua) -- Vietnam's tax revenue from import
and export in the first nine months of this year reached 9,700
billion Vietnamese dong (roughly 822 million U.S. dollars) or 69.3
percent of the target set for the year, Vietnam News Agency (VNA)
reported today.
</P>
<P>
The customs sector foresaw that it will fail to meet the
government target of 17,500 billion dong (nearly 1.5 billion
dollars) in tax revenue for 1997, said the agency.
</P>
<P>
General Director of the Customs Department Phan Van Dinh
attributed the shortfall to structural adjustments of imports and
exports.
</P>
<P>
The government has imposed a tightened control over imports by
raising import taxes since early this year in a bid to protect
local producers.
</P>
<P>
Imports of fully-assembled motorbikes and under-12-seat
automobiles were stopped in mid-April, as were 12 categories of
consumer goods.
</P>
<P>
As a result, the import volume of consumer goods saw a
year-to-year drop of 18.9 percent in the first six months of this
year, said the agency.
</P>
<P>
The restriction on steel and paper imports also deducted 89
billion dong (7.62 million dollars) and 42 billion dong (3.59
million dollars) from import tax revenue forecast in the first
half of 1997.
</P>
<P>
In an effort to increase revenues, the Customs Department has
toughed its anti-smuggling and anti-tax evasion measures.
</P>
<P>
It cracked 10,900 smuggling and tax evasion cases involving
commodities worth over 400 billion dong (34 million dollars) in
the past nine months, doubling the figure of the same period last
year.
</P>
<P>
In the third quarter of 1997, the department uncovered 4,519
cases of commercial fraud involving a total of 200 billion dong
(17 million dollars). 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971015.0169 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Ugandan Army on Alert in North </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KAMPALA, October 15 (Xinhua) -- The Ugandan army and security
forces in the north are on alert in the wake of infiltration out
of a besiege last week by some 250 rebels of the Lord's
Resistance Army (LRA), "The New Vision" reported today.
</P>
<P>
The government detachments are deployed at all sub-counties in
Aruu and Agaga counties of Kitgum District to block the road for
the rebels to escape.
</P>
<P>
Security sources said their fellow soldiers have stepped up
patrol in the southern part of Kitgum bordering Gulu.
</P>
<P>
James Oryem Canogura, Kitgum assistant resident district
commissioner, confirmed the military reinforcement in the areas
of his district. But he did not give further details.
</P>
<P>
Another report said some LRA rebels raided a prison farm in
Ajumani in the northwest Sunday and freed some 80 prisoners. But
the report had not been confirmed by the Ugandan army.
</P>
<P>
A security source insisting on anonymity said a plane destined
for Ajumani was delayed at Entebbe International Airport
yesterday following the report on the matter. The report said the
rebels had planted mines in the airport in the town of Ajumani.
</P>
<P>
The LRA is a rebel group operating in the north and has some
450 fighters, but it had more than 2,000 soldiers in previous
years. An earlier report said Joseph Kony, leader of LRA, was
pinned down in a remote valley between northern Gulu and Kitgum
districts. 
</P>
</TEXT>
