<HEADLINE> Swazi Trade Unions Might End Strike: Report </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, October 15 (Xinhua) -- Swaziland trade unions
might call off the national strike which began earlier Monday,
South Africa's Business Day newspaper said today.
</P>
<P>
The Swaziland Federation of Trade Unions' general council met
Monday night to decide whether to call off the national strike,
it said.
</P>
<P>
The paper quoted Swazi sources as saying there were strong
indications that the federation might call off the action in view
of growing signs that workers were ambivalent about the strike.
</P>
<P>
The possibility of the strike ending comes about despite its
continuance in forestry and the majority of sugar companies,
while workers at Swazi Rail and other transport companies joined
the strike Monday.
</P>
<P>
At the same time, mixed reports were received as to whether
the teachers, who had embarked on a separate strike in support of
an 18 percent wage increase, would continue their strike.
</P>
<P>
The leaders of the Swaziland National Teachers' Association
went to ground at the outset after it became clear that they had
failed to explain honestly to their members the status of
discussions with the government. 
</P>
