<HEADLINE> ECOWAS Wants Achievements Better Known </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, October 15 (Xinhua) -- The Economic Community of West
African States (ECOWAS) will focus on establishing an information
mechanism to make itself better known both in the sub-region and
worldwide.
</P>
<P>
The regional organization, established in 1975, has so far
achieved much but the international community and citizens of
ECOWAS countries are ignorant of these achievements, according to
Lansana Kouyate, executive secretary of ECOWAS.
</P>
<P>
The major reason is "the information mechanism is deeply
lacking," he said, quoted by the Guardian newspaper today.
</P>
<P>
Kouyate, a Guinean who replaced Edouard Benjamin as the
executive secretary at the August ECOWAS summit in Abuja, the
Nigerian capital, is in the United States for a visit.
</P>
<P>
The executive secretary stressed the extent of ignorance of
the international community on ECOWAS, saying that "here in New
York, for instance, when you ask people about ECOWAS, they will
say it is a peace-keeping operation in Liberia."
</P>
<P>
Therefore he vowed to devote efforts to having a strong
information mechanism for ECOWAS both as an instrument of
education and mobilization.
</P>
<P>
Beside, poverty eradication will also be the major policy
thrust of the sub-regional economic bloc, he said, adding that
the creation of a conducive environment for economic prosperity
was fundamental to the achievement of the ideals of ECOWAS.
</P>
</TEXT>
