<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Russian FM to Discuss Israeli Concern Over Iran's </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, October 15 (Xinhua) -- Russian Foreign Minister
Yevgeny Primakov is due to visit Israel at the end of October to
allay Israel's concern over Russia's support to Iran's missile
program, Israel Radio reported today.
</P>
<P>
Primakov is scheduled to hold talks with Israeli Prime
Minister Benjamin Netanyahu, his Israeli counterpart David Levy
and Defense Minister Yitzhak Mordechai on amending the bilateral
ties that have been strained by Israeli protests against Russian
aid to Iran's missile program, which Israel regards as top threat
to its security.
</P>
<P>
In a September 27 interview with a local newspaper, Mordechai
sounded alarm about Iran's missile program, saying Tehran is
nearly completing its development of long-range missiles that will
threaten both Israeli and U.S. security.
</P>
<P>
Mordechai revealed that Israel and the United States had
received intelligence that Iran has progressed faster than
previously thought in both its medium-range ballistic missile and
nuclear weapons programs.
</P>
<P>
He warned that, at the current pace of development, Tehran
would be able to produce missiles that can hit Israel, Gulf
states, Asia and parts of Europe by 1999. He believed that Iran
also wants to increase its chemical weapons and produce
biological and nuclear weapons.
</P>
<P>
Israeli officials believed that Iran has embarked on three
missile programs classified in ranges of 1,500, 3,000 and 5,500
kilometers.
</P>
<P>
Israel and the U.S. have been trying to pressure Moscow to
stop its aid to Iran in developing mass destruction weapons, but
they disagreed over how to exert the pressure.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. government wants to concentrate on quiet diplomatic
efforts, while Israel is lobbying the U.S. Congress to cut off the
U.S. aid to Moscow, which stands at 95 million U.S. dollars in
1997.
</P>
<P>
Frustrated by U.S. refusal to cut aid to Russia, Israel had to
increase diplomatic efforts. Israeli officials have actively
lobbied their colleagues in Europe, Russia, and the U.S. to stop
the transfer of missile technology to Tehran.
</P>
<P>
Israel had also tried to seal a fat deal to buy Russian
natural gas with Moscow in exchange for its halt to aiding
Iran. But the first Russian visit by Israeli Prime Minister
Benjamin Netanyahu in mid-March has failed to reach an agreement
in the respect.
</P>
<P>
For its part, Russia has strongly denied that it is helping
Iran develop ballistic missiles, and insists its nuclear aid to
Iran is only limited to developing a civilian nuclear
reactor. 
</P>
</TEXT>
