<HEADLINE> China to Build Large Oil Projects in Kazakhstan  (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, October 15 (Xinhua) -- China has committed to
undertaking its largest-ever overseas oil program in neighboring
Kazakhstan to meet its rising domestic demand for energy,
according to a Kazakhstan official at the 15th World Petroleum
Congress (WPC).
</P>
<P>
Paythan Sarmurzina, director of the Department of Economy and
Trade with Kazakhstan's Ministry of Economy and Trade, told Xinhua
today that the program will include construction of two
trans-national pipelines and the joint development of the Uzen
oilfield, Kazakhstan's second as well as three other oilfields.
</P>
<P>
The cooperative partners signed the agreements in Alma-Ata,
capital of Kazakhstan. Experts estimated the cost at 9.5 billion
U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
According to Sarmurzina, the two pipelines are expected to pump
crude oil from the northwest parts of Kazakhstan to China's
Xinjiang Uygur Autonomous Region and Iran.
</P>
<P>
A project official with the China National Petroleum
Corporation (CNPC) revealed that the 3,000-km, 3-billion-US dollar
pipeline project is slated to start next year. The annual
transmission capacity is designed to reach 25 million tons upon
completion in 2005, which would resolve the crude oil shortage in
western China.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971015.0180 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China to Build Large Oil Projects in Kazakhstan  (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Another pipeline, with a length of 800-1,000 km, will link
Kazakhstan with Iran via Turkmenistan. The project is considered
beneficial for both China and Kazakhstan to tap the gradually
opening Iranian oil market.
</P>
<P>
According to the agreements, the CNPC is also committed to
developing the Uzen oilfield, whose recoverable reserves are
estimated at 110 million tons. Oil experts said that the annual
crude output could peak at some 10 million tons.
</P>
<P>
In addition, CNPC last June purchased a 60 percent stake in
Kazakhstan's Aktobemunajgaz Oil and Gas Corp. CNPC is expected to
ship the first batch of oil this month in accordance with the
production-share contract.
</P>
<P>
Huang Yan, vice-president of CNPC, in a recent interview with
Xinhua, said that China's rapid economic growth increased oil
consumption and led to a shortage. "The annual demand rises at the
pace of 5 percent while the production could only increase less
than 2 percent," he said.
</P>
<P>
China's petroleum industry has been actively involved in
overseas exploration and development since 1992, he said..
</P>
<P>
"It is expected that China will ship back more than one million
tons of crude from overseas as the country boosted its cooperation
in the petroleum industry with other countries including
Kazakhstan," he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
