<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-15 09:35 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Israeli Scientists Discover Radio-like Mechanism in Brain </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, October 15 (Xinhua) -- The brain interprets sensory
input using a mechanism similar to that of an FM (frequency
modulation) radio, Israeli scientists reported in today's issue of
"the proceedings of the National Academy of Science".
</P>
<P>
Ehud Ahissar, of the Weizmann Institute's neurobiology
department, and his two assistants showed that the brain uses
this radio-like mechanism to "tune in" to a particular frequency,
allowing data gathered via touch to be translated into
information about external objects.
</P>
<P>
They did their study on rats, which twitch their whiskers
when looking for food. The rats' hairs oscillate at a rate
of about eight motions per second, informing the neurons in
their brain to tune in to a "transmission frequency" of
about 8 Hertz.
</P>
<P>
When the hairs touch an object, they trigger more neutral
signals that modulate the regular 8 Hertz transmission. The
timing is determined by the object's location, enabling the
brain to create an internal "image" of the object's
whereabouts.
</P>
<P>
"We hope our study will contribute to the deciphering of
the neutral code -- the way in which information is encoded
by the sensory organs, and decoded by the brain," said
Ahissar.
</P>
<P>
He noted that cracking the neural code could advance brain
research tremendously, just as the deciphering of the human
genome code has gradually revolutionized genetics and molecular
biology.
</P>
<P>
Until now, scientists studying touch or the other senses
have focused on identifying the cells in the brain that
receive the signals and on assessing their intensity. But the
Weizmann scientists found that the brain actually knows what
it is being told by the senses, and that the timing of
the signals also plays a vital role in this process.
</P>
<P>
Ahissar says the brain seems to be tuned to its own
"radio stations." He shows that neural signals generated by
touch modulate the oscillation frequency of these cells. As
they are regular and persistent, these oscillations provide the
brain with a "yardstick" with which the timing of incoming
signals can be compared. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971015.0184 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Saudi Arabia to Continue Global Oil Policy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, 15 (Xinhua) -- Saudi Arabia will continue its policy
of fulfiling global demand for oil under both normal and extreme
conditions, according to Ali L. Al-Naimi, its minister of
petroleum and mineral resources.
</P>
<P>
In his speech at today's session of the 15th World Petroleum
Congress, Al-Haimi said that Saudi Arabia has consistently adhered
to a policy of ensuring a stable world petroleum supply, and will
remain committed to providing reliable supplies for three major
consuming regions -- North America, Europe and Asia. Balancing the
supply and demand for oil is basic to our marketing strategy, the
minister added.
</P>
<P>
 Saudi Arabia, the world's largest petroleum producer and
exporter, has proven oil reserves of over 263 billion barrels, or
26 percent of the worldwide total. The country, which produces
eight million barrels of crude oil and 700,000 barrels of liquid
natural gas daily, recorded total 1996 oil sales of over 51
billion US dollars.
</P>
<P>
Saudi Arabia has also expanded efforts to market oil in Asia
over recent years, with the daily export volume standing at four
million barrels.
</P>
<P>
The minister noted that Saudi Arabia's oil policy is based on
five building blocks -- huge oil reserves, prolific production,
reserve capacity, stable and consistent oil marketing policies and
advanced technology.
</P>
<P>
Moreover, the country has its own fleet of ocean-going
supertankers.
</P>
<P>
Saudi Arabia is developing a large oilfield in the remote
southeast to promote oil growth, with the project scheduled for
completion in mid-1998. Saudi-based Aramco has drafted a
three-year program to produce 10 million barrels of crude oil
daily.
</P>
<P>
Saudi Arabia continues to promote cooperation between OPEC
members and other outside oil producers, according to Al-Naimi.
</P>
<P>
The minister stressed that his country is greatly concerned
about environmental problems. "The Kingdom and neighboring
countries are introducing steps to reduce and prevent ocean
pollution resulting from shipping activities," said Al-Naimi.
</P>
</TEXT>
