<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Heavy Oil to Play Greater Role in World Energy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, October 15 (Xinhua) -- Huge reserves and increased
exploration will help heavy oil play a greater role in world
energy supply in the future, a leading international expert said.
</P>
<P>
The potential in heavy oil production is of "the utmost
importance to the energy position of the world," said Richard
Meyer, a researcher with Canada's Unitar Center for Heavy Crude
and Tar Sand, at the ongoing 15th World Petroleum Congress.
</P>
<P>
He added that the world heavy oil resource is comprised of about
210 billion barrels of unproved reserves and 299 billion barrels of
original reserves.
</P>
<P>
Cumulative production has amounted to about 88.8 billion barrels
to date, with annual production standing at about 2.4 billion
barrels, Meyer said.
</P>
<P>
He went on to note that a major proportion of heavy oil is
contained in 52 giant fields worldwide, and 183 of the
approximately 1700 heavy oil fields are at least partially
offshore.
</P>
<P>
Moreover, he said, the large resource base of heavy oil is
favorable to exploitation and countries with potential in this
field have stepped up development.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
