<DOCNO> XIE19971015.0190 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-15 10:11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Turkish Jets Bomb PUK-Controlled Area in </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA, October 15 (Xinhua) -- Iraq's Patriotic Union of
Kurdistan (PUK) has confirmed that Turkish warplanes bombed its
area in northern Iraq, local newspaper Daily News reported
today.
</P>
<P>
The bombardments took place Monday while Turkish jets
attacked Turkey's outlawed Kurdish Workers' Party (PKK) rebels in
the area, Shazad Saib, a senior official at the PUK Ankara
office, was quoted as saying.
</P>
<P>
In one incident, several PUK positions were hit by the bombs
dropped by Turkish warplanes, Saib said.
</P>
<P>
Late last month, around 15,000 Turkish troops, backed by air
and artillery fire, launched a cross-border incursion in
northern Iraq in a bid to destroy newly-built PKK camps.
</P>
<P>
Turkey started to withdraw its troops from northern Iraq
early Monday, leaving some units in the area to prevent a
possible comeback of the rebels, according to media reports.
</P>
<P>
Saib stressed that the PUK expects Turkey to take a neutral
stance in northern Iraq, indicating that Ankara helps the
Kurdistan Democratic Party (KDP) led by Massoud Barzani in their
fightings against the PKK.
</P>
<P>
The KDP has been fighting against both the PUK and PKK in
northern Iraq after Iraqi President Saddam Hussein lost control
of the area due to a crushing defeat in the 1991 Gulf War.
</P>
<P>
The PUK, which allegedly gains support from Iran and
maintains a relaxed relationship with the PKK, vows to topple
the Saddam regime through armed struggle.
</P>
<P>
However, the KDP, backed by both Baghdad and Ankara, has been
wrestling with its main rival PUK for the control of northern
Iraq and has also been fighting alongside with Turkish troops in
the area against the PKK rebels over the past several months.
</P>
<P>
Turkey had repeatedly accused Tehran and Damascus of
supporting the PKK, vowing to eradicate the Kurdish separatists
with force. Ankara has frequently launched cross-border
operations aimed at wiping out the PKK militants in northern
Iraq.
</P>
<P>
Saib had denied earlier that the PUK was sheltering the PKK
rebels in northern Iraq, describing as "baseless" media reports
that the PKK militants, escaping Ankara's offensive, had been
taking refuge in PUK-controlled area.
</P>
<P>
The PUK, KDP and representatives from Turkey, Britain and the
United States, three sponsors for the northern Iraq issue, met
in London last week to discuss the situation in northern Iraq,
but failed to achieve any positive results. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
