<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Motorola Celebrates 10 Years in China, Makes Investment Commitment (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, October 15 (Xinhua) -- Motorola, on the occasion of
the 10th anniversary of its entry into China, expects to invest
2.5 billion U.S. dollars by the year 2000.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, P.Y. Lai, president of the Motorola (China)
Electronics Ltd., said the company will spend at least another one
billion U.S. dollars annually on material and services from
Chinese suppliers.
</P>
<P>
A new office building, Motorola's headquarters for its China
operations, is nearing completion in Beijing.
</P>
<P>
"The decision to place Motorola's headquarters in Beijing shows
our confidence in investing in China and our commitment to the
country's future," said Rick Younts, executive vice-president of
Motorola.
</P>
<P>
Since the establishment of its Beijing representative office in
1987, Motorola has set up one exclusively-funded enterprise and
six jointly-owned ones. With a total commitment of 1.2 billion
U.S. dollars, Motorola is the single biggest U.S. investor in
China as well as the biggest foreign investor in China's
electronics industry.
</P>
<P>
"The past 10 years have seen Motorola's good cooperation with
China," Lai said.
</P>
<P>
Motorola will continue participating in the development of
China's central and western region, he said. In 1995 Motorola
funneled 30 million U.S. dollars into southwest China's Sichuan
Province and founded its first joint venture there.
</P>
<P>
In response to a government call for revitalizing the
state-owned enterprises, Motorola has committed the bulk of its
annual projected investment of one billion U.S. dollars to the
purchase of state-owned enterprises.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
