<DOCNO> XIE19971015.0193 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Motorola Celebrates 10 Years in China, Makes Investment Commitment (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Robert Galvin, chairman of the Motorola's executive committee,
attributed the company's achievements in China to the Chinese
government's reform policies, rapid economic progress and a good
investment climate.
</P>
<P>
"Mutual trust is Motorola's precious experience in working in
cooperation with China. The trust that China gives to Motorola has
provided it with opportunities for development, which is valuable
for both." Galvin said.
</P>
<P>
Motorola, together with other U.S. companies based in China,
has launched the US-China Ties Normalization Initiative, a
non-official organization aimed at boosting bilateral commercial
and business contacts.
</P>
<P>
Lai held that problems in U.S.-Chinese relations such as the
intellectual property rights and most-favored-nation (MFN) trading
status should be dealt with through appropriate channels and in a
spirit of mutual cooperation.
</P>
<P>
"No matter how U.S.-China relations are troubled by unfavorable
factors, a sound commercial link is indispensable for stable
growth ... and it has always been an important part of Motorola's
efforts to promote bilateral ti," Lai said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
