<HEADLINE> ASEAN Emerges as S. Korean's Biggest Exports Market </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SEOUL, October 15 (Xinhua) -- The Association of Southeast
Asian Nations (ASEAN) has emerged as South Korea's largest export
destination, leaving behind the United States for the first time.
</P>
<P>
The Ministry of Trade, Industry and Energy said Wednesday that
South Korea shipped 14.021 billion U.S. dollars in goods, or 15.9
percent of its total exports, to the ASEAN bloc between January
and August.
</P>
<P>
The country also exported 13.926 billion dollars to the United
State, 10.344 billion dollars to the European Union and 9.899
billion dollars to Japan in the same period.
</P>
<P>
Last year, the United States was South Korea's biggest market
with exports worth 21.671 billion dollars, to be followed by ASEAN
(20.270 billion dollars), Japan (15.767 billion dollars and the EU
at 15.325 billion dollars, the ministry said.
</P>
<P>
Increased exports to ASEAN was attributed to the expansion of
the regional grouping which accepted Myanmar and Laos as its new
members in July and the expansion of economic cooperation between
the bloc and South Korea.
</P>
<P>
On the other hand, ASEAN was South Korea's fourth biggest
import market. In the first eight months of this year, South Korea
imported 8.395 billion dollars worth of goods from ASEAN
countries.
</P>
<P>
As a result, trade volume between South Korea and the ASEAN
registered 22.416 billion dollars, ranking fourth among the
country's major trade partners.
</P>
<P>
"As ASEAN's goods and services trade is expected to reach 707
billion dollars in 2000 and 1,273 billion dollars in 2005, the
bloc will play an important role in the world economy. Despite its
recent currency crisis, ASEAN's trade with South Korea will
steadily increase," a ministry official said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
