<HEADLINE> Major News Items in Leading French Newspapers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, October 15 (Xinhua) -- The following are major news
items in leading French newspapers today:
</P>
<P>
Liberation:
</P>
<P>
-- After four months of fighting, the battle for Brazzaville,
the capital of Congo Republic, has entered its final phase. The
southern part of the city, which was spared from fighting until
Monday, saw its population fleeing the area under heavy
bombardment and air raid by a Mig-21 combat aircraft from the camp
of former President Denis Sassou Nguesso. Congolese President
Pascal Lissouba is in Kampala seeking military aid from Uganda.
</P>
<P>
-- Despite pressure from Washington, London and Ankara for an
end of fighting, two principal factions of Iraqi Kurds have been
engaged in a fratricide combat since Monday in the northern part
of Iraq along the line of demarcation between the two
factions. But different from the inter-Kurdish war in August and
September 1996 which resulted in the death of thousands, Iraqi
troops are less involved this time in the feud between the forces
of Massud Barzani and Jalal Talabani.
</P>
<P>
Le Figaro:
</P>
<P>
-- French Prime Minister Lionel Jospin has rejected accusation
by the opposition parties and the national employers association
CNPF that he had "fooled" Frenchmen by pretending to hold a
national jobs conference in order to present his plan on 35-hour
workweek. He said that he prefers a France "which proposes,
animates and has dialogue" instead of one which is "in the line of
European conformism."
</P>
<P>
-- The Democratic and Popular Forces (FDP) loyal to former
Congolese President Denis Sassou Nguesso announced the capture of
the capital Brazzaville on Tuesday, after one day of intensive
fighting between the forces of Sassou Nguesso and those of
President Pascal Lissouba around the presidential palace and the
Maya-Maya international airport of Brazzaville. The FDP also said
they had taken control of three strategic localities between 100
and 200 kilometers from the city Pointe-Noire. 
</P>
</TEXT>
