<BODY>
<HEADLINE> S. African Police, Army Mobilized to Protect </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, October 15 (Xinhua) -- South African Security
authorities have vowed to take measures to curb killings and
violent activities to protect farmers.
</P>
<P>
Special police and defense force operations would be stepped
up to protect farmers, especially in the Free State, Divisional
Police Commissioner Andre Pruis said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The concrete measures include road blocks, tactical response
teams and special units to track down suspects, Pruis said.
</P>
<P>
The commissioner made the remarks after President Nelson
Mandela announced an intelligence probe into the spate of
killings on farms.
</P>
<P>
"We are determined to root it out," Mandela told reporters
after meeting a South African Agricultural Union (SAAU)
delegation in Pretoria.
</P>
<P>
The SAAU presented Mandela with a memorandum demanding that a
commission be appointed to investigate the possibility that the
violence was part of an orchestrated campaign to drive farmers
off their land.
</P>
<P>
According to statistics, attacks on farmers have increased by
53 percent during the first three months of the year, compared to
the same period last year.
</P>
<P>
The SAAU described as "nauseating and atrocious" statistics
that farmers were being murdered at a rate four times higher than
other South Africans. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
