<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Israeli Researchers Crush Garlic Mystery </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, October 15 (Xinhua) -- Israeli researchers at the
Weizmann Institute have revealed a molecular mechanism that
serves as the basis for some of the plant's therapeutic effects,
local English daily The Jerusalem Post reported today.
</P>
<P>
The study was conducted by Professors David Mirelman and Meir
Wilchek of the Biological Chemistry Department of the institute.
</P>
<P>
They developed a unique procedure for producing large
quantities of pure allicin - garlic's main biologically active
ingredient. Produced when garlic cloves are crushed, allicin
naturally protects the plant from soil parasites and fungi and
is also responsible for its pungent odor.
</P>
<P>
In the study which appeared in the October issue of the
American Society for Microbiology's Antimicrobial Agents and
Chemotherapy, Mirelman and Wilchek explained how allicin fights
infection.
</P>
<P>
Their research supports the idea that garlic is an excellent,
albeit noisome, antimicrobial drug that can disable a large
variety of pathogens, including certain bacteria, fungi and
viruses.
</P>
<P>
The second study, soon to be published in the
Netherlands-based journal Biochimica Biophysica Acta, could help
clarify the role allicin serves in preventing heart disease and
other disorders. Both pieces of research revealed and
characterized a molecular mechanism by which allicin blocks
certain groups of enzymes.
</P>
<P>
The studies revealed that allicin kills amebas that cause
dysentery by blocking enzymes vital to their life cycle. This
discovery could lead to the use of allicin as a medication
against bacteria that have developed resistance to certain
antibiotics.
</P>
<P>
Since similar enzyme activity is involved in the formation of
cholesterol, the researchers think allicin may be able to
prevent its production and accumulation on the inside walls of
coronary arteries.
</P>
<P>
Mirelman and Wilchek also confirmed that allicin prevents the
formation of oxygen-free radicals, which can set off the process
of tumor development. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
