<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China, Russia Join Hands in Pipeline Project </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, October 15 (Xinhua) -- Russia and China have spent
three years studying the physical feasibility of two pipelines to
transport the natural gas of Siberia to China's coastal areas, Ott
Victor Logancsvich, Russian vice-minister of fuel and energy,
said at a press conference of the 15th World Petroleum Congress
today.
</P>
<P>
He said that the senior energy officials of Russia and China
will hold further negotiation on the two projects during the
conference.
</P>
<P>
When completed, the two pipelines will have a maximum
transporting capacity of five percent of Russia's gas output
annually, and will also supply the gas markets of other Far East
nations.
</P>
<P>
Zhang Chengwu, chief representative of the China National
petroleum Corporation in Moscow, said that one of the pipeline
projects will link the natural gas reserves of Russia's Irkutsk
and Rizhao of China's Shandong Province, and will reach the
Republic of Korea and Japan at its final stage.
</P>
<P>
The other pipeline, running from West Siberia to Shanghai, via
the Xinjiang Uygur Autonomous Region, is expected to help ease the
energy supply bottleneck in the booming southeast China.
</P>
<P>
According to official statistics here, natural gas will
experience a big-margin rise over the coming decades. In 2000 and
2020, the output of natural gas is estimated to be 26-35 billion
cubic meters and 58 to 85 billion cubic meters, respectively,
while the natural gas consumption will be 26-29 billion cubic
meters and 88-105 billion cubic meters. The gap will exist beyond
the year 2020, and thus leave a huge market potential for foreign
gas companies.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
