<HEADLINE> Pakistan Rupee Devalued by 3.53 against U.S. Dollar </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, October 15 (Xinhua) -- The State Bank of Pakistan
(SBP) today re-adjusted the Rupee by Rs 3.53 downward against U.S.
dollar setting the spot buying and selling rate at Rs
44.0500/44.2703.
</P>
<P>
According to an official notification of SBP received here, the
revised rates at which authorized dealers will buy and sell U.S.
dollar to the public with effect from October 15, 1997 are as
follows: Buying Rs 44.0060 and selling Rs 44.3144.
</P>
<P>
It is the fifth adjustment of Rupee against Dollar at official
level since last April. The value of Rupee was last re-adjusted on
June 28, this year, by 7 paisas against U.S. dollar.
</P>
<P>
The devaluation of Pak Rupee has apparently been made due to
mounting pressure by the exporters, particularly, those concerned
with European markets, experts here said.
</P>
<P>
European currencies have long been adjusted downward against
U.S. dollars and had been adversely affecting Pakistani exports,
they said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
