<DOCNO> XIE19971015.0216 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Asia to Depend More on Mideast Oil: Research Paper </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, October 15 (Xinhua) -- Asia's dependence on oil from
the Middle East is set to grow heavier over the next decade and
proper measures should be considered for the region's energy
security, Japanese research results obtained here today show.
</P>
<P>
Oil imports from the Middle East accounted for 75 percent of
Asia's total in 1995 and the figure is likely to climb up to
nearly 90 percent by 2010, Kazuya Fujime, managing director of
Japan's Institute of Energy Economics, said in a paper submitted
to the ongoing 15th World Petroleum Congress here.
</P>
<P>
In Asia, oil demand is expected to keep soaring as economic
growth maintains a fast pace, but scant increase in oil production
will leave an expanding gap in balance between demand and output,
according to the paper.
</P>
<P>
Kazuya Fujime forecasts that East Asia's daily oil demand will
increase by 4.4 percent annually to reach 14.9 million barrels in
2010 while daily crude oil production will rise by just 0.6
percent annually to six million barrels in 2010.
</P>
<P>
He said that the present two biggest crude oil producers in
Asia, namely China and Indonesia, will both be net oil importers
in the early 21st century.
</P>
<P>
In China, oil demand is expected to reach 6.5 million barrels a
day in 2010, while crude oil output will total just 3.9 million
barrels a day, Kazuya Fujime said.
</P>
<P>
Indonesia's daily oil demand will be 1.6 million barrels by
that time and its daily output then will be 1.3 million barrels,
he said.
</P>
<P>
Asia as a whole will have to import 21.2 million barrels of oil
a day in 2010, of which 10 percent will be covered by countries
such as Mexico, the United States, CIS and Africa, and 90 percent
will come from the Middle East, he said.
</P>
<P>
He suggested that for energy security, Asian countries have to
have enough oil stock to absorb the shocks due to short-term
supply cut of Mideast oil, diversify importing oil sources in
Pacific Rim countries, develop indigenous energy sources and save
energy.
</P>
<P>
Regional organizations like APEC will also be useful to work
out and implement proper joint action programs in the field, he
said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
