<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Community Service Offers New Opportunity for Laid-off Workers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NANCHANG, October 15 (Xinhua) -- Urban residents here can park
their bikes at outdoor sheds after work and not worry about having
them stolen because laid-off workers have been given jobs
providing security.
</P>
<P>
The bike guards are just one example of finding useful jobs for
redundant workers as an increasing number of China's surplus
laborers turn to community services for employment.
</P>
<P>
Nearly 4,000 displaced workers in Nanchang, capital of central
China's Jiangxi Province, have found new jobs in community
services since June.
 "I never thought of doing community service," said Zhao Long, a
laid-off worker who now runs a second-hand goods market.
</P>
<P>
"The market didn't cost me too much and, more importantly, my
experience as a worker is of great help in the process," he said.
</P>
<P>
The city has organized 748 community service units and plans to
employ 10,000 more laid-off workers this year.
</P>
<P>
Home-based jobs have become popular such as carrying coal and
gas, taking care of the elderly and child care. As a result, one
tenth of the city's laid-off workers have found employment in
community service.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
