<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Jiangsu Opens Up Agriculture to Overseas Investors </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NANJING, October 15 (Xinhua) -- East China's Jiangsu Province
has opened up its agricultural sector to overseas investors in an
attempt to modernize it.
</P>
<P>
The province, one of the leading grain producers in China, has
created 12 export-oriented agricultural development zones. By end
of June this year, 690 million yuan had been invested in
development on a 212-square-kilometer area.
</P>
<P>
Local governments have approved 71 overseas-funded and 254
domestic firms to operate in farm produce processing, fruit
preservation, flower cultivation, poultry and domestic animals
breeding and raising.
</P>
<P>
Jiangsu Province has 4.7 percent of the arable land in China
but produces 8 percent of the grain and 13 percent of the
cotton, and its output of meat, vegetable oil, aquatic products and
silkworm cocoons was among the highest in the country, said Jiang
Daoyuan, deputy secretary-general of the provincial government.
</P>
<P>
In recent years, the provincial government has established a
series of preferential policies to channel more overseas
investment into agriculture.
</P>
<P>
Overseas companies are exempt from paying agricultural and
income taxes for cultivating older and hilly areas, exploring
untapped natural resources and developing high-technology products.
</P>
<P>
By the end of June this year, the province had secured
contracts worth 850 million U.S. dollars for 480 projects, Jiang
said. The export value of farm and sideline produce totalled 5.3
billion U.S. dollars in 1996, accounting for 37.7 percent of
Jiangsu's foreign trade volume, Jiang said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
