<DOCNO> XIE19971015.0229 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Britain to Continue Land Discussions with </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, October 15 (Xinhua) -- Britain will only help finance
land acquisition and resettlement in Zimbabwe if farms are
acquired from willing sellers in a transparent manner and with
full and fair compensation, a senior British diplomat has said.
</P>
<P>
David Quarrey, head of political section at the British High
Commission in Harare, told the Zimbabwe News Agency Tuesday that
his government remained prepared to continue discussions with
Zimbabwe on that basis.
</P>
<P>
"We are willing to help meet the cost of land acquisition if
it was bought from willing sellers, and of land resettlement
provided it was bought in a transparent manner with full and fair
compensation," Quarrey said.
</P>
<P>
The statement came in the wake of comments by Zimbabwean
President Robert Mugabe who, during the start of his provincial
tours in Matableleland South Monday to assess the land
redistribution program, said Zimbabwe would continue compulsory
acquisition of land and would not compensate for the land.
</P>
<P>
Zimbabwe's land resettlement program hit a snag in 1989 when
Britain, which solely funded the program since 1980, withdrew
assistance, saying the initial program was a failure.
</P>
<P>
However, the Zimbabwean government went ahead and passed the
land acquisition act of 1992 under which the state can
compulsorily acquire land, a step heavily criticized by western
donors.
</P>
<P>
Since then negotiations to resume British funding for the
resettlement and land reform have not been fruitful as Zimbabwe
refuses to meet the given conditions.
</P>
<P>
Mugabe said Monday, "we are prepared to pay for development,
not the soil. However, if Britain wanted compensation they should
have given us the money and we would pass it on to their
children."
</P>
<P>
Zimbabwe still needs more than two billion Zimbabwe Dollars
(160 million U.S. Dollars) to fund the acquisition of over 2,000
farms identified countrywide.
</P>
<P>
At least 62,000 people have been resettled since independence
but another 100,000 still wait for the land which the government
has been promising for the past 17 years. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
