<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, October 15 (Xinhua) -- Indonesian Security police will
be out in full force on Thursday to try to control huge partisan
soccer crowds expected for semi-final matches at the South East
Asian games in Jakarta.
</P>
<P>
SEA Games officials Wednesday said the security department
planned to deploy all personnel to maintain order during the
matches.
</P>
<P>
"Our security is ready for it," said a SEA Games spokesman.
"There will be more rules for spectators too. For example they
will not be allowed to bring in drinking water in bottles."
</P>
<P>
In one game the fans threw bottles at the Thai team which was
in the stands to watch an Indonesia match.
</P>
<P>
Jakarta's military spokesman, Lieutenant Colonel D.J.
Nachrowi, said all 7,500 troops and police reserved for the SEA
Games would be assigned to maintain order during the matches,
according to a report from the Jakarta Post.
</P>
<P>
Earlier in the week, crowds mobbed ticket booths, standing on
top of each other and screaming as they tried to secure free
passes to the matches.
</P>
<P>
Indonesia topped the five-team group standings in the
round-robin preliminaries and will meet Singapore.
</P>
<P>
Thailand will play Vietnam in the other semi-final match.
</P>
