<DOCNO> XIE19971015.0236 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Roundup: Excises on Luxury &AMP; Imported Goods Increased </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, October 15 (Xinhua) -- Excise duties on 21 items of
luxury and imported goods and oil in Thailand have begun to
increase starting today.
</P>
<P>
This is part of the government's endeavers to meet the budget
surplus target of 1 percent of gross domestic product in fiscal
1998, as required by the International Monetary Fund (IMF).
</P>
<P>
Since early hours today, gasoline and diesel oil prices have
been among the first to rise, by one baht per liter (36.55 baht to
one U.S. dollar).
</P>
<P>
This is the 13th oil price increase since the baht was floated
on July 2, and the Thai currency has depreciated by 41.7 percent
against the dollar.
</P>
<P>
Under the government's economic revival plan, unveiled on
Tuesday by Deputy Prime Minister Virabongsa Ramangkura and Finance
Minister Thanong Bidaya, tax increases were announced.
</P>
<P>
Excise duties on alcoholic liquors, including beer, increased
by between two percentage points and 10 percentage points.
</P>
<P>
Excise duty on tobacco products rose by two percentage points,
from the old 68 percent to 70 percent.
</P>
<P>
On imported items, all are subject to a 10 percent surcharge,
except items on which customs duties are now less than 5 percent.
</P>
<P>
In addition, imported automobiles (completely built-up units)
will face a new customs duty rate of 80 percent, compared to 42
and 68.5 percent in the past depending on different cylinder
capacity.
</P>
<P>
Customs duties on cameras, lenses, spectacles and frames,
watches and clocks, pens and lighters will all jump by 25
percentage points, from 5 percent to 30 percent.
</P>
<P>
Import duty will increase by 10 percentage points (from 20
percent to 30 percent) for perfume and cosmetics, leather handbags
and belts, leather and canvas shoes, crystal and costume jewelry.
</P>
<P>
The government expects to generate 40 billion baht (1.1 billion
U.S. dollars) in additional income from these tax and duty
increases, which will remain in force until December 31, 1999.
</P>
<P>
In mid-August, the value-added tax (VAT) rate was raised from 7
percent to 10 percent.
</P>
<P>
The tax increase on oil could be a double-edge sword. While it
will bring more revenue for the government and cut petroleum
import bills, it will also affect industrial and commercial
operators, who will have to pay more for their energy costs.
</P>
<P>
It is reported that so far this year an estimated 700,000
people have lost their jobs and the number could pass the one
million mark next year.
</P>
<P>
Prime Minister Chavalit Yongchaiyudh has said recently that it
may take two to three years before the economy revives. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971015.0237 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Fujian Targets Funds to Upgrade Port Capacity </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
FUZHOU, October 15 (Xinhua) -- Fujian Province is seeking to
raise 20 billion yuan from foreign and domestic sources for a
large-scale port upgrading project.
</P>
<P>
According to sources with the departments in charge of the
project, the upcoming construction will be divided into two
phases.
</P>
<P>
In the first phase to 2000, the province will need 8 billion
yuan to construct 59 ports, including 21 deep-water berths which
would add 38 million tons to the province's port handling capacity.
</P>
<P>
In the second phase through 2010, another 11.6 billion yuan
will be needed to develop 62 berths, including 41 deep-water
berths.
</P>
<P>
The province will have a combined port handling capacity of
181.7 million tons and 111 deep-water berths when the project is
completed. Major ports will be able to accommodate ships ranging
from 20,000 to 100,000 tons each.
</P>
<P>
With more than 3,300 kilometers of coastline and many natural
bays, Fujian Province has the advantage of developing port
transportation. The province has six natural ports which could
handle 50,000 tons each.
</P>
<P>
Six large ports in the province -- Xiamen, Sandu'ao, Luoyuan,
Meizhouwan, Dongshan and Shacheng -- each has a handling capacity
of 100,000 to 500,000 tons. 
</P>
</TEXT>
