<HEADLINE> Slovakia Woos International Loans for Road Building </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PRAGUE, October 14 (Xinhua) -- Slovakia is wooing international
loans to overhaul its outdated highways, which have become a
"bottleneck" in the country's economic development.
</P>
<P>
Expressways now only account for one percent of Slovakia's
highway systems, 60 percent of which are third-class roads that
are in poor conditions, the Czech media said.
</P>
<P>
Slovakia recently decided to invest 140 billion crowns (4.4
billion U.S. dollars) in the next eight years to build new
highways and update the existing roads.
</P>
<P>
Because it is short of funds, the Slovak government has turned
to international banks for help.
</P>
<P>
In the first half of this year, the European Investment Bank
(EIB) provided Slovakia with a loan worth one billion crowns (30
million U.S. dollars) for constructing the expressway linking
Bratislava, the Slovak capital, to the area bordering Hungary and
Austria.
</P>
<P>
In August, the government signed another agreement with the
Industrial Bank of Japan for a loan worth four billion crown (120
million U.S. dollars).
</P>
<P>
It is reported that loan protocols with other international
banks are also under negotiation. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
