<HEADLINE> Quadrangle Plan Needs Boost: Thai Deputy Minister </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, October 15 (Xinhua) -- Thai Deputy Finance Minister
Thawatwong na Chiangmai has stressed that the economic quadrangle
plan needs to be pursued with greater vigor, the Bangkok Post
reported today.
</P>
<P>
The plan has been experiencing a slowdown with the number of
investment projects falling.
</P>
<P>
There is an urgent need for improved transportation and
communications systems to enable better coordination for the plan,
Thawatwong told a seminar in Chiang Mai at the weekend on Chiang
Mai's role in the economic quadrangle plan, which is involved with
Northern Thailand, Laos, Myanmar and China's Yunnan Province.
</P>
<P>
He believed that the plan, initiated in 1992 to encourage trade
and tourism among the four countries, would bring great benefits
to the estimated 200 million people living in the area.
</P>
<P>
He said the Thai Cabinet has already given Chiang Mai,
Thailand's second largest city 700 kilometers north of Bangkok,
the right to coordinate the work of the economic quadrangle plan.
</P>
<P>
Chiang Mai can take a leading role to help press the plan
forward so that it can emerge as a center of economic cooperation
in the sub-regional quadrangle, he said.
</P>
<P>
He revealed the Thai Finance Ministry has recently given soft
loans to Myanmar to continue construction and expansion of the
167-km road linking Tachilek, a Thai border town, with Keng Tung,
Eastern Myanmar. The project is expected to complete by the end of
next year.  
</P>
</TEXT>
