<HEADLINE> Chinese Olympic Shooter Wang Vows to Fight On </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANGHAI, October 15 (Xinhua) -- China's Barcelona Olympic
Champion shooter Wang Yifu, who has been suffering a damaged
cervical vertebra which was believed to have cost him the gold
medal at the Atlanta Games, said he will not quit if health
permits.
</P>
<P>
"If the health permits, I will not call it quit, " said the
37-year-old shooter. "I hope to take part in the Asian Games in
Thailand next year and even the 2000 Olympic Games."
</P>
<P>
Zhang Heng, head coach of the Chinese national shooting team,
said he hopes the four-time Olympian can stay in the team and
continue to win honor for the country.
</P>
<P>
"But it's more important for him to keep fit," Zhang added.
</P>
<P>
Wang collapsed after his last shot in the Atlanta Games which
squandered his 3.8-point lead. He blamed his disastrous last shot
to blackout caused by the injury.
</P>
<P>
Wang was treated in the hospitals for three months after
returning from Atlanta. He was recovering but could not be healed
of the injury, doctors said.
</P>
<P>
The former Olympic champion, who also serves as a coach of the
national team, resumed training only two months ago. 
</P>
</TEXT>
