<HEADLINE> Brazil Rejects U.S. Position on FTAA </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRASILIA, October 14 (Xinhua) -- Brazil`s Foreign Minister Luiz
Felipe Lampreia said today his country opposes U.S. position to
apply the so-called fast track in the setting up of the Free Trade
Area of the Americas (FTAA).
</P>
<P>
The priority of the foreign policy of Brazil is the Southern
Common Market (Mercosur), said the Minister.
</P>
<P>
"We do not want an anticipated FTAA and the foreign policy of
Brazil is based on negotiation rather than imposition", Lampreia
stated.
</P>
<P>
Today`s meeting between the President of Brazil Fernando
Henrique Cardoso and U.S. President Bill Clinton will not be
limited to the anticipation of FTAA issue.
</P>
<P>
"We will have a moderate and lengthy pace of negotiations due
to the rich, diversified and varied relations between Brazil
and the United States", he added.
</P>
<P>
The meeting in the Planalto Palace will be very rewarding
despite of differences between the two countries, he said.
</P>
<P>
The Brasilian government does not agree on the U.S. position
which is looking forward to apply a fast track in the setting up
of FTAA, Lampreia said, adding that Washington is putting a lot of
pressure on Brazil. 
</P>
</TEXT>
