<DOCNO> XIE19971015.0252 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Two Confirmed Dead in Colombo Blast </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
COLOMBO, October 15 (Xinhua) -- Two people have been confirmed
killed in a bombing which ripped the business district in Downtown
Colombo early this morning.
</P>
<P>
Tourism Minister Dharmasiri Senanayake told Xinhua that so far
there have been two deaths as a result of the bombing.
</P>
<P>
The number of casualties could be much higher if it were not
the Full Moon holiday today, on which people do not need to work
in office.
</P>
<P>
Earlier the National Hospital in the Sri Lankan capital said 30
to 40 people were killed in the incident. The hospital, the
biggest medical facility in Colombo, has so far admitted more than
100 injured people, including two Americans. Ambulances are still
moving in more wounded.
</P>
<P>
Senanayake said the fresh bombing was carried out in the same
way as the bombing of the Central Bank building on January 31,
1996.
</P>
<P>
In that incident, several LTTE rebels driving a truck, which
was loaded with explosives, slammed into the bank building and set
off a major explosion, killing more than 100 people and injuring
1,400 others.
</P>
<P>
The Liberation Tigers of Tamil Eelam (LTTE) has been fighting a
14-year ethnic war with the government for a separate state of
their own in the north and east of the country.
</P>
<P>
There are also reports saying that the bomb was planted in a
car parked near the Galadari Hotel in the downtown area.
</P>
<P>
Earlier, Industrial Development Minister C. V. Gunaratne said
the explosion was carried out by the LTTE, which was recently
declared a terrorist organization by the United States.
</P>
<P>
The bombing was in retaliation for the announcement, the
minister said.
</P>
<P>
U.S. Secretary of State Madeleine Albright on October 8
announced that the LTTE, along with 29 other organizations in the
world, was on the country's terrorist organization list and would
be barred from entering and raising funds in the United States.
</P>
<P>
The Bank of Ceylon and the twin towers of the World Trade
Center, which was declared open by President Chandrika Kumaratunga
three days ago on Sunday, were seriously damaged in the explosion.
</P>
<P>
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971015.0253 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Vietnam, Iraq to Enhance Cooperation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HANOI, October 15 (Xinhua) -- Vietnam and Iraq have decided to
enhance their cooperation in rice farming and oil production in
anticipation of what is called Iraq's post-embargo period,
following talks between officials from the two countries.
</P>
<P>
According to reports released here today, Iraq will reserve
10,000 ha of arable land for an Iraqi-Vietnamese joint-venture in
rice-growing while reserving an oil field with an estimated
deposit of two billion barrels of crude oil.
</P>
<P>
The venture is a result of talks between the Iraqi Deputy Prime
Minister Mohammed H. Al-Zubaidi, who arrived here monday for a
six-day official visit to Vietnam, and Vietnamese Prime Minister
Phan Van Khai and his Vietnamese counterpart Deputy PM Nguyen Cong
Tan on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Iraq will invest in growing tea and take part in
building an oil refinery in Vietnam. All tea products made by an
Iraqi-Vietnamese joint-venture will be sold in Iraq.
</P>
<P>
The Vietnamese also asked Iraq to consider the possibilities of
Vietnamese labourers traveling to Iraq to work, and establishing
another joint venture in growing cotton in Iraq after the current
embargo is lifted.
</P>
<P>
The Vietnamese people and government were very sympathetic with
the Iraqi people for the current difficulties caused by a
prolonged economic embargo, Deputy Prime Minister Tan told his
guests.
</P>
<P>
He reaffirmed that "Vietnam fully supports the genuine
aspiration of the Iraqi people, calling for an end to the current
embargo against Iraq."
</P>
<P>
Iraq appreciated Vietnam for its support to Iraq, particularly
through the United Nations program of exchanging Iraqi oil for
food and medical supplies.
</P>
<P>
Over the first nine months of this year, Vietnam sold food and
other commodities to Iraq worth more than 58 million
U.S. dollars. Subsequent sales contracts already signed amounted
to another 70 million dollars, Iraqi Trade Minister Mohammed Mehdi
said.
</P>
<P>
He said Iraq would continue buying Vietnam's products through
the U.N.-sponsored program. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
