<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Clinton Says U.S. Seeking Viable Environment Policy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRASILIA, October 14 (Xinhua) -- U.S. President Bill Clinton
said here today that his country is willing to change its
environmental preservation policy.
</P>
<P>
After meeting with his Brasilian counterpart Fernando Henrique
Cardoso, Clinton expressed his willingness during a press
conference to create a viable plan to seek solutions to
environmental problems.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. President defended a wide international accord on
preserving the environment by reducing gases that contribute to
the greenhouse effect.
</P>
<P>
Regarding the establishment of a Free Trade Area of the
Americas (FTAA), Clinton said the economic bloc is important
because it would help usher small Latin American countries toward
democracy, which is a basic requirement to entering the bloc.
</P>
<P>
On trade between the United States and Brazil, Clinton said the
tax barriers the United States imposed on Brazilian imports were
small hurdles that can be solved.
</P>
<P>
Clinton said Brazil could export more goods to the United
States or to the European Union countries.
</P>
<P>
During the press conference, Clinton apologized to Brazil for a
document released by the U.S. embassy before his South American
tour. The document said corruption in Brazil is an endemic part
of its culture. Clinton said this criticism is wrong. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971015.0256 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Military Fight Rebels on Colombo </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
COLOMBO, October 15 (Xinhua) -- A giant explosion shook
Downtown Colombo early this morning and government troops who
rushed to the explosion scene are reportedly fighting with LTTE
rebels who are said to have carried out the bombing.
</P>
<P>
Fighting is still going on between the government troops and
the rebels near a downtown hotel in the Sri Lankan capital, where
a strong car-bomb ripped the business compound at around 7:10 a.m.
local time, sources quoted the military and police as saying.
</P>
<P>
The National Hospital in Colombo said 30 to 40 people were
killed in the incident. The hospital, the biggest medical facility
in the capital, has also admitted 88 injured people, including two
Americans. Ambulances are still moving in more wounded.
</P>
<P>
The Bank of Ceylon and the twin towers of the World Trade
Center, which was declared open by President Chandrika Kumaratunga
three days ago on Sunday, were seriously damaged by the car-bomb
which had been planted in a car park in the Galadari Hotel.
</P>
<P>
Witnesses said the glass walls of the buildings have all fallen
down, making a mess in the area.
</P>
<P>
Tourism Minister Dharmasiri Senanayake was in the hospital
visiting the injured on behalf of the government.
</P>
<P>
Police have tightened up security in the Sri Lankan capital and
additional road blocks have also been put in place.
</P>
<P>
Police said the explosion took place near the Galadari Hotel, a
five-star landmark by the seaside.
</P>
<P>
Troops and police have sealed off the area, allowing only
military vehicles and ambulances to enter, and military
helicopters were hovering over the scene.
</P>
<P>
Local sources close to the military said the explosion was
carried out by the rebels of the Liberation Tigers of Tamil Eelam
(LTTE), which has been fighting a 14-year ethnic war with the
government for a separate state of their own in the north and east
of the country.
</P>
<P>
LTTE has carried out many suicide bombing attacks in the
capital before.
</P>
<P>
A train carrying several hundred Colombo office workers back to
their home towns in the south was blasted by two bombs at a
railway station in suburban Colombo on July 24, killing more than
90 people and injuring 400 others.
</P>
<P>
On January 31,1996, the building of the Central Bank of Sri
Lanka, which is located one block away from the Galadari Hotel,
was hit by a truck-bomb driven by LTTE suicide bombers. The
explosion killed more than 100 people and injured 1,400 others.
</P>
<P>
The country's main oil storage facilities in Colombo was
destroyed by the rebels in October 1995 and 29 people were killed
in that incident.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
