<HEADLINE> Giant Blast Injures 30 in Colombo </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
COLOMBO, October 15 (Xinhua) -- A giant explosion occurred in
the business district of the Sri Lankan capital of Colombo early
this morning, injuring at least 30 people.
</P>
<P>
Sources in the National Hospital said that at least 30 wounded
people have been rushed to the hospital for treatment, but they
added that the total number of casualties was still not available
yet.
</P>
<P>
The National Hospital is the biggest medical facility in the
Sri Lankan capital.
</P>
<P>
Police have tightened up security in the capital and additional
road blocks were also put in place.
</P>
<P>
Thick smoke can be seen above the sky in Colombo 1, the
business district of Colombo.
</P>
<P>
Police said the explosion took place near the Galadari Hotel, a
five-star landmark by the seaside.
</P>
<P>
Troops and police have sealed off the area, allowing only
military vehicles and ambulances to enter.
</P>
<P>
A military helicopter was hovering over the scene.
</P>
<P>
Many people fled the scene and caused great chaos and traffic
jams.
</P>
<P>
Local sources close to the military said the action was carried
out by the LTTE rebels.
</P>
<P>
The Liberation Tigers of Tamil Eelam (LTTE) has been fighting a
14-year ethnic war with the government for a separate state of
their own in the north and east of the country.
</P>
<P>
LTTE has carried out many suicide bombing attacks in the
capital
before.
</P>
<P>
A recent attack took place on July 24, when a train carrying
several hundred Colombo office workers back to their hometowns in
the
south was blasted by two bombs at a railway station in suburban
Colombo, killing more than 90 people and injuring 400 others.
</P>
<P>
On January 31, 1996, the building of the Central Bank of Sri
Lanka,
which is close to the explosion site today, was hit by a
truck-bomb
driven by LTTE suicide bombers. More than 100 people were killed
and
1,400 others injured in the bombing.
</P>
<P>
The country's main oil storage facilities in Colombo were
destroyed by the rebels in October 1995 and 29 people died in that

incident.  
