<HEADLINE> U.S. Secretary of State to Visit Haiti </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, October 14 (Xinhua) -- U.S. Secretary of State
Madeleine Albright will go to Haiti on Friday to seek an end to
the political crisis in the Caribbean country.
</P>
<P>
It will be the first visit by a U.S. secretary of state to
Haiti since June 1995 when Albright's predecessor Warren
Christopher visited the nation.
</P>
<P>
Albright will stop off in Haiti on her way back from a trip to
South America with President Bill Clinton, State Department
spokesman James Rubin announced today.
</P>
<P>
"The secretary's visit is intended to demonstrate our
continuing interest in Haiti and our support for Haiti's efforts
to develop a democratic society and to reconstruct its economy,"
Rubin said.
</P>
<P>
He said Haiti has made considerable progress since a U.S.-led
military force reinstated the elected government in 1994. He
acknowledged, however, that much remains to be done.
</P>
<P>
Since Haitian Ex-Prime Minister Rosny Smarth resigned in June,
there has been no agreement on a replacement.
</P>
<P>
There is rising crime in Port-au-Prince, the capital, along
with severe economic problems, the two most difficult problems
confronting Haitian President Rene Preval. 
</P>
