<HEADLINE> World Bank Finances Zambia's Road Sector Investment Program </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, October 14 (Xinhua) -- The World Bank today
approved a credit of 70 million U.S. dollars to support Zambia's
road sector investment program.
</P>
<P>
The project aims to reform the road sector policy and
institutional framework to enhance capacity, increase the
efficiency of the use of resources and improve planning and
implementation performance.
</P>
<P>
It is also designed to reduce the strain on limited government
revenue as well as create greater opportunities for the private
sector to participate in the design, construction and maintenance
of roads and create 14,000 new jobs by 2002.
</P>
<P>
The project will also establish a pilot program for community
road management in at least three districts to test approaches for
sustainable improvements in maintenance of undesignated roads and
to promote increased usage of non-motorized transport means.
</P>
<P>
The credit will be channeled through the International
Development Association, the World Bank's concessionary lending
wing for developing countries. 
</P>
</TEXT>
