<TEXT>
<P>
SHANGHAI, October 15 (Xinhua) -- Wang Junxia, Olympic champion
in the women's 5,000 meters in Atlanta, said here on Tuesday that
she will take part in the 2000 Olympic Games.
</P>
<P>
Wang, the most glittering star from the Ma's Family of the
legendary coach Ma Junren, was showing up at the courtside of the
track and field competition of the Eighth National Games.
</P>
<P>
On her prospect for the next Olympic Games, the star runner
dubbed as "the Mysterious Oriental Deer" nodded her head in
confirmation. "Sure, the 2000 Sydney Games," the local Xinmin
Evening News quoted her as saying.
</P>
<P>
The 24-year-old runner, also silver medalists in the 10,000m in
Atlanta, was hindered in her training after her Olympic glory,
complaining of a nagging headache.
</P>
<P>
"Now, I have a full recovery from the illness," she said. "I
feel very good in training."
</P>
<P>
The Oriental Deer who broke the 10,000 meters world record four
years ago in Beijing, backed to the track in August after the
Chinese athletes failed to bring home a single medal for the first
time from the World Athletics Championships in Athens.
</P>
<P>
Wang disclosed that she is pondering upon the idea to establish
an athletics school to provide a training base for the young
hopefuls.
</P>
<P>
"Right now, I'm now too busy and I hope to focus my attention
on it after the National Games," she said.
</P>
<P>
Wang, who still holds the 10,000m world record, was expected to
compete in the National Games to repeat the glory as she did four
years ago in Beijing.
</P>
<P>
But she refrained herself from competing in the Games at the
moment, saying she was not ready for such a big Games as she was
still regaining her top form.
</P>
<P>
In the last edition, Wang emerged as the top long-distance
runner in the world by beating the 3,000m world record twice in 24
hours and setting a new world mark in the 10,000m event. 
