<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Ukrainian Parties Prepare For Parliamentary Elections </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KIEV, October 14 (Xinhua) -- With a new parliamentary election
law finally in place, political parties in Ukraine will need to
run national campaigns and also seek campaign funding.
</P>
<P>
Ukrainian candidates for the parliament -- the Supreme Soviet
-- used to campaign strictly as individuals. The new elections law
approved on September 24 this year reserves half the 450 seats in
the next legislation for candidates elected from party
lists. Ukraine's political parties for the first time have to
worry about a war chest, advertising budget and fundraising.
</P>
<P>
Experience offers few clues on what to expect in the coming
parliamentary elections due in March 1998, said Sergy Odarych,
president of the Ukrainian Perspective Foundation. In the 1994
parliamentary elections, some winning candidates spent up to four
million U.S. dollars and others as little as 100 dollars.
</P>
<P>
"This will be the first experience of party elections, which
makes it really difficult to talk about cost," Odarych said.
</P>
<P>
The parties themselves say they have not come up with campaign
budgets yet, and some parties are not going to have an election
budget at all.
</P>
<P>
Georty Ponomarenko, deputy chief of the Communist Party
campaign staff, said he is under no illusion about rich
supporters. "We will rely on party membership dues," he said.
</P>
<P>
He added that the party treasury currently contains merely
10,000 hryvnas (about 5,400 U.S. dollars) and no one knows how
many donations will come in. It is unrealistic to talk about a
full-fledged campaign budget, he said.
</P>
<P>
The Socialists, the second largest faction in the present
parliament behind the Communists, also claim empty coffers. Party
spokesman Viktor Yakovlev acknowledged: "Our members pay us one
percent of their income, but considering that pensions and wages
have not been paid for a long time, we do not get very much."
</P>
<P>
Roman Zwarycz, head of the Rukh National Democratic party's
electoral campaign, said his party is well prepared for the
pending elections. "We started collecting money from sponsors who
are interested in forces supporting businesses in Ukraine," he
said.
</P>
<P>
The Rukh also collects money from ordinary citizens throughout
the country. "Regional headquarters are providing for campaigns in
their regions," Zwaryca added.
</P>
<P>
He said the Rukh plans to communicate its campaign programs to
the public through both print and broadcast advertising. An
initial series of Rukh advertisements have already hit the
country's television screen, and further commercials with
conservative social messages are planned.
</P>
<P>
The Socialists will seek publicity in a different way.
</P>
<P>
"Our party is unable to pay for TV advertising and we cannot
buy full page ads in the newspapers," said Yakovle. "Nevertheless,
our party is well-known in Ukraine and people will vote for it."
</P>
<P>
He said his candidates will go to people's homes to talk to
them so that every candidate will really have to earn his
mandate." This type of work with people proved to be very
successful in the 1994 elections, especially in villages," said
Yakovlev. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
