<HEADLINE> Free Trade Accord Signed Between Hungary and Israel </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BUDAPEST, October 14 (Xinhua) -- Hungary and Israel signed a
free trade agreement here today in a bid to promote economic
development and cooperation.
</P>
<P>
Under the agreement, signed by Hungarian Minister of Industry,
Commerce and Tourism Fazakas Szabolcs and visiting Israeli
Minister of Industry and Trade Natan Sharansky, the two countries
will gradually lift trade tariffs reciprocally by the year 2001.
</P>
<P>
After the treaty takes effect on January 1, 1998, 97 percent of
the products exported from Hungary to Israel will be granted the
status of duty-free. Also Hungary will open more duty-free trading
areas to Israel.
</P>
<P>
Hungary and Israel have seen an increase in bilateral trade
since the two established diplomatic ties in 1989.
</P>
<P>
And Hungary is a major foreign investment recipient from Israel
in Eastern Europe. By the end of 1996, Hungary had introduced an
investment of 370 million U.S. dollars from Israel and another 600
million dollars yet to be gained. 
</P>
</TEXT>
