<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Correspondence Classes Popular with Farmers in Eastern China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HANGZHOU, October 15 (Xinhua) -- A song popular among farmers
in east China's Zhejiang province begins:
</P>
<P>
"No school buildings, no enclosures,
</P>
<P>
The earth serving as classrooms,
</P>
<P>
Crops and poultry as experimental tools,
</P>
<P>
Teachers, students scattered all over the country."
</P>
<P>
These lyrics are part of the school anthem of the China
Farmers' Correspondence Technology University, launched by the
China Association for Science and Technology in 1985. The school
offers courses to farmers in plantation, breeding, processing and
township enterprises.
</P>
<P>
The university has trained thousands upon thousands of farmers
since its founding and has become a major channel for farmers to
learn new agricultural technology.
</P>
<P>
More than 30 majors are offered, and farmers can take year-long
courses by paying only 35 yuan. Annual enrollment has grown from
hundreds to the present 40,000, said Wang Yangjie, an official of
Zhejiang's Association for Science and Technology.
</P>
<P>
In addition to correspondence courses, governments also invite
experts to visit fields or cottages for face-to-face lectures. As
a result, about 80 percent of the learners pass written exams or
field tests, and 40,000 have been promoted to farmer technicians.
</P>
<P>
The province has had 270,000 farmers trained by the university,
and set up 88 correspondence branches, as well as guidance centers
in more than 900 townships.
</P>
<P>
"Without the university, I would have been still in poverty,"
said farmer Huang Defa in Tangkun village of Linhai city. Three
years ago, he grew citrus on one-third hectare and earned 4,000
yuan, which was not enough to pay his debts.
</P>
<P>
But, last year, he made nearly 100,000 yuan (12,000 US dollars)
off the same land. Now his story of getting better off, along with
100 others, has been written in a book to encourage other
farmers.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
