<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Oil Expert Calls for Technological Advancement </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, October 15 (Xinhua) -- Technological advancement will
be the key for the world petroleum industry in dealing with major
challenges in the 21st century, a leading international expert
said here today.
</P>
<P>
"Under the growing pressure of competition between energy
players, we will need more technological advances and
breakthroughs," said Philippe Jaffre, chairman and chief executive
officer of the French oil giant Elf Aquitaine.
</P>
<P>
He made the remarks in a plenary address to the ongoing 15th
World Petroleum Congress (WPS) this morning.
</P>
<P>
Application of new technologies will be used not just to reduce
costs but also to discover and produce new diversified reserves,
Jaffre noted.
</P>
<P>
Noting that although discovery rates have been greatly
improved, companies are still wasting two-thirds of their
exploration budgets in drilling dry holes, Jaffre said this means
that the oil industry still have a large potential for improvement.
</P>
<P>
"We need technology to help us in the field of geology,
geochemistry, seafloor mapping, geophysics, and also for better and
faster seismic interpretation," he said.
</P>
<P>
"We will encourage new enhanced recovery studies, in particular
on old production sites," he said, adding that the industry will
benefit from multilateral drilling techniques, 4-dimension seismic
field monitoring and improved ways for chemical injection.
</P>
<P>
Improvement in technology will also be needed to reach new areas
such as the Arctic zone or additional reserves such as
non-conventional crudes from sands and bituminous shales, he said.
</P>
<P>
Jaffre also underlined the industry's need to strive for
improvements in pipeline networks, in liquefaction processes and
on-site conversion from gas to liquid fuels, especially high quality
middle distillates.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, he held that technological improvement in itself is
not enough for the industry. "Major management responsibilities will
be needed to withstand major changes and pressures," he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
