<HEADLINE> U.S. Calls on Greece, Turkey to reinstate Overflight Ban </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, October 14 (Xinhua) -- The United States on
Tuesday urged Greece and Turkey to resume their ban on military
fights over Cyprus as tension rose between the two
Mediterranean neighbors over the divided island.
</P>
<P>
"We urge all sides appreciate the benefits of reinstituting a
complete, open-ended moratorium on overflights of Cyprus by
Greek and Turkish military aircraft at the earliest possible
time," State Department spokesman James Rubin told reporters.
</P>
<P>
Greek and Greek Cypriot forces have been recently holding
naval exercises, and Turkish and Turkish Cypriot forces also
plan to stage the similar naval exercises soon.
</P>
<P>
Rubin called the two exercises "unfortunate" as they
complicated an overflight ban.
</P>
<P>
"There is a spate of exercises going on, and that is
unfortunate in light of the desire for an overflight ban ... We
think fewer military activities are better than more military
activities," he said.
</P>
<P>
The United States, according to Rubin, would not take sides
but said Washington had backed separate announcements on May 9
by both Greece and Turkey that they would stop military
overflights of Cyprus.
</P>
<P>
Cyrus has been divided into a Greek Cypriot controlled south
and a Turkish Cypriot north since Turkish troops entered the
northern third of the island in 1974. 
</P>
</TEXT>
