<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Duma Should be Prudent With No-confidence Motion </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, October 14 (Xinhua) -- Russia's deputies in the State
Duma, the lower house of parliament, should take a prudent
position in their cabinet debate on a no-confidence motion on
Wednesday, said President Boris Yeltsin.
</P>
<P>
Sergei Yastrzhembsky, press secretary for Yeltsin, warned the
Duma against passing a no-confidence vote, saying "such a decision
will bring no positive result and will not resolve any problems."
</P>
<P>
"The government will not work in a state of suspense,"
Itar-Tass news agency quoted Prime Minister Viktor Chernomyrdin as
saying. "And we will decide everything within the constitution,"
he said.
</P>
<P>
Chernomyrdin said that only by holding "direct talks" can the
conflicts between the cabinet and the legislature be
resolved. Also he made clear today that he would resign if
parliament passes the no-confidence vote.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Boris Nemtsov, First Deputy Prime Minister, pointed
out the possibility of a cabinet crisis incurred by the vote. This
would harm the country's economy severely, he added.
</P>
<P>
Under Russia's 1993 constitution, a no-confidence motion can be
passed if it has the support of a majority of the total number of
deputies in the Duma. Thus the votes of at least 226 of the 450
deputies are required. Nikolai Ryzhkov, First Deputy Speaker of
Duma, said today they had already acquired the 226 votes needed.
</P>
<P>
If the motion is passed, Yeltsin has the choice of dismissing
the government or simply rejecting the no-confidence vote.
</P>
<P>
If the Duma expresses no confidence in the government a second
time within three months, the president must then either dismiss
the government or dissolve the Duma and call for new elections.
</P>
<P>
The State Duma will start the debate on the motion on Wednesday
at noon GMT. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
