<HEADLINE> Massachusetts Public Colleges Urged to Ban Alcohol </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, October 14 (Xinhua) -- After two students died from
overdrunk, Massachusetts' Board of Higher Education today
unanimously voted to urge all 29 state colleges and universities
to ban most alcohol use on campus.
</P>
<P>
The ban would prohibit alcohol on campuses or in dormitories
where any of the residents are under 21. Violators would be
subject to dismissal.
</P>
<P>
But licensed establishments such as on-campus pubs and limited
events at which everyone was 21 or older would be allowed to serve
alcohol.
</P>
<P>
The ban was an enforcement in the crackdown on alcohol abuse
that followed the deaths of two students from the University of
Massachusetts in Amherst and the Massachusetts Institute of
Technology (MIT) respectively.
</P>
<P>
Scott Krueger, an 18-year-old freshman at MIT died last month
of alcohol poisoning after attending a fraternity party. Adam G.
Prentice, a 21-year-old junior at Umass-Amherst, died earlier this
month after falling through the roof of a greenhouse while drunk.
</P>
<P>
Some board members acknowledged that, even though the legal
drinking age is 21, illegal drinking and alcohol abuse are
widespread among undergraduates. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
