seven accords upon cooperation in different sectors.
</P>
<P>
Brazil`S President Fernando Henrique Cardoso and U.S.
President Bill Clinton were present during the signing ceremony at
the Planalto Presidential Palace.
</P>
<P>
The documents signed were on education, public administration
modernization, judicial, technological, environmental and space
cooperation and the peaceful use of nuclear energy.
</P>
<P>
----
</P>
<P>
NEW YORK -- A merger wave has emerged in a wide range of
European companies as the continent is heading towards a single
economy.
</P>
<P>
Several merger and takeover bids announced over the weekend and
on Monday involve amounts of billions of U.S. dollars, a variety
of sectors and companies across the borders, according to reports
reaching here.
</P>
<P>
They include a 30 billion dollar merger plan involving the
insurance business between Britain's B.A.T. Industries and the
Switzerland-based Zurich Group and a 9.4 billion dollar takeover
bid by Italy's Assicurazioni Generali for France's Assurances
Generales.
</P>
<P>
----
</P>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS -- With the conclusion and implementation of a
number of international arms control and disarmament legal
instruments, it was obviously highly necessary to strengthen the
international non-proliferation efforts, Sha Zukang, Chinese
ambassador for disarmament affairs, said here Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Addressing the First Committee of the 52nd session of the
General Assembly, Ambassador Sha Zukang said the indefinite
extension of the Non-Proliferation Treaty, the conclusion of the
Comprehensive Test Ban Treaty, the completion of the negotiations
on the Additional Protocol to Safeguards Agreements, the entry
into force of the Chemical Weapons Convention and the negotiations
to enhance the effectiveness of the Biological Weapons Convention
had enhanced and would further enhance international
non-proliferation.
</P>
<P>
----
</P>
<P>
BONN -- The finance ministers of Germany and France Tuesday
reached an agreement on how future members of the single European
currency (Euro) should informally coordinate their economic
policies after the currency's introduction in January 1999.
</P>
<P>
Under the agreement reached by German Finance Minister Theo
Waigel and his French counterpart Dominique Strauss-Kahn, finance
ministers of those EU states that form the single currency should
meet first in an "informal forum" to coordinate their economic
policies prior to finance ministers meetings of all EU member
states.
</P>
<P>
A proposal to form such a forum would be submitted by Germany
and France at the next EU finance minister meeting due in
November, said the two ministers after their meeting in the
western German city of Muenster.
</P>
<P>
----
</P>
<P>
LONDON -- The United States, the only superpower in the world,
remains the biggest international arms trader in 1996, with its
arms sales increasing from 1995's 14 billion to 17 billion US
dollars, according to an authoritative annual report.
</P>
<P>
The report named "The Military Balance", published Tuesday by
London's International Institute for Strategic Studies (IISS),
said: "The international arms trade grew by eight percent in 1996
in real terms from 36.9 billion to 39.9 billion dollars, following
a 13 percent increase in 1995."
</P>
<P>
The United States, the world's biggest arms exporter, exported
various arms worth 17 billion dollars last year for a 42.6 percent
global arms sales market share. 
</P>
