<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Philippine Government Debts Increase This year </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, October 15 (Xinhua) -- The total debts incurred by the
Philippine national government in the first eight months of this
year reached 1.203 trillion pesos (about 35.3 billion U.S.
dollars), slightly higher than the 1.155 trillion pesos for the
whole 1996.
</P>
<P>
According to a Philippine Central Bank report, which was
published here today, domestic debts accounted for the bulk of the
total borrowing at 727 billion pesos while foreign debts were
placed at 15.73 billion dollars.
</P>
<P>
The report said that as the foreign debts were incurred at an
exchange rate of 30.165 pesos to the dollar, the depreciation of
the peso, now around 34 pesos against the dollar, would cost the
government much more for the repayment.
</P>
<P>
It said the foreign debts were incurred from the issuance of
bonds which were floated in the international market.
</P>
<P>
The rise in government obligations is due to the effect of the
currency turmoil which prevailed during the period under review,
the report said.
</P>
<P>
Under the current fiscal program, the government is allowed to
earmark only 73.9 billion pesos of the total budget for debt
service. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
