<HEADLINE> IDB to Support Central America Countries' Entrace to NAFTA </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SAN JOSE, October 14 (Xinhua) -- The President of the
Inter-American Development Bank Enrique Iglesias said the
bank will support the attempt of Central American
countries to be admitted in the North America Free Trade
Agreement (NAFTA).
</P>
<P>
Iglesias was quoted today by Costa Rica`s daily "La Nacion"
as saying he was optimistic about the possibility that the U.S.
Congress grant President Bill Clinton the fast track authorization
to negotiate the setting up of the Free Trade Area of the Americas
(FTAA).
</P>
<P>
Iglesias, who is currently under medical treatment in a Sao Paulo
hospital in Brazil due to a renal problem, met last week with
journalists from Central America in Washington.
</P>
<P>
The head of the IDB asserted that the entrance of Central America
to NAFTA must be a previous step to the setting up of FTAA,
expected by 2005. NAFTA was enacted since 1994 in United States,
Canada and Mexico.
</P>
<P>
Central America must step on its own integration and insist,
as it did last May during U.S. president visit to San Jose,
on its entrance to the North American bloc, he added.
</P>
<P>
The FTAA was proposed by Clinton to Presidents and heads of
states of 34 hemispheric countries in December 1994. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971015.0295 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Men Show More Responsibility in Family Planning </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, October 15 (Xinhua) -- Family planning, which used to
be thought of as a woman's affair in China, has more men getting
involved, according to experts at an international conference on
population in Beijing.
</P>
<P>
Twenty-two million Chinese men got vasectomies in 1995, or half
the world's total for that year, according to the China State
Family Planning Commission (SFPC).
</P>
<P>
"Although the country's rate of vasectomies is about 10
percent, because the population is so large, China is still in the
lead in the world in using this male sterilization method," said
Professor Liu Yunrong of the SFPC's Science and Technology
Institute.
</P>
<P>
UN statistics show that the world's average prevalence rate of
vasectomies is five percent. The prevalence rate is an index of
popularity of a particular contraception method.
</P>
<P>
The number of condom users in China has been increasing year by
year, and was eight million in 1995 for couples of reproductive
age. China produces one billion condoms annually.
</P>
<P>
The use of this convenient and safe contraception tool should
be increased, experts say.
</P>
<P>
More Chinese couples are asking for information on
childbearing, fertility regulation, and reproductive health, and
are making decisions together, experts say, adding that many
would-be fathers are playing an important role in helping women
through the period of pregnancy.
</P>
<P>
Since 1980, when China began encouraging couples to have only
one child, the government has said that men and women should both
be responsible for family planning. The Constitution says that
husbands and wives should participate in family planning.
</P>
<P>
Demographers say that the active participation of men will
ultimately benefit women and children, and will help to protect
women's rights, and will help avoid risks and health problems
caused by induced abortions.
</P>
<P>
Experts predict that Chinese males will choose condoms more
frequently, especially in coastal and border areas, while the
vasectomy rate will remain stable for quite a long time. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
