<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Prodi Asked to Seek Confidence Vote </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ROME,October 14 (Xinhua)-- Italian President Oscar Luigi
Scalfaro today asked Premier Romano Prodi to go before parliament
for a confidence vote after Prodi government reached an agreement
with ally Communist Refoundation ending a week-long crisis.
</P>
<P>
President Scalfaro rejected Prodi's resignation, tendered
Thursday after the Communist Refoundation refused to support the
1998 budget draft, and told him to go before Parliament "as soon
as possible".
</P>
<P>
Prodi said he did not know if there will be a formal confidence
vote to officially register the return of his majority.
</P>
<P>
Prodi resigned before a formal vote could be called showing the
government had lost its majority, therefore, a confidence vote may
be replaced by a less-divisive motion backing Italy's effort to
join the single currency, political observers said.
</P>
<P>
The speakers of the Lower House and Senate would have to decide
"the procedures to follow," Prodi said.
</P>
<P>
Prodi met with Senate Speaker Nicola Mancino and Lower House
Speaker Luciano Violante separately this afternoon.
</P>
<P>
Scalfaro sent the government back to Parliament after Prodi and
Bertinotti, in a meeting today at Palazzo Chigi, finalized an
agreement on the 1998 budget draft that restored the government's
majority.
</P>
<P>
The draft budget aims to cut pension and welfare spending to
help Italy maintain the financial discipline required to join the
single European currency to be launched on January 1999. 
</P>
</TEXT>
