<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Philippines' Balance of Payments Yields Surplus </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, October 15 (Xinhua) -- The Philippines' balance of
payments (BOP) position yielded a surplus of 3.164 billion U.S.
dollars in the first semester of the year.
</P>
<P>
The BOP surplus was registered with the narrowing of the
country's current account deficit, local newspaper Manila Bulletin
today quoted Central Bank Governor Gabriel Singson as saying.
</P>
<P>
Current account deficit for the first six months of the year
shrunk by 22 percent to 2.1 billion dollars from 2.7 billion
dollars in the same period of last year.
</P>
<P>
The improvement, similarly, caused the current account deficit
as a percentage of gross national product to drop to 4.5 percent
from 6.6 percent in 1996.
</P>
<P>
This means that the country's export performance is slowly
inching up although not enough to outpace the demand for imported
products, Singson said.
</P>
<P>
He said the improvement in the current account position was
driven by a 6.2-percent increase in the net earnings from trade in
services.
</P>
<P>
A smaller merchandise trade deficit, too, contributed to the
current account improvement.
</P>
<P>
Singson also said the current account deficit could have
narrowed further if there had not been the negative effects of a
weak currency, which was the overall sentiment in the region.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
