<HEADLINE> Stockton to Be Sidelined For the Start of NBA Season </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW YORK, October 14 (Xinhua) -- Utah Jazz's star guard John
Stockton, who had knee surgery on Monday night, will be bystander
for the first six to eight weeks of the regular season.
</P>
<P>
The 35-year-old guard, known for assists and steals, had
arthroscopic surgery on his left knee to remove loose
cartilage. The team's orthopedic surgeon Lyle Mason said the
injury did not heal easily.
</P>
<P>
Stockton has only missed four games during his entire NBA
career. He has played in all 127 playoff games in Jazz history and
led the team to the NBA finals for the first time.
</P>
<P>
Stockton is the third big-name player who will miss the start
of the season with a major injury. Miami's Alonzo Mourning with
knee surgery will be out eight to 12 weeks and Chicago's Scottie
Pippen with foot surgery will be out two to three months. 
</P>
</TEXT>
