<HEADLINE> China Urges Strengthening of International </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, October 14 (Xinhua) -- With the conclusion and
implementation of a number of international arms control and
disarmament legal instruments, it was obviously highly necessary
to strengthen the international non-proliferation efforts, Sha
Zukang, Chinese ambassador for disarmament affairs, said here
today.
</P>
<P>
Addressing the First Committee of the 52nd session of the
General Assembly, Ambassador Sha Zukang said the indefinite
extension of the Non-Proliferation Treaty, the conclusion of the
Comprehensive Test Ban Treaty, the completion of the negotiations
on the Additional Protocol to Safeguards Agreements, the entry
into force of the Chemical Weapons Convention and the negotiations
to enhance the effectiveness of the Biological Weapons Convention
had enhanced and would further enhance international
non-proliferation.
</P>
<P>
Sha said it was easy to see that all the above
non-proliferation regimes established on the basis of relatively
broad participation while taking into account the need of peaceful
uses as much as possible. They would therefore be relatively
effective and have vitality.
</P>
<P>
Sha said that at the same time, a small number of developed
countries, with the purpose of deterring their opponents, set up a
series of so-called non-proliferation mechanisms and arrangements
during the Cold War period. Although these mechanisms and
arrangements might have played a certain role in
non-proliferation, they were discriminatory and exclusive in
nature and non-transparent in practice.
</P>
<P>
The ambassador said that as the above-mentioned international
legal instruments were already or about to be in place,
maintaining or even enhancing these discriminatory and exclusive
mechanisms and arrangements clashed with the relevant
international legal instruments. What was even worse, they would
continue to impede the social and economic development of all
countries, the developing countries in particular.
</P>
<P>
Sha said what was most serious was that some countries, under
the pretext of preventing proliferation, interfered in and blocked
the legitimate and normal economic and technological exchanges of
the countries, particularly the developing countries. They had
adopted double standards.
</P>
<P>
Sha said that China had determined its position and policy on
international affairs on the merits of each case by proceeding
from the fundamental interests of the people of China and of the
world as a whole. China would never yield to any outside pressure
or enter into alliance with any big power or group of countries;
nor would it establish any military bloc, participate in the arms
races or seek military expansion. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
