<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Merger Wave Emerges in Europe </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW YORK, October 14 (Xinhua) -- A merger wave has been emerged
in a wide rage of European companies as the continent is heading
towards a single economy.
</P>
<P>
Several merger and takeover bids announced over the weekend and
on Monday involve amounts of billions of U.S. dollars, a variety
of sectors and companies across the borders, according to reports
reaching here.
</P>
<P>
They include a 30 billion dollar merger plan involving the
insurance business between Britain's B.A.T. Industries and the
Switzerland-based Zurich Group and a 9.4 billion dollar takeover
bid by Italy's Assicurazioni Generali for France's Assurances
Generales.
</P>
<P>
Other merger and takeover bids unvealed involve the industries
of beverage, publishing, cement and banks in Holland, Finland and
Sweden.
</P>
<P>
Analysts attribute the merger wave to reasons such as
ever-fiercer global competition, the imminency of Europe's planned
launch of a common currency, and booming stock prices that make
it attractive to offer shares as payment for takeovers.
</P>
<P>
Low interest rates in Europe are also a factor which is pushing
companies to make more productive use of their cash.
</P>
<P>
U.S. banks in Europe are believed to have their influence
behind such a merger trend but analysts say Europe's merger move
may reshape parts of its business landscape and raise the
competitive threat for U.S. companies in global markets. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
