<HEADLINE> IMF Chief Endorses Thailand's Efforts for Financing </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, October 14 (Xinhua) -- Michel Camdessus, managing
director of the International Monetary Fund (IMF), today issued a
statement endorsing Thailand's efforts for restructuring its
financial sector.
</P>
<P>
Camdessus noted the Thai government has made a significant
announcement today about its detailed strategy to restructure its
troubled financial sector. The announcement contains the key
elements of the restructuring process for 58 suspended finance
companies as well as measures to beef up the remaining
institutions.
</P>
<P>
"In particular, the institutional framework for the
restructuring or liquidation of the suspended finance companies
has been clarified, and two new institutions are being created to
implement and oversee this process," Camdessus said. "I
particularly welcome the announcement that the strongest possible
criteria will be adopted and that only the very strongest finance
companies will be allowed to reopen."
</P>
<P>
Although the some Asian countries along with the IMF put
forward an assistance package of some 16 billion U.S. dollars in
August to help Thailand solve its financial crisis, the IMF chief
said it would go a long way toward resolving remaining market
uncertainties about the implementation of financial sector
restructuring and other elements of the economic program.
</P>
<P>
Camdessus also reaffirmed that the IMF, together with the World
Bank and other agencies, would continue to work closely with the
Thai government to help implement the financial restructuring
strategy. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
