<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> US Leads in Inventory Management: Report </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW YORK, October 14 (Xinhua) -- The United States continues to
top Japan and Europe in inventory management in the electronics
industry, an annual study showed.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. levels of inventory as a percentage of revenue are
significantly lower than the Japanese and European levels, with
the U.S. standing at 12 percent, Japan 24 percent and Europe 19
percent, the Massachusetts-based PRTM company reported today.
</P>
<P>
Inventory management is a strong measure of a company's
operational health and it is a major cost of doing business,
analysts said.
</P>
<P>
The items used in the just-released study include inventory
turns, asset turnover, inventory as a percentage of revenue,
growth rate, gross margins and cash-to-cash cycle time.
</P>
<P>
On every indicator except asset turnover, the U.S. led in
performance, the study said.
</P>
<P>
PRTM is a globally-oriented management consultancy focusing on
core processes at high-tech companies. The study, now in its 19th
year, received responses from 354 companies in the U.S., Japan and
Europe. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
