<HEADLINE> GCC Classifies Goods for Unified Tariffs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUWAIT CITY, October 14 (Xinhua) -- The Gulf Cooperation
Council (GCC) finished classifying commodities today, thus
clearing an obstacle on the way to unifying tariffs among its
member nations, Kuwaiti News Agency reported.
</P>
<P>
GCC's Customs Committee started a meeting earlier today in
Saudi capital Riyadh to work out the classification of the
remaining 36 commodities out of a total of 1,276.
</P>
<P>
All the commodities are now divided into three categories -
goods exempted from tariffs, basic goods to be levied for a tariff
ranging from 4 to 12 percent and other goods without a set tariff
limit.
</P>
<P>
Up to 1,240 commodities had been categorized in accordance with
an internationally accepted classification list in previous
meetings of the committee.
</P>
<P>
Abdallah Al-Khlaifi, GCC's assistant secretary general for
economic affairs, said Monday that the common customs duties of
the GCC members would range between zero and 12 percent on basic
and non-essential goods, which at present vary from 4 to 25
percent.
</P>
<P>
If successful, the unification of tariffs among GCC member
nations would prove to be a major step toward the proposed
formation of an Arab common market in the future.
</P>
<P>
GCC, a political and economic organization founded in 1981,
consists of six Arab countries of Saudi Arabia, Kuwait, the United
Arab Emirates, Oman, Qatar and Bahrain. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
