<HEADLINE> Hypertension Treating Norvasc Sees Record Sales </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW YORK, October 14 (Xinhua) -- Norvasc has become the largest
selling cardiovascular medicine in the world, Pfizer Inc. of the
United States, which makes the medicine, said today.
</P>
<P>
Sales of Norvasc for the first three quarters of 1997 amounted
to 1.59 billion U.S. dollars, an increase of 25 percent over the
same period in 1996, Pfizer announced in its quarterly report.
</P>
<P>
The revenue includes 705 million dollars for the U.S. market
and 888 million dollars for markets abroad.
</P>
<P>
"Norvasc continues to benefit from a growing body of scientific
evidence supporting its efficacy and unique safety profile," the
company said.
</P>
<P>
Sales of Norvasc, which treats hypertension and angina, are
23.9 percent of the company's pharmaceutical group revenues
totaling 6.66 billion dollars for the first nine months of this
year.
</P>
<P>
Pfizer, a research-based health care company with global
operations, has been listed as "the world's most admired
pharmaceutical/health care company" by the Fortune magazine in its
latest issue.
</P>
<P>
Pfizer's total revenues for the first three quarters of 1997
stood at 9 billion dollars and net income 1.65 billion dollars.
</P>
<P>
They represent growths of 11 percent and 16 percent
respectively over the same period in 1996. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
